<SECOND>AM-Weapons Imports,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post: NRA Blocks Gun Halt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A complaint by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> stopped the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firearms </ORGANIZATION> from banning the importation of 25 more models of semiautomatic weapons Thursday, a newspaper reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, in its Friday editions, said the bureau was ordered to hold off by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials after the <ORGANIZATION> NRA </ORGANIZATION> raised objections. The newspaper said senior <ORGANIZATION> BATF </ORGANIZATION> officials decided at a meeting Thursday morning to announce the restrictions on the additional models later in the day, according to an official familiar with the events. But then they were instructed by the parent <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> not to proceed, according to the official. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, a senior <ORGANIZATION> NRA </ORGANIZATION> official, said the group learned on Wednesday night that other weapons might be added to the list of five types of assault weapons which drug czar <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> temporarily banned on Tuesday and contacted <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> officials who said there would not be any new restrictions, the newspaper said. The ban announced by <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> included the Chinese-made AK47 and the Israeli <PERSON> Uzi </PERSON>, and covered about 80 percent of total imports of semiautomatic weapons. <ORGANIZATION> ATF </ORGANIZATION> then sought to close the door on the semiautomatic weapons not covered by the initial ban, fearing that these firearms would fill the void, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> BATF </ORGANIZATION> officials worried that manufacturers affected by the import ban would complain they were unfairly singled out.
</TEXT>
