<FIRST>r i PM-China-Suicide     03-16 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Suicide,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suicide Kills 140,000 Chinese A Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 140,000 Chinese take their own lives every year _ most of them women _ and suicide has become a particularly serious problem among rural women, a Chinese sociologist says. <PERSON> Shan </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangnai </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> said suicide is the leading cause of abnormal deaths in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and 70 percent of all victims are female, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported today. `` It used to be a taboo in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to study suicide. Yet in recent years we are increasingly haunted by the rising problem,'' the paper quoted her as saying. A survey of 10 million people taken by the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preventive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> found the suicide rate for urban women to be 10.2 per 100,000, and for urban men 7.23 per 100,000. In rural areas, the suicide rate was 23.34 for women and 18.6 for men. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the suicide rate is about 12 per 100,000. <PERSON> Shan </PERSON> said half the suicides among women are caused by family disputes and marital problems. He noted factors such as the breakup of the traditional extended family and lengthy separations as rural people stream into cities looking for work. Rural women are still treated as dependents and men dominate in the family, <PERSON> Shan </PERSON> said, adding that the psychological and emotional needs of women are largely ignored. He said women also appear to have more difficulty adapting to rapid changes in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s social values and moral standards brought about by industrialization and improving living standards. Rural women who migrate to the cities looking for work often find `` the sharp contrast is too much for them,'' <PERSON> Shan </PERSON> said. Those who return to their villages have difficulty adjusting again to rural poverty. Tens of thousands of Chinese committed suicide as a result of persecution during the ultra-leftist 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. The more recent phenomenon of suicide, linked to changing social conditions, has only recently begun to be a subject for study. In January 1988 the southern city of <LOCATION> Canton </LOCATION> opened the nation's first suicide prevention and treatment center In the first year it received about 140 phone calls, 600 letters and dozens of visitors asking for help, the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> also opened a suicide prevention center last September.
</TEXT>
