<FIRST>r i PM-RoyalOpera     03-16 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Royal Opera,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expensive Night At The Opera</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The price of the best seats at the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, Covent Garden, will rise to about $ 170 each when <PERSON> Luciano </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Placido </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Domingo </ORGANIZATION> sing there next season, general director <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaacs </PERSON> says. `` We either charge these prices or we go out of business,'' <PERSON> Isaacs </PERSON> told a news conference Wednesday. He said performance standards at one of the world's leading opera houses need to be improved at a time of falling government subisidy. Next year's subsidy is $ 23.6 million _ 40 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION>'s income and down from 60 percent five years ago. <PERSON> Isaacs </PERSON> hopes that Spanish-born tenor <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> will return in January to repeat his title role in <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON>'s `` Otello,'' and that Italian tenor <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> will star in <PERSON> Gaetano </PERSON> <PERSON> Donizetti </PERSON>'s `` L'elisir d'amore'' in February `` We expect no falling off at the box office,'' <PERSON> Isaacs </PERSON> said. The director also announced an 11 percent overall rise on seats for other than special performances. The best seats will be $ 140. Seats at the very top of the house, where only a corner of the stage can be seen, remain at $ 4.
</TEXT>
