<FIRST>r i PM-BerlinDeathPenalty     03-16 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Berlin Death Penalty,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allies Abolish 44-Year-Old Death Penalty In West Berlin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The three Allied military powers in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> have abolished a law allowing them to pronounce the death penalty, erasing a controversial regulation adopted 44 years ago, officials say. No one has ever been executed under the now-defunct law, said a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> military spokesman who requested anonymity. But the continued existence of the regulation has irritated many West Berliners. `` The Allies are conscious of many Berliners' objections'' to the law, said a statement issued by French military authorities on Wednesday. `` Beginning today ... no person can be sentenced to death because of violations against the Allies.'' <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> officially control <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> under post-war treaties which left the Soviets in charge of communist <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. The French military spokesman said the three Allies were abolishing the death penalty in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> to `` bring their regulations into accordance with German law.'' <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has no death penalty. The spokesman said the law was aimed at preventing attacks against Allied soldiers and officials in the years immediately after <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s 1945 defeat.
</TEXT>
