<FIRST>r a PM-PigeonBurial     03-16 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pigeon Burial,0556</SECOND>
<UNK>City Halts Mass Pigeon Burials</UNK>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The practice of disposing of pigeons by burying them alive was suspended after an official of the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> contacted the mayor's office. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON>, of the society's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> headquarters, said he offered to travel to <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> and provide a `` blueprint'' for urban pigeon control that would include alternatives to burying the birds alive in the county landfill. <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON> said Tuesday that the society might challenge the practice of burying live birds. `` I would say certainly it violates the spirit, if not the letter, of the anti-cruelty law'' protecting animals in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON> said he knew of no other place in the nation where pigeons were buried alive. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadidian </PERSON>, an urban wildlife biologist with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, also said he'd never heard of such a practice elsewhere. <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Scotty </PERSON> <PERSON> Baesler </PERSON>, who was in a meeting Wednesday afternoon, issued a statement that the burials were suspended. He said he was unaware of the practice until it was reported Wednesday in the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> Herald-Leader. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, of the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> Humane society, said he was not aware the birds were being buried alive. `` Of course, we see problems with that,'' he said. The city had a year-round trapping program and caught about 125 birds a week, said <PERSON> Gayle </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, an aide in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>. He said the pigeons congregate on public buildings and leave smelly droppings. They were removed by city sanitation workers, tied in burlap bags and taken to the landfill, where the bags were buried. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the method combined `` reasonable humaneness and convenience.'' The method was inexpensive, but that was not the deciding factor, he said. <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON> said there is no evidence that killing pigeons eliminates the problem in the long run. Instead, the <ORGANIZATION> Humane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> advocates taking measures to limit roosting spots, `` pigeon-proofing'' buildings by placing sharp spikes on roosting areas, frightening the birds with noisemakers and passing laws to limit the food supply from citizens, restaurants and other sources. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said it was expensive to pigeon-proof buildings and that pigeons were smart birds that soon learned to ignore noisemakers and predator decoys. The only solution is to kill the birds, he said Tuesday. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said that despite the apparent success of a pigeon shoot Sunday in downtown <LOCATION> Somerset </LOCATION> in southeast <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>'s pigeon problem was not bad enough to warrant blocking off downtown and shooting the birds `` I think the problem would have to be much more serious before we'd close the downtown and let -LRB- hunters -RRB- cut loose on them,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> <PERSON> Estes </PERSON>, community development director in <LOCATION> Somerset </LOCATION>, said 500 to 600 birds, about half the pigeon population there, were killed in Sunday's shoot, and he expected half that many to be killed in a shoot scheduled Saturday. <PERSON> Hodge </PERSON> said he had been trying Wednesday to contact <LOCATION> Somerset </LOCATION> officials to offer them a similar plan for pigeon control but had been unsuccessful. <PERSON> Estes </PERSON>, who said he planned no further shoots after Saturday because of `` the media aggravating you to death,'' said he considered the method more humane than live burial. `` I'm not out here choking ours to death,'' he said.
</TEXT>
