<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Security,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Watkins Seeks Tighter Air Security Over Defense Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Energy Department is urging aviation authorities to restrict flights over its military nuclear reactors to make them more secure against potential terrorist attack. `` We've got a lot to do in that area,'' Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee Wednesday. `` It's going to be some time before we get this completely closed.'' The issue was raised by Sen. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., during a hearing in which <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> pledged to give top priority to modernizing and cleaning up the department's nuclear weapons complex, which includes 16 major facilities in 12 states <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> said he was stunned to read a recent report that there are no effective restrictions on airplane flights over the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plant near <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, whose reactors are the nation's only source of a gas used in nuclear warheads. Those reactors currently are not operating because of safety problems. `` If there is one place where we have fallen down on what is A, B, C in security, it is in this area,'' <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> also includes an Energy Department research laboratory, a plant that makes naval reactor fuel material, two chemical separation plants and a facility that produces weapon-grade plutonium. The only nuclear weapons plant that now has prohibited airspace is the Pantex plant near <LOCATION> Amarillo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which is the final weapons assembly point. The Charlotte Observer reported in last Sunday's editions that classified security reports obtained by the newspaper in a Freedom of Information Act request showed <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> officials had repeatedly urged the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to ban low-altitude flights over the 300-square-mile facility. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had failed to justify the need for the restrictions, which the aviation agency views as excessive. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said he was personally involved in trying to establish the air restrictions, not only at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> but also at other sensitive weapons plants. `` We've got to take a look all around,'' he said, to find ways of better protecting the weapons complex from possible air attacks by terrorists or damage from a crash. `` I believe with the new secretary of transportation and with my personal friend coming into the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>, I do n't see any problem getting it reestablished,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said. Although he was not more specific, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, a retired admiral, apparently was referring to recent reports that Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> IV, commander of naval forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> since March 1987, would be named <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> administrator. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration had not yet nominated anyone for the job. The Observer report said that last September, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> dropped its 1983 request to prohibit flights below 14,000 feet for <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and eight other weapons sites. The agency settled for a 2,000-foot minimum limit at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. That restriction, however, is voluntary and not enforceable, the report said.
