<HEAD>Baker Plays Down Suggestion that Israel and PLO Talk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Amid Israeli complaints, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> is playing down his suggestion that direct talks between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> may be needed if alternate peace efforts fail. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations Wednesday that an Israeli-PLO dialogue was difficult to foresee but should not `` categorically'' be ruled out. This represented a shift in tone from Tuesday when he told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee that if talks between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and non-PLO Palestinians do not prosper, `` I suppose we would then have to see negotiations between Israelis and representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s remark triggered a telephone call from <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Arens </PERSON>, who told the secretary that the statement was `` damaging'' to the prospects for a dialogue between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and non-PLO Palestinians. <PERSON> Arens </PERSON>, here for official talks, disclosed the phone call to Israeli reporters. At Wednesday's hearing, Sen. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., said <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>'s statement was an `` open invitation'' for the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> to engage in terrorist activities against Palestinians who choose to bargain with <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> replied that he only meant to say in his earlier remarks that an Israeli-PLO dialogue should not be `` categorically, absolutely, totally and completely'' ruled out `` under any and all circumstances,'' because it might help the peace process. The comment did not repudiate what he had said Tuesday but there was a clear change in emphasis. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has steadfastly refused to talk to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and says the dialogue the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> opened with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> last December has strengthened the group's hand. <PERSON> Arens </PERSON> accused the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday of committing the `` worst atrocities we've ever seen since World War II.'' In his remarks Wednesday, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> seemed to hold out little hope that an international conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, advocated by many <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states, could make a significant contribution to peace. What is needed instead, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said, are `` mutually reciprocal and reinforcing steps'' by both <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> to build confidence. `` Both sides have to take steps,'' he said. The mood at the hearing was generally friendly but there were some hints that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may encounter some resistance, especially on Central American policy. Subcommittee Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., said the only aid package he could support for the Nicaraguan Contra rebels would be one leading to their resettlement in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> or elsewhere from the base camps where they now are housed in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said he believes the Contras should remain intact at least until national elections are held in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> next February. He implied that the rebels could then be reintegrated into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> if the elections are fair. The administration is expected to seek a humanitarian aid package for the Contras in the $ 40 million to $ 50 million range in the next few days. On <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said that if the rightist ARENA party wins presidential elections there on Sunday, future <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to that country should carry strict conditions because of the ties he said ARENA has with death squad activities. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> replied that it would be a mistake to exaggerate the size of the death squad problem, contending that politically motivated murders averaged 800 per month in 1981 and 1982 compared with 280 per year at present. He added, however, that the administration is aware of continuing human rights problems in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, recalling that Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> raised that issue with Salvadoran officials during a visit there six weeks ago.
