<HEAD>House Committee Approves Uniform Poll Closing Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sponsor of legislation that would establish a uniform closing time for polls in 48 of the 50 states says he expects full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approval of the bill as early as next month. On Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved the measure on a voice vote. Rep. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>, sponsor of the bill, said he expects the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to approve the measure in early April, but <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has indicated passage could come before the Easter recess which begins March 24. Election officials in the West have charged that the early projection of the winner in the presidential race discourages people from voting in their states and the drop in turnout had affected the outcomes of close local races. Swift, D-Wash., has said previously that studies have shown voter turnout can drop by as much as 2 percent in states where the polls are still open but the winner in a presidential contest is known `` With passage of this legislation we will be one step closer to preserving the integrity of election day not only in the West, but across the country,'' said <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>. <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>'s bill was similar to ones approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> twice before, but both times the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> failed to act. A different version of a uniform poll closing bill is before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Under <PERSON> Swift </PERSON>'s bill, polls would close simultaneously across the country at 9 p.m. EST on election day. In the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> time zone, daylight-saving time would be extended for a maximum of two weeks in presidential election years. The extension would allow polls in that time zone to close at 7 p.m. PDT. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> are exempt from the legislation, but could change their poll closing times if desired. <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said the need for a uniform closing time became apparent with the 1980 election when television networks projected the results based on exit polling hours before the polls on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> closed. The networks have since agreed not to project election results in a state where the polls have n't closed, but in 1988 the problem was different as President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> rolled up a large electoral college majority before Western polls closed. <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> said his uniform poll closing bill `` will ensure that voters in all regions of the country will be able to cast their ballots without being told who won the election. `` The networks held to their part of the bargain last November, now it is up to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to send this legislation to the president.'' While a version of a poll closing bill cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commitee </ORGANIZATION> late last year, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourned before the the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> had an opportunity to act. Sen. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., has introduced legislation that avoids a change in daylight-saving time and simply calls for the polls to close at 7 p.m. Pacific time, 8 p.m. Mountain time, 9 p.m. Central time and 10 p.m. Eastern time <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, an <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> spokeswoman, said the chairman of the rules committee, Sen. <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Ky., has indicated he expects <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' bill to clear the panel in early April
</TEXT>
