<HEAD>Cartoonist, Guest of Administration, Tweaks New Department, Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As his only non-family, non-official guest on becoming secretary of veterans affairs, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> chose World War II cartoonist <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON>, who says the new department `` sounds like the same old bureaucracy under a different name.'' <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON>, winner of the Pulitzer Prize, created the bedraggled dogfaces <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> for the soldier's newspaper `` Stars and Stripes.'' `` <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> told the truth of the war, World War II, and the fatigue, sadness, anxiety and humor of the period,'' <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> said in his remarks on the White House South Lawn, with <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON> close to him on the podium. <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON>, 67, was a constituent when <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> represented the South Side of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> during 12 terms in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. During an interview before Wednesday's ceremony, <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON> said he knew <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> only slightly, and did not know whose idea it was to make him a prominent part of the day's events. <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON> carries a few more pounds and gray hairs than he did in slogging his way up the <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> in 1943-1944, where he collected a minor shoulder wound from a German mortar round that inspired one of his best panels _ Soldier, standing, to medic, seated at a table with boxes of medals before him: `` Just gim me the aspirin. I already got a purple heart.'' He told two reporters, one from Stars and Stripes, `` I ca n't help thinking <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> knows my attitude'' as an opponent of the large, main-line veterans groups and of what he saw as their grasping attitude. `` We were against the special philosophy, if you're a veteran you're a special case,'' he said. `` Just by virtue of being a veteran, I do n't think that entitles a guy to a gravy-train ride for the rest of his life.'' <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON> belonged to the tiny <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, serving two terms as chairman, and has not used any veterans benefits. `` We backed the GI bill, but our slogan was, ` Citizens First, Veterans Second,''' he said. `` I have n't paid dues for years, but they still send me mail. `` There are millions of guys for whom the military experience was the one great experience of their lives. I do n't blame them for wanting to sit around on a Saturday night with their friends and tell lies about their experience.'' <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON> said he had not paid close attention to veterans affairs recently, so his opinions had to be tentative. _ Agent Orange: Veterans are being forced to try to prove illnesses are connected to exposure to that defoliant, but `` the burden of proof ought to be on the government Those kids ought to have it made up to them. I'm very much in favor of a liberal hand'' in compensation. _ A <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> department replacing the old Veterans Administration: `` It sounds like the same bureaucracy under a different name ... maybe it will be entirely different.'' He was not at all tentative on universal service. `` I think it's great, the idea of putting two or three years of a young man's -LRB- or woman's -RRB- life into public service,'' he said. `` If you're not inclined to the military, then CCC-type work.'' The CCC was the <ORGANIZATION> Civilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>, a depression-era agency tha provided jobs, clothes and food for young men in camps working on conservation projects. `` I think everyone owes his country a few years out of his life, just a short period, two years, maybe three.'' The point of this, he said, is to `` make better citizens out of them.. bond them to their country. Though many proponents of universal service have said the ending of the draft in 1973 ended valuable lessons in democracy through the military's mixing of classes, races and viewpoints, <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON> said he thought `` the sociology is obviously a side benefit.'' <PERSON> Mauldin </PERSON> himself enlisted in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> in 1940, more than a year before the entry of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> into World War II, because, `` I had some friends in the unit I wanted to be with. ... I wanted to get into something, not out of something.'' Which started his cartoonist juices flowing: `` I do n't want to pick on <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Boy </PERSON>,'' he said with a grin, recalling cartoons of last fall's campaign lambasting the Vietam-era plunge into the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> of Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>.
