<HEAD>Troubled Church Reopens Without Incident; Priest Suspended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Roman Catholic church where parishioners rebelled over the removal of a Polish priest has reopened, but church authorities revealed that the priest has been suspended by his superiors. Police have guarded St. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> the Archangel church since it was closed Feb. 18 by <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> after a weeklong sit-in by about 200 dissidents upset over the sudden, unexplained ouster of the Rev. Roman Palaszewski. There were relatively few worshipers Wednesday at four early morning Masses, two celebrated in English and two in Polish, said the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Smyka </PERSON>, associate pastor. `` It was very, very emotional,'' <PERSON> Smyka </PERSON> said. `` The 6:30 Mass _ I think I cried through half of it. It was just so good to be back in the church. I mean, that's what our business is as priests.'' Some parishioners said they were overjoyed by the church's reopening Some said they heard about it by word-of-mouth, or by making daily drives by the church since the announcement that it would reopen. Monsignor <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Grieco </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Egan </PERSON>, said Wednesday that <PERSON> Palaszewski </PERSON> was suspended indefinitely for defying orders from his Franciscan superiors in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, to return to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> last month. `` He's still ordained, but he can not function as a priest because he did n't obey his superior who commanded him, under obedience, to return to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Grieco </PERSON> said `` He would not be able to say Mass or administer the sacraments.'' <PERSON> Palaszewski </PERSON>, who spent three years at the church under an agreement between his superiors in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and Franciscan officials in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, has been in seclusion in the <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> area since his removal in December. About 50 worshipers attended a Lenten prayer service Wednesday evening. They entered the church under the watchful eye of a police officer sitting in a van parked discreetly across the street. Four or five dissidents watched quietly from across the street Wednesday evening as worshipers entered the church. They then gathered at a Polish club a block from the church to plan a demonstration outside the church this weekend on Palm Sunday, the start of the holiest week in the church year. `` They did n't heal our wounds _ everything is the same,'' said <PERSON> Genevieve </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozlowski </PERSON>, a parishioner for 25 years and one of the protest leaders. She was unaware of Wednesday's opening, but said she and many other protesters plan to boycott services because they do n't believe their complaints have been addressed, <PERSON> Kozlowski </PERSON> said. The dissidents are demanding <PERSON> Palaszewski </PERSON>'s return to the parish and the removal of the church's pastor, the Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bambol </PERSON>, who they claim engineered <PERSON> Palaszewski </PERSON>'s removal because of his popularity among recent immigrants. They also question <PERSON> Bambol </PERSON>'s commitment to maintaining the church's <LOCATION> Polis </LOCATION> traditions. <PERSON> Bambol </PERSON>'s supporters have said <PERSON> Palaszewski </PERSON> paid scant attention to parishioners who were not recent immigrants. A weeklong sit-in by about 200 dissidents who occupied the church in shifts ended early Feb. 18 when church authorities summoned police to expel them. Two who refused to leave voluntarily were charged with trespassing. <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> suspended Masses indefinitely the same day. <PERSON> Bambol </PERSON> said after the prayer service that the dissidents are welcome to return as long as they `` abide by the rules of the church.'' He said he was `` very joyful, very happy'' that the church had reopened. `` After all we were all suffering for so long unjustifiably ... we are happy to be back in harness, so to speak,'' he said. `` This is a period of reconciliation.''
