<HEAD>200,000 Expected To Watch Discovery Land On Mojave Desert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 200,000 spectators will converge on this <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> military base to watch Discovery land early Saturday, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> predicted. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON> said Wednesday that the crowd would be that big `` because it's a weekend landing at the beginning of spring vacation.'' The space shuttle and its five-man crew is scheduled to touch down at 6:34 a.m., capping a five-day mission highlighted by deployment of a $ 100 million communications satellite and experiments aimed at developing new medicines and learning how bones heal and chicken embryos develop in the weightlessness of space. Trouble with a valve on board Discovery had threatened to end the mission a day early, but it was apparently fixed Wednesday and <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> is aiming for a Saturday landing. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials said Wednesday that because of a desire to perform handling and braking tests, Discovery might land on concrete Runway 22 instead of on its normal landing strip, Runway 17, which is on the unpaved, clay surface of <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION>. Runway 17 is roughly three miles from the public viewing site on the lakebed's east shore. Runway 22 is about 4.5 miles, but `` it's still a good view You'll see ` em fly right past,'' <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, five airmen playing the role of injured astronauts were rescued Wednesday from a make-believe space shuttle fire in an emergency drill by ground crews who will greet Discovery when it returns Saturday. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> routinely holds such simulations before real shuttle landings. The east shore viewing site will be open to the public 24 hours before the landing, and vehicle passes are not required. But gates to the main parts of <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> will be closed to anyone not on official business. Access to the viewing site will be closed one hour before the landing, <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON> said the two largest crowds for shuttle landings numbered 500,000, when <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> landed here on July 4, 1982; and 410,000 on Oct. 3 when Discovery glided to the desert floor to complete the first shuttle flight since Challenger blew up after liftoff on Jan. 28, 1986.
