<HEAD>Homeless Housing Board Called Do-Nothing Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State and congressional housing experts say a federal panel charged with coordinating programs for the homeless has done little or nothing to address the problem. Witnesses at a congressional hearing Wednesday lambasted the <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on the Homeless, saying it has not met its legislative mandate. The criticism came at a joint hearing of two <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panels as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on housing introduced legislation touted by sponsors as `` the framework for a new national housing strategy.'' The litany of the council's failures began in the opening statement from Rep. <PERSON> Cardiss </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., who chairs the Government Activities and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said the council `` has failed almost completely to carry out the mandates set for it by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said. The council was established in 1987 by Title II of the McKinney Act to coordinate 20 new programs created by the act. It is supposed to provide information on the programs and help state and local governments and non-profit organizations implement them. Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the Employment and Housing subcommittee, said much of the information that homeless providers needed to apply for <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> money was provided instead by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> NGA </ORGANIZATION> testified that after receiving numerous questions from states, she developed a report on the status of programs under the McKinney Act and related legislation. She said the report has now been updated three times. `` This publication contains the type of information the council should be disseminating,'' said <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>. Other witnesses said the council, in a year and a half since enactment of <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, failed to hire a complete staff or identify regional and field coordinators for programs. It focused too much on the development of an electronic data base which housing providers could not use, often sent information regarding application deadlines late, met just five times and produced only three monthly newsletters which contained useless information, the witnesses said. <PERSON> Cassandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, the council's former executive director, blamed a lack of resources. `` The duties with which the council is charged and its ability to carry them out must be brought into balance,'' she said. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gave the council broad authority to develop programs and issue timetables but not the power or resources to do the job. She recommended increasing the staff size and removing the council from the administrative wing of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, which she said has been unwilling to share information. The council, composed of the heads or their designees of 10 Cabinet departments and five independent agencies, was headed under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration by then-housing secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has yet to choose his successor.
