<FIRST>r a PM-HeartFailure     03-16 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Heart Failure,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Heart Failure Drug Not as Good as Old Standby</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 200-year-old mainstay of treatment for congestive heart failure will continue to play its key role after research showed that a highly touted replacement is not as good for many patients, experts say. When testing began several years ago with the new drug, called milrinone, some experts predicted it would supplant digitalis as the medicine of choice for the 4 million Americans with congestive heart failure. The latest study, published today, compared milrinone to a form of digitalis called digoxin in people with mild to moderate heart failure. Although milrinone worked, it was not as effective as digoxin. Those receiving it did worse and suffered more side effects. `` The clinical wisdom of a few years ago that it would be a replacement for digitalis is not correct,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> DiBianco </PERSON>, who directed the study. `` It will not replace digitalis.'' Experts said the findings were surprising and disappointing. But in an editorial published with the study in the New England Journal of Medicine, Dr. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohn </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> said, `` The good news for now is that digoxin can be used with greater confidence in its efficacy.'' Doctors also said there should still be a place for milrinone because it may be used in people who can not tolerate digitalis. <PERSON> DiBianco </PERSON> said he would like to be able to prescribe milrinone for such people, but `` for the majority of my patients, digitalis now even more firmly becomes the standard drug.'' DiBianco, a researcher at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Adventist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Takoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, was the study's principal author. Research was conducted on 230 patients at 32 hospitals. An injected form of milrinone, produced by Sterling Drug, was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> last year for short-term treatment of acute heart failure. However, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has yet to clear the medicine's pill form, which was used in the latest study. In the three-month comparison study, patients with mild to moderate heart failure were randomly assigned to take milrinone, diuretics, digoxin or a combination of these drugs. The conditions of 20 percent of those taking milrinone deteriorated within two weeks after treatment began, compared with only 3 percent of those receiving digoxin. Side effects of milrinone included palpitations, irregular heartbeat, lightheadedness, low blood pressure, nervousness and headaches. Among those who once suggested that milrinone might replace digitalis was Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baim </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Beth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. His early results showed that the drug helped people with severe congestive heart failure who did not respond to other medicines. Although the latest results are disappointing, he said, `` I still believe that there is a clear beneficial role in the patient who has heart failure that is refractory to the conventional agents.''
</TEXT>
