<HEAD>Fears Of Violence Kept Campaign On Airwaves, Off Streets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Images of violence, catchy music and casual character assassination were among the dominant features of an election campaign that tried to stick to the airwaves and stay off of the streets. For one thing, radio and television advertisements were much safer than public appearances in this country, where expressing your political preference can be lethal. The campaign ended Wednesday with a burst of such advertistments and a rally by the leftist Democratic Convergence. No campaigning is permitted from today until Sunday's presidential balloting. The political parties knew that more than 85 percent of Salvadorans homes have radios, the most pervasive medium in a country where personal messages from one town to another are relayed between songs on music stations. There are 51 AM stations in the country of 5.5 million people _ 3 million radio receivers and 4.5 million daily listeners. Now Salvadorans are being asked to go to the polls to pick a president under the threat of violence by the leftist guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, whose nine-year war against the U.S.-supported government has claimed 70,000 lives. The rebels, as in previous elections, have threatened violence and urged voters to stay home on election day. In 1984, nearly 75 percent of the voters cast ballots. They chose <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Democrat </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> as president and gave a strong second place to a surging right-wing party _ the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> _ that now threatens to wrest power from the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>. Political parties avoided big rallies both in the capital and in the countryside during this year's four-month campaign. A <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> rally on Saturday was the largest of the campaign, drawing more than 20,000 people in the capital. Most election work was carried out by party volunteers working city blocks and at so-called `` carnivals,'' where party leaders mingled with the people while local bands played and liquor flowed. Several people were killed in the early days of the campaign. The leftist guerrillas threatened city mayors, then killed nine of them, and leaders of the two dominant parties accused each other of political slayings. As a result, all the parties took the lion's share of their campaigns to the airwaves. Several sectors of society, principally the Roman Catholic church, harshly criticized the mudslinging that marked the ads. The <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> ran a television ad that showed a blood-covered man's body on the floor, followed by an image of a similarily butchered woman. `` This is the kind of violence <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> brought to the country,'' says a guttural voice over a horror movie soundtrack, playing on accusations that <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, known as <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, is linked to right-wing death squads who killed thousands of reputed leftists in the early 1980s. <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> ran radio ads alleging that <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON> embezzled or squandered millions of dollars, some of it destined for victims of the 1986 earthquake. Both parties denied each other's accusations. The leftist <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convergence </ORGANIZATION> ran television ads showing soldiers firing on crowds while a voice sang, `` Let me not be indifferent to pain.'' The three parties flooded the airwaves on Wednesday, but the well-funded rightist party had by far the most broadcast time. `` Of course, not only do we benefit from the propaganda, but we block others,'' said an <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> campaign organizer, speaking on condition of anonymity. But the airwaves are n't reserved for the parties. The rebels spoke to voters with their clandestine <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Venceremos </ORGANIZATION>, taking credit for an attack on the presidential palace and threatening election workers in an effort to enforce their election boycott.
