<HEAD>Parole Officials: McGivern May Be Released Friday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A convicted cop-killer granted clemency in 1985 may go free as early as Friday, said state parole officials who voted to release him. A three-member panel of the state Board of Parole voted unanimously Wednesday to release <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON>, who some saw as an unrepentant murderer. But <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> also had some well-known supporters, including folk singer <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Seeger </PERSON>, conservative columnist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> and civil rights lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON>. `` It's been a long haul. I've been in this for 13 -LCB- years,'' said <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON>. `` I'm happy for <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>, his wife and his family.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavanagh </PERSON>, the prosecutor who won the 25 years to life sentences handed <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON>, 44, and co-defendant <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON>, said the parole board's decision was `` a sad commentary on our criminal justive system.'' Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s grant of clemency for <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> on New Year's Eve 1985 was denounced by many <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law enforcement officials and by then Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> At the time, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> was considered a potential 1988 presidential contender. Although <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s clemency made <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> immediately eligible for parole consideration, the state board twice refused to free him before Wednesday's hearing at <LOCATION> Otisville </LOCATION> state prison where <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> was being held. The board's executive director, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Elwin </PERSON>, said <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> could be freed as early as Friday. Through three trials, <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> and <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> steadfastly maintained their innocence in the 1968 shooting death of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Westchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> deputy, during an escape attempt. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>, the 86-year-old brother of the slain deputy, said <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> should have been kept in prison for life. `` But what are you going to do?'' he said after the parole board decision. `` There's nothing I can do about it.'' <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> was n't granting interviews Wednesday, but <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> said his friend's parole was `` wonderful.'' <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> said he felt the parole board's decision might help his bid for early release. Thus far, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has refused to grant <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> clemency and he's not eligible for a parole hearing until late 1991. That's when <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> would have been first eligible for parole without <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s clemency. In the past, the board had cited the serious nature of the crime in keeping <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> behind bars. On Wednesday, the board noted <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON>'s `` outstanding record'' while in prison. Leading the effort to win <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON>'s freedom has been free-lance writer <PERSON> Marguerite </PERSON> <PERSON> Culp </PERSON>, a former newspaper reporter who met <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> while he was in prison and married him on the 10th anniversary of the shooting. <PERSON> Elwin </PERSON> said <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> and his wife planned to live at her home in <LOCATION> Woodstock </LOCATION>. That's not far from where <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON>, <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> and inmate <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowerman </PERSON>, according to prosecutor <PERSON> Kavanagh </PERSON>, tried to escape while being transported from state prison to a court appearance. At the time, <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> and <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> were serving state prison sentences for the armed robbery of a gas station. <PERSON> Bowerman </PERSON>, a jailhouse lawyer, was helping them appeal their convictions. <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bowerman </PERSON> were fatally shot and <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> and <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> were wounded. <PERSON> Kavanagh </PERSON> said it was <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> who fired the shot that killed <PERSON> Fitzgerald </PERSON>. Even though <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> and <PERSON> Culhane </PERSON> have maintained <PERSON> Bowerman </PERSON> acted alone, a second deputy in the car, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>, said they were involved. Singer has since committed suicide.
