<HEAD>Lawsuit Over Sanctuary Bugging May Be Revived</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Churches won a court victory over the government's electronic war against the Sanctuary movement, but four <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> churches must meet another test to keep their lawsuit alive, a federal appeals court ruled. In a dispute that grew out of the federal government's use of electronic surveillance to track the Sanctuary movement, the court ruled unanimously Wednesday that churches have the right to sue over the issue. `` Of course, we're delighted,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrott </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Southside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presbyterian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION> `` We've always felt that the infiltrators in our church were a disgrace.'' But in order to keep their lawsuit alive, the churches must prove that the surveillance is continuing or likely to resume, according to the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruling. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> must weigh the evidence, the court said. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Baird </PERSON>, a lawyer for the churches, called the 3-0 ruling `` a great stride forward toward protecting worship services from electronic surveillance.'' <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> declined to comment. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> district director of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said he had not seen the ruling and could not comment. The court did not say whether government infiltration and secret recording of church services, without a search warrant, would violate freedom of religion or the constitutional ban on unreasonable searches. That is a key issue in the pending appeal of eight Sanctuary movement workers, including five members of the clergy, convicted in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> in 1986 of a variety of immigration charges, including illegally harboring and transporting Central American refugees. It was disclosed in that case that paid government informants had secretly recorded worship services and Bible classes. A federal prosecutor said the surveillance was proper because the church was the site of a criminal conspiracy. The criminal appeal was argued before another panel of the 9th Circuit last December and has not yet been decided. The civil suit that led to Wednesday's ruling was filed by churches in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>. They said informants working for the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> attended and secretly recorded their services between March 1984 and January 1985. Once the surveillance was disclosed, church officials said, their attendance declined, a Bible study group was canceled, and members became more reluctant to seek pastoral counseling and less open in their prayers and confessions. The suit sought a ruling that the surveillance was improper and a court order banning it in the future. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> dismissed the suit without a trial, saying that even if all the allegations were true, the churches as organizations had not been harmed. But the appeals court disagreed. `` When congregants are chilled from participating in worship activities, when they refuse to attend worship services because they fear the government is spying on them and taping their every utterance ... we think a church suffers organizational injury because its ability to carry out its ministries has been impaired,'' said the opinion by Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Norris </PERSON>.
