<HEAD>Dukakis Calls on Bush to Free Funds for Boston Harbor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is being asked to back up his presidential campaign rhetoric blasting Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for failing to clean up <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, for whom the polluted harbor became a political liability, asked the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration Wednesday to put `` its money where its mouth was.'' `` When you make the kind of statements that were made in the campaign, you've got an obligation to make good on them,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. The governor faulted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for proposing cutbacks in federal wastewater construction programs that would cost <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> $ 40 million. In addition, he charged that while <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has earmarked $ 59 million for the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> project, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has not included those funds in its budget. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he was confident the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> congressional delegation would reverse those decisions. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, as the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate for president, staged a surprise cruise in September on <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> to criticize <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for pollution. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporters argued that the governor was primarily responsible for the legislation designed to end the pollution by the next century. But the charges, reinforced by a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> campaign TV commercial, stuck to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, leaving the Democrat on the defensive. `` I'm proud to say that as of today, we're right on schedule _ and that's the way we're going to keep it,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told reporters Wednesday, flanked by Environmental Affairs Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVillars </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> Executive Director <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>. The governor ticked off a series of steps already taken to address the harbor pollution, beginning with the creation of the water resources authority. Noting that the agency has already spent $ 350 million of the projected $ 6.5 billion cost, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said the state water authority has stopped the discharge of `` floating scum'' from its aging treatment plants at <LOCATION> Nut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Deer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> promised that families will notice cleaner beaches this summer in the metropolitan area.
