<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     03-16 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Free Market Premier, Government Sworn In In Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ante </PERSON> <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> was installed today as premier and promised a series of democratic-oriented economic and political initiatives to roust this Communist country from a nine-year economic slide. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> said in his inaugural speech that a free-market economy is the `` ultimate achievement of mankind _ for which no alternative has yet been found.'' A new Cabinet was also sworn in. `` There is no solution to the economic crisis without the strengthening of political democracy in the country,'' he said, urging the creation of `` a new modern socialist system.'' The new premier said this <LOCATION> Balkan </LOCATION> country of 23 million people has to undergo `` a fundamental change'' in order to revive the economy. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is burdened by 346 percent annual inflation and a $ 21 billion foreign debt. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> indicated he would seek closer links the West, including greater economic cooperation with the European Economic Community. He advocates reshaping the country's banking system along Western lines, creating a stock market and ending state subsidies to money-losing companies. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, which split from the Soviet bloc in 1948, is a founding member of the non-aligned movement, and both superpowers vie for its good graces. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON>, a successful businessman, called for an immediate introduction of shares and bonds, private initiative and entrepreneurship and an end to state interference in the operation of businesses. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON>, a former president of the Croatian republic, succeeds <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>, who, together with his entire <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>, resigned Dec. 30. <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>'s government was the first to resign since the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> took power after World War II. He stepped down following his government's failure to solve the country's daunting social and economic problems, including a dramatic rise in social and ethnic unrest. Economic problems have been accompanied by a resurgence of historic ethnic rivalries a this loose federation of six republics and two autonomous provinces. Much of the recent unrest has centered on the southern province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, where ethnic Albanians form a majority of 90 percent. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON>'s 19-member Cabinet, the smallest in postwar history, is a mix of prominent politicians and technocrats, with only two ministers retaining the seats they occupied in <LOCATION> Mikulic </LOCATION>'s government. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Budimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Loncar </PERSON> and Defense Minister Gen. <PERSON> Veljko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadijevic </PERSON> remained in the new administration, while <PERSON> Dobrosav </PERSON> <PERSON> Culafic </PERSON>, Interior Minister in <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>'s government, lost his job. <PERSON> Culafic </PERSON> was replaced following severe public criticism of his handling of tensions in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, where emergency measures were imposed last month in order to prevent clashes between ethnic Albanians and Slavs living there. The important <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> went to Gen. <PERSON> Petar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gracanin </PERSON>, president of the largest republic of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, of which <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> is an administrative part. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> named as vice premiers <PERSON> Aleksandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitrovic </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>'s vice president, and <PERSON> Zivko </PERSON> <PERSON> Pregl </PERSON>, executive secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Slovene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> party The choice of vice premiers indicates <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> took a balanced stand between <LOCATION> Slovenia </LOCATION>, which advocates a market economy and more political pluralism, and <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, which strives for more centralism and political orthodoxy. In his choice of <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> members, <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> has for the first time abandoned the principle of absolute parity among the republics and autonomous provinces _ which, strictly adhered to in the past, provided for equal <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> representation of all regions. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is run by a state presidency, a collective nine-man body whose chairmanship rotates annually. It is the supreme commander of the armed forces and executes foreign policy. The government is responsible for executing economic policy, while the Communist Party Presidium, or Politburo, has 23 members to oversee state activities.
</TEXT>
