<HEAD>Trial Of Two Dissidents Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two dissidents imprisoned since October for inciting anti-government demonstrations went on trial today, the latest in a series of crackdowns on leading activists. <PERSON> Hana </PERSON> <PERSON> Marvanova </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dvorak </PERSON>, both members of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, were arrested just prior to an Oct. 28 march marking the 70th anniversary of Czechoslovak independence. The two also are accused of inciting a mass demonstration on Aug. 21 in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>'s Wenceslas Square. The charges against the two have been changed several times during their pretrial detention. But the London-based emigre publishing house <PERSON> Palach </PERSON> <PERSON> Press </PERSON> said they face incitement charges that could jail them for up to five years.
