 The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> says it is checking into claims by a radio station caller that a group called Guardians of the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolution </ORGANIZATION> planted the bomb that destroyed a van driven by the wife of the USS Vincennes skipper. Meanwhile, trustees at the private school where the skipper's wife teaches scheduled an emergency meeting today in response to parents' concern about student safety if <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> returns to her fourth-grade classroom The caller, who spoke with a <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> accent and claimed to be a member of the group, linked Friday's car bombing to last July's downing of an Iranian jetliner by a missile fired from the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, the radio station said All 290 people aboard of the jet were killed when Capt. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> gave the order to fire in the belief the aircraft was an attacking warplane. The caller to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> KNX </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday also threatened additional attacks against <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' wife and `` all the American officers and officials,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Nadel </PERSON>, the station's executive news producer `` We're looking into -LRB- the claim -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. He declined to elaborate. Terrorist expert <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said he doubts the validity of the call because it came five days after the bombing and was n't phoned to a news wire service like most legitimate claims for such acts. Guardians of the Islamic Revolution has told international news organizations it was responsible for the Dec. 21 bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, that killed 270 people. The Islamic group also has claimed credit for a July 1987 car bombing in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> that killed a former minister in the government of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s deposed <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Reza </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahlavi </PERSON>, and the October 1987 slayings of two opponents of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s regime. Mrs. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> escaped uninjured in Friday's bombing of the family van. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> said the bomb was a non-military device, possibly a pipe bomb. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Orrantia </PERSON> has said no possible motives for the attack on the van have been ruled out, including retribution for the airliner downing. Mrs. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' future at La Jolla Country Day School may be discussed at today's board of trustees meeting, which was called after the school received a bomb threat Tuesday, board member <PERSON> Houshmand </PERSON> <PERSON> Aftahi </PERSON> said. Police found no explosives, but the incident apparently caused concern among parents that such threats will continue if Mrs. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> returns to the school, where students will be off the next two weeks for spring break. `` I hear that some parents are concerned and they want to know what the school is going to do about it,'' <PERSON> Aftahi </PERSON> said. `` We're all concerned about the security of our children, and we feel that her presence on the campus, at this point, is not good,'' an unidentified parent told the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZ