<HEAD>South Africa Questions Impartiality Of U.N. In Namibia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said today that <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> fundraising efforts to benefit the <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement have raised doubts about the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s impartiality in monitoring the Namibian independence process. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has been soliciting funds for the International Day for the Elimination of Racial Discrimination, set for March 21, said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Heerden </PERSON>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s director general of foreign affairs. He said some of the money raised will go into four funds that are spent for the benefit of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spent about $ 30 million on <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> from these funds last year, <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Heerden </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> has waged a guerrilla war since 1966 in a bid to win independence for the territory, which has been ruled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since World War I. Last year, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan that calls for the independence process to begin April 1, leading to elections in November. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> is favored in the elections, but other political parties will be competing. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Heerden </PERSON> said there would be `` hell to pay'' when these parties learn that the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> was raising money that would benefit <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Heerden </PERSON> also accused <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> of inflating the number of its supporters living as refugees outside <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> has said there are 80,000 refugees, while the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> has put the figure at around 60,000, and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has suggested there might be as few as 15,000. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> receives funds from various countries and organizations on a per capita basis. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> operation in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> involves 4,650 peacekeeping troops and will cost in excess of $ 400 million. One of the major Namibian political parties today accused Australian peacekeepers of attending a party of <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> supporters and wishing the organization well in the elections. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turnhalle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> said about five Australian peacekeepers went to the party Tuesday evening in the northern town of <LOCATION> Grootfontein </LOCATION>. At one stage, one of the Australians went to the microphone and wished SWAPO success in the elections, the alliance said in a statement. The alliance, a multiracial coalition, is expected to be <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>'s main competitor in the elections About 170 peacekeepers from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> arrived in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> today to join the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> forces. More than 20 nations are sending troops and administrative personnel to participate in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> effort.
