move the proceedings to a special committee for hearing evidence, followed by a floor vote on whether to convict <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> of conspiracy, perjury and disclosing secret wiretap information in an investigation of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> corruption. <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>, 52, would remain free if convicted but would lose his seat on the federal bench and his $ 89,500 annual salary. Packed galleries were ordered by Sergeant-at-Arms <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giugni </PERSON> to `` keep silent on pain of imprisonment'' as <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> took the floor to address an extraordinary <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> session with attendance among lawmakers unusually high. `` The jury heard all the evidence and argument on both sides,'' <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> said. `` They were attentive. The prosecutors never complained about either the quality of the jurors or the attention they gave. Those jurors deliberated carefully. They reached a conclusion. All 12 of them agreed that I was not guilty.'' Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, one of the prosecutors, scoffed at <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON>' position. He said a double-jeopardy defense did not apply in an impeachment trial but that the judge was seizing on it anyway `` to shield himself from the consequences of his inexcusable breaches of the public trust.'' `` Over five years, Judge <PERSON> Alcee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastings </PERSON> engaged in a clearly discernible pattern of misbehavior,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said. `` He conspired to sell his public office for personal gain, he subverted our judicial process by repeatedly lying under oath and he divulged confidential information in violation of his own court order,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Jack 