<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supreme Court Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> is being criticized for sending a letter used by conservative <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> to support their claim that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is `` a Christian nation.'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kropp </PERSON>, president of People for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION>, said the letter has lent support to a movement that is `` a force for religious intolerance.'' The liberal activist group supports strict separation of church and state. <PERSON> O'Connnor </PERSON> said in a brief statement Wednesday that she was sorry the way her letter was used. `` I regret that a letter I sent to an acquaintance in response to her request for information was used in a political debate,'' said <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, a former state legislator from <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. `` It was not my intention to express a personal view about the subject of the inquiry, but merely to attempt to respond appropriately to one of the many requests for information which come across my desk.'' She declined further comment. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s May 19, 1988 letter was sent to <PERSON> Annetta </PERSON> <PERSON> Conant </PERSON>, author of a resolution characterizing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> nation that was adopted last January by the <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The resolution is a rallying point for backers of the state's former <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> governor, <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, who was removed from office last year Moderate Republicans and prominent Jewish Republicans in the state expressed dism