<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Guerrillas paralyzed bus services, sabotaged power lines and staged sporadic attacks today in a stepped-up campaign to disrupt Sunday's presidential election. Most bus drivers refused to work because rebels warned bus companies to keep their vehicles off the nation's streets and gas stations to remain closed. Many gas stations were guarded by troops to prevent rebel attacks. `` It does not matter that we have the soldiers here. We ca n't work because the workers have not come in,'' a watchman at one gas station said Much of the capital and the eastern half of the country was without power after rebels destroyed electricity poles, the power company said. Schools were closed throughout <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, while army helicopters and planes flew over the capital. One soldier was killed and four were wounded during a pre-dawn guerrilla attack in <LOCATION> Entre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rios </LOCATION>, 40 miles east of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, the military said. The <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, the umbrella group for the leftist guerrillas, also launched morning attacks in the towns of <LOCATION> Cinquera </LOCATION> and Tejutepeque in the eastern department of <LOCATION> Cabanas </LOCATION> and in the provincial capital of <LOCATION> Zacatecoluca </LOCATION>, officials said. No casualties were immediately reported. In the capital, an army convoy waited outside the eastern bus terminal to transport passengers to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vicente </LOCATION>, 30 miles to the east, but few customers were seen early this morning. `` No one has come in. The owners are afraid. So are the people,'' said dispatcher <PERSON> Lazaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s western bus terminal. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said there normally are 300 bus departures and arrivals daily. The rebels have called for an election boycott and warned they would sabotage any vehicle ignoring the transport ban. Such threats have stopped about 90 percent of the nation's transport in the past. Private operators used flatbed and pickup trucks to transport people throughout <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, and some vehicles carried white flags. News reports said citizens were offering similar transport services in other cities. On Wednesday, when campaigning officially ended, rebels attacked the presidential palace with grenades and bombs and killed a prominent rightist political adviser in the capital. Also Wednesday, a civilian judge indicted two military officers on charges of massacring 10 peasants. It was the first time in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s nine-year civil war that officers have been indicted in a human rights case. In Wednesday night's attack on the palace, shrapnel from a rocket-propelled grenade injured a palace guard and six civilians who live nearby, authorities said. The leftist rebels claimed responsibility in a radio broadcast. President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> was not present when the grenades and catapult-launched homemade bombs began landing, said Col. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Casanova </PERSON>, commander of the Zapote garrison next door. Unidentified gunmen on Wednesday killed <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Peccorini </PERSON>, a political adviser to the Arena party. <PERSON> Peccorini </PERSON> was shot three times while being driven in his car, authorities said. <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> of Arena, or the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, is favored to win Sunday's vote, with <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON> <PERSON> of </PERSON> <PERSON> the </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>'s centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> second and <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Ungo </PERSON> of the leftist Democratic Convergence third. If <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> wins, it would be the first time in Salvadoran history that voters dumped an incumbent party in favor of another. The military said it would provide armed escorts Sunday to vehicles taking voters to the polls. The rebels have boycotted every election this decade as a farce, accusing the government of ignoring the fundamental economic and social problems of this Massachusetts-sized nation of 5.5 million people.
