<HEAD>Widespread Defiance of Birth Control Policies Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s policy of one child per couple and restrictions on early marriages are being widely ignored, according to a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> survey released Thursday. Results of the survey said that since the one-child policy was started in 1980, about 9 million babies a year have been born outside the state plan. <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> head <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> <PERSON> Peiyun </PERSON> said the survey was an `` alarm bell.'' She said the average Chinese couple between 1980 and 1987 had 2.47 children. Last year there were approximately 23 million births and 7 million deaths in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, pushing the nation's population close to 1.1 billion. The two-year survey, which covered 2 million people, found that women bearing two or more children accounted for 40 percent of the unauthorized births. About one-fifth of the unauthorized births were to women under 20, which is the legal age for women in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to marry, the People's Daily said in reporting results of the survey. The survey found that less than 60 percent of women of child-bearing age practice birth control. The government has had substantial success in limiting family sizes in cities but has met strong resistance in the countryside. Rural couples, wanting boys in particular to help in the fields and to care for them when they become old, have been willing to pay steep fines for violating the one-child policy. The government has acknowledged that its target of limiting population to 1.2 billion in the year 2000 is not possible. Estimates for the number of Chinese at the turn of the century have jumped to 1.3 billion, about 20 percent of total world population.
