<HEAD>Satellite Facing Budget Ax Helps Locate Earthquake Faults</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Scientists have discovered a series of unknown earthquake faults thanks to pictures from a satellite that has been facing the budget ax. The faults are located in the central and eastern parts of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> and were found using images taken by the Landsat satellite, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The faults were discovered by studying a series of images taken in differing optical and infrared spectra, according to scientists at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> ` s Jet Propulsion Laboratory in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and at <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Some of the faults are inactive, but others may still be seismically active, the scientists said. The faults form part of a complex fault region between <LOCATION> Death </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andreas </LOCATION> fault region. Without the Landsat images, the faults would not have been discovered, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. His announcement was made even as scientists and politicians were struggling over financing to keep the Landsat system going. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> announced recently that it would have to shut down the Landsat system at the end of this month because of a lack of money to operate it. Subsequently Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> began encouraging other government agencies to chip in funds to keep the system going and the cutoff has at least been delayed. Landsat, which studies the Earth's surface for mapping, mineral studies and other research, still faces a tenuous financual future, however.
