<SECOND>AM-Dalai Lama, Bjt,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tibetan Leader Optimistic Chinese Will Negotiate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHARMSALA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tibetans' spiritual leader, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, said Thursday he believes <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> is ready for negotiations that would grant greater freedom to his people and the land he fled 30 years ago. In an interview at his exile headquarters in the remote Himalayan foothills of north <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> admitted he has had no recent indication of this from <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> authorities. In fact, the Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> has been under martial law since bloody anti-Chinese protests there last week. But the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> adhered to his belief that change is sweeping <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, that the new concept of reform in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will soon come to the world's other major communist power. `` Within a few months, talks may start,'' the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> said. In the meantime, he said, he will continue to support non-violent protest in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. `` Peaceful demonstrations _ that I am supporting. That is the only way to make -LRB- our situation -RRB- known to the outside world,'' the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> said. Tibetans `` should not indulge in damaging and burning property. They should not indulge in stoning. Even if the Chinese open fire, they should not retaliate,'' he said. The Dalai Lama spoke at midafternoon in the hilltop compound that houses his residence, offices, Thekchen Choeling Temple and <LOCATION> Namgyal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monastery </LOCATION> where maroon-robed monks debate ancient scriptures and venerate this bespectacled, 54-year-old farmer's son as a living god-king, the 14th reincarnation of the earthly manifestation of <PERSON> Buddha </PERSON>. On another March 16 afternoon, exactly 30 years ago, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> was in a more remote and far grander Himalayan compound, in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>. Surrounded by Chinese troops who had moved their artillery within range of his palace, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> and his advisers were at the brink of the decision that would propel him and eventually 110,600 other Tibetans into exile. By the night of March 17, he had slipped out of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>'s Norbulinka Palace disguised as a Tibetan soldier and shouldering a rifle By April 18, 1959, he was safe in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, free to speak against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. But the Tibetans' uprising had failed. The Chinese guns had bombarded <PERSON> Norbulinka </PERSON>, and thousands of Tibetans were dead. It was the approach of this anniversary that resulted in more bloodshed in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> last week. By official count, 16 people were killed when police opened fire during a pro-independence demonstration in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> in which Chinese-owned shops and vehicles were set afire. Western travelers said as many as 20 or 30 were killed. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s subsequent ban on foreigners entering <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> makes it impossible for the outside world to know with any certainty what is happening in the ancient kingdom, which Chinese troops entered in 1950. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> maintains <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> has traditionally been part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> and his government in exile say <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> has been independent for centuries. `` In the last few days, you see a sad situation within <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>,'' the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> said, a long shawl of finely spun wool protecting him from the mountain chill. `` In the last 30 years, they -LRB- the Chinese -RRB- have used every repression,'' he said, speaking in English. `` We lost everything in the last 30 years, but we still remain. We are the same Tibetans the Chinese bullied 30 years ago.'' Despite the imposition of martial law, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> said he thought <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s eagerness to open its economy to the outside world would bring greater awareness and greater tolerance to political problems at home. Reflecting a sense that time may be running out, that an influx of Chinese settlers in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> would obliterate the separate Tibetan identity, the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> last June made his biggest concession to date. He proposed his homeland become `` a self-governing democratic political entity... In association with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' In return, he said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> could retain troops on Tibetan soil and handle <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s foreign policy. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> rejected the proposal, saying it failed to relinquish the concept of Tibetan independence, but it said it was willing to talk to the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON> on Thursday repeated that talks should start at a lower level, in a neutral spot outside Chinese control. `` If the Chinese do not want to talk, OK. The last 30 years we spent like this,'' he said.
