<FIRST>r w AM-WorldRain     03-16 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-World Rain,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 6:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<HEAD>World is Wetter, But Not Everywhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's land areas have become wetter over the last century or so, but the rainfall increases have skipped large areas of the planet, according to a study released Thursday. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> have seen measurable increases in precipitation since the late 1800s, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> reported. At the same time, however, there has been a decline in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and in tropical areas of the Northern Hemisphere. The analysis of rainfall patterns was compiled by <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, R.S. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Eischeid </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION>. Their findings are to be published in an upcoming issue of the Journal of Geophysical Research. The scientists looked at nearly a century of records. <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said the primary period of increasing rainfall in the <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION> was from the 1940s to the mid-1950. In the Northern Hemisphere, the overall trend is almost unchanged, he said, noting, however, that there seems to have been a decline in rainfall in northern tropical areas in the last 15 years or so. Rainfall patterns show substantial variability from time to time, the scientists noted, changing over periods of a decade or more. Thus, they said, it is difficult to determine whether rainfall has been affected by long-term phenomena such as that embodied in the Greenhouse theory, which predicts that changes in the atmosphere will cause worldwide temperatures to warm, leading to changes in rainfall and other climate phenomena.
</TEXT>
