<HEAD>IRS Says Budget Crunch Won't Slow Return Processing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, under heavy fire for often answering taxpayers' questions incorrectly, will not slow its processing of tax refunds despite scattered personnel and supply shortages caused by the budget crunch, acting Commissioner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said Thursday. `` We have a management problem trying to conserve resources. ... We are looking for about $ 50 million'' to continue present levels of operations for the next six months, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> oversight subcommittee. But the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> will not let the problem slow returns processing, reduce services to taxpayers or deter the agency's enforcement efforts, he vowed. On another problem, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> appeared to confirm reports that the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has had a policy of sometimes not telling taxpayers when they neglect to take credit for taxes withheld from their paychecks. That would result in an overpayment of taxes. Until last December, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> told Rep. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Tenn., some credits `` were not picked up'' at one stage of the agency's review of tax returns and `` it is possible that taxpayers did not get the refund they were entitled to. Although changes in those procedures were made last year, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> added, `` I still am not completely satisfied with that program.'' He said he has asked for a report from other <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> officials. The existence of such a policy was asserted by <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employees in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> in interviews with Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Tenn., and The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> One employee, speaking only on the condition she not be named, said an agency handbook prohibited telling a taxpayer that he or she had neglected to subtract taxes withheld from taxes owed. In most such cases, she said, taxpayers were overcharged by $ 100 to $ 1,000, and often these cases involved retirees' pensions. When <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was asked about the policy, she said, `` We were told the taxpayers had to find their own mistakes.'' There were so many complaints from <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> workers about the policy that it was modified last year to permit notification of taxpayers who failed to subtract taxes withheld from wages or from periodic pension payments, the employee said. But the old policy remains in effect in cases of lump-sum pension payments. The Memphis worker is involved in an <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> program to identify taxpayers who failed to report some or all of their income. She and others in the program start checking returns about 15 months after they are filed. If they find underreporting, they send the taxpayer a form letter asking for an explanation. After <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> testified Thursday, his principal spokesman, <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, said the agency's policy is `` to make sure that people who are entitled to refunds get them.'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> spent a good deal of his time before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel apologizing that <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employees in some areas of the nation are correctly answering taxpayers' telephoned questions barely half the time. `` Our accuracy rate is unacceptable,'' he said. `` We will not be satisfied until we see substantial improvement.'' Although the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> disagree on just how often telephone `` assistors'' are wrong, the precise figure did n't seem to matter to members of the subcommittee. `` You're talking about whether we should give you a ` D' or a ` D-minus,''' said Rep. <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, the chairman. `` Calling the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> for tax advice is a real crapshoot.'' The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> have been exchanging words since March 10, when the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> called a news conference to announce that its 5,000 employees who answer taxpayers' telephoned questions were giving correct answers about 71 percent of the time. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said the correct figure for the nation was closer to 62 percent and said the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> had labeled some misleading answers as correct. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> apologized for the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> interpretation. But ironically, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> Thursday announced that an updated, although more limited, test indicated that <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employees were correct about 66 percent of the time. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> acknowledged that the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and its 115,000 employees, who collect about $ 1 trillion a year in taxes, are having trouble living within their $ 5.2 billion budget. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified sources Thursday as saying the agency `` is in the throes of a full-fledged cash crisis.'' Much of the trouble can be traced to the fact that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gave the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> $ 100 million less this year than it asked for and then required the agency to cut other programs to finance a pay raise for workers. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> saw the trouble coming late last year and asked the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to request additional money, but the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> refused.
