<HEAD>Teams Getting Ready for Vermont-to-Massachusetts Solar Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the best engineering students in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> are busy trying to build cars that will take them 200 miles over four days. That wo n't be so easy as it sounds, because the cars will have to be powered only by the sun. The <LOCATION> Montpelier </LOCATION>, Vt.-to-Cambridge, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, race, called the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tour </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sol </ORGANIZATION>, is set for May 25-28. The race is patterned after a competition in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> that has attracted hundreds of entries since it began in 1985, including several from the schools involved in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> race this year. `` There's a very high interest level,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> Professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wills </PERSON>, who is coordinating the race. `` At <LOCATION> Dartmouth </LOCATION>, the solar car project has attracted the most interest of any engineering project that I've seen.'' The winning team will get a trip to the European race, also called the Tour de Sol, this summer. Solar-powered cars use photovoltaic cells to collect energy from sunlight that power their electric motors. The cars can reach speeds of more than 60 mph. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> team, said it is redesigning parts of the car that entered last year's European race but was disqualified because of a technical problem in the drive system. Changes will include a new drive system and a new computer. `` We did pretty well, considering we were using a back-up drive system,'' <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. The other four schools participating are <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lowell </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Worcester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do n't know of any single activity on campus that has created as much enthusiasm as the solar car project,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Larrabee </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wills </PERSON> said the race will be run along back roads and will take the competitors through each of the five campuses. The times for the four daily legs of the race will be compared to calculate the winner. `` We managed to hit all the campuses, and that's a big selling point for us,'' he said. `` Everyone on the campuses will be able to see the cars.'' Though the Tour de Sol cars are designed with the hope that one could someday be used commercially, for now their cost is too high. <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> car, for example, cost about $ 80,000. <PERSON> Wills </PERSON> said students get their schools or companies to sponsor the cars, but the cost is worth it because students learn about many engineering problems. `` Even the professors learn a lot,'' he said.
