<TEXT>
 Council members hoping to keep undesirables off their wealthy island are considering installing closed circuit cameras to monitor bridges and the main highway into town. Town Manager <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Doney </PERSON> said the cameras would enable authorities to film `` vehicles, pedestrians and cyclists ... anyone coming to <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> to do anything of an illegal nature.'' He said he thought the cameras could have `` a very good psychological effect on deterring crime.'' Town Attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> said the constitutionality of the proposal, submitted Tuesday by a resident, should be studied before the council votes on it, and council members asked the town's <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to study the matter. Council President <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Douthit </PERSON> said the idea was `` definitely worth the research.'' `` The only people who might be bothered by this are those with a guilty conscience,'' <PERSON> Douthit </PERSON> said. `` You are photographed any time you go into a bank, any time you go through a toll booth on the turnpike and in many retail establishments and condo buildings. I do n't see this as being any different.'' The proposal would place cameras on four bridges and on the town's approach on Highway A1A from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>.
