 About 100 students at <ORGANIZATION> Colby-Sawyer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> sat in Thursday at the administration building, singing `` I Am Woman,'' to protest the possible admission of men. The protest gave way after about four hours to an emotional meeting between the students, nearly one-quarter of the school's roughly 450 enrollment, and two administrators `` This institution runs because of our money. We should be put on the task force'' studying coeducation, one student told President <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Stock </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Trustee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> at the meeting. `` We deserve that.'' In addition, the students asked Stock to scrap separate meetings scheduled with staff, administrators and students in favor of a campuswide meeting, and to delay by a month the April 1 trustees' vote on admitting men Students complained that coeducation has been discussed, partly in response to the prospect of a dwindling applicant pool, since October, but that students learned of it only recently. Students, one told <PERSON> Stock </PERSON>, feel `` segregated and manipulated.'' Stock and <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> responded that the administration has not meant to keep anyone in the dark. `` There's been no effort at all to divide and conquer. Rather, just the opposite _ to let everyone know at the time we know,'' <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> said. The liberal arts school has been all-women for more than 60 years. The school traces its roots to a small academy chartered in 1837.
