<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Senate Foreign Relations Committee voted unanimously today to approve the nomination of <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> as the No. 2 man at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, ending a controversy over his ties to former Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s international consulting firm The 19-0 vote came after <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>, who earned more than $ 900,000 last year as president of <ORGANIZATION> Kissinger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, agreed to voluntarily disqualify himself from all matters involving former clients of the firm during his government service. But <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> was not been required to divulge the names of those clients to the committee, a move sought by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, R-N.C. Several senators pointed out that such a request put the nominee in the position of making disclosures beyond those required under the Ethics in Government Act. The nomination now goes to the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which is expected to approve <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> as undersecretary of state on Friday. The vote came after <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> grilled <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> about his ties to <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s firm. `` <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> was ... a political entity. He still is. That's why <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> got well over a million dollars,'' the senator said <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> brought up the difficulties encountered by former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> in his recent failed attempt to become defense secretary due in part to his financial ties to defense contractors. `` I wish he had an opportunity to answer questions in public about his income,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said. `` He wa