onal information under the firm's confidentiality contract with its clients. The firms include such concerns as <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> conglomerate <ORGANIZATION> Daewoo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, H.J. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, and the Italian car maker <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.p.a. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ITT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, A.B. <ORGANIZATION> Volvo </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. He also testified that under advice from the Office of Government Ethics, he would disqualify himself for a period of one year from any future matters at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> involving the clients he worked with while with the firms. `` There will be no conflicts of interest because I have no outside interests,'' <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said. He also argued that his step to disqualify himself for the one-year period on all matters involving former clients was voluntary and went beyond the requirements of the Ethics in Government Act, which he said only required a recusal case-by-case. But given the current climate on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> in the wake of the intense scrutiny of Tower over his failed nomination to head the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> was queried during his initial hearing about everything from his 30 years in government service to his personal habits. Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, apparently in jest, even asked <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> at one point, `` Have you ever, in public or private, pinched a woman's behind?'' The room erupted in nervous laughter, with <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> responding in the negative.
