<HEAD>Israeli Youngsters Play Russian Roulette in the Streets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli teen-agers are playing a form of Russian roulette that involves dodging speeding cars in an apparent attempt to share the dangers faced by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers, an official said Thursday. The game, which has swept the country in epidemic form, appears in different versions nationwide, said <PERSON> Shai </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadish </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s Road Safety Unit. Teen-agers either lie in the path of an approaching car and wait until the last moment to scamper away or leave school bags in the middle of the road, darting out to snatch them from oncoming cars, <PERSON> Gadish </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The Education and Transportation ministries have sent psychologists to high schools in an attempt to discover why the dangerous game is so popular, he said. <PERSON> Gadish </PERSON> said teen-agers hear about the brave deeds of older friends and brothers in the army. `` They want to imitate them by exhibiting their own courage ... by endangering their own lives,'' he said. Israelis are drafted into the army on their 18th birthday. Men serve for three years and women for two. `` We live in a society where you need to show courage,'' <PERSON> Gadish </PERSON> said. `` These youths know it's dangerous in the streets and that they can show their bravery there.'' Only one youth has been slightly injured playing the game, <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials said. <PERSON> Gadish </PERSON> said teens usually play the game on their way home from school, and high school principals have asked parents to discourage their children from participating. `` We are worried that the more publicity this game of Russian roulette in the streets receives, the more popular it will become,'' said <PERSON> Atniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneller </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>.
