<HEAD>US Agencies Say Apples Safe for Kids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three federal agencies proclaimed today that apples are safe for children to eat, attempting to calm fears about a chemical used by some growers that has been linked to cancer and claims that preschoolers are especially vulnerable. `` The federal government believes that it is safe for Americans to eat apples,'' said a joint statement by the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The agencies said there is no `` imminent hazard posed to children'' by the consumption of apples. At a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing, <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> noted that he moved swiftly to raise concerns about fruit imported from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> after traces of cyanide were found in two grapes. He declared he would do the same if he thought apples were dangerous for children. There has been growing concern among parents and school officials about whether children should continue eating apples and apple products until questions about the health questions. At the center of the controversy is the chemical daminozide, sold under the trade name Alar, which the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said has caused cancer in test animals. Last month a private environmental group issued a report suggesting that children are especially at risk from Alar because they consumer many times more apples and apple products, compared to their weight, than adults. School systems in a number of cities including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> have stopped providing children apples after the report by the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> was made public and the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> program `` 60 Minutes'' reported on the controversy. In a statement, the three federal agencies said: `` The federal government encourages school systems and other responsible for the diets of children to continue to serve apples and other nutritious fruit to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> children.'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the reaction to claims that young children are exposed to a dangerous levels of Alar in apples has caused a `` panic'' that is not warranted. He said there is `` not a signficant risk at this time facing the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people in the consumption of apples.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, acting deputy <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on children, families, drugs and alcoholism that while the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has conclude that daminozide causes cancer, its continued use does not pose a threat that would warrant the chemical being ordered immediately off the market. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> in his testimony criticized the <ORGANIZATION> NRDC </ORGANIZATION> study's risk estimates as not being `` scientifically sound'' and said the report has caused `` misinformation and fear'' to dominate the debate. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said if daminozide were a newly introduced pesticide it would not be approved. Sen. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., suggested that the manufacturer of Alar `` would do us all a public service if they suspended production of the product'' because the controversy is harming the apple industry <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said most growers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state do not use daminozide, but there was no agreement among witnesses as to how widespread the use of the chemical actually is. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has concluded that about 10 percent of the apples are sprayed with Alar, but the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has cited a figure of about 5 percent. Consumer groups have claimed that spot checks have shown a use as high as 30 percent. Several senators said the controversy is threatening the apple industry. `` The apple market is dead as a doornail right now across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, whose family owns an apple orchard.
</TEXT>
