<HEAD>Woman Given Probation, Ordered To Introduce Herself To Store Owners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Nosrat in 2nd graf cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge placing a shoplifter on five years of probation also ordered her to introduce herself to merchants and receive permission before shopping in their stores. <PERSON> Nosrat </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 51, of <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> faced up to a year in prison as a repeat offender. But during sentencing Monday, Madison County Judge <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> said there is evidence Mrs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> had been diagnosed as suffering from kleptomania, a persistant impulse to steal. In asking the court for probation, Mrs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoffer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, said, `` It's a situation where she has no control. This is not a lady who is personally dishonest.'' Deputy County Attorney <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> argued for a one-year sentence, saying previous probation sentences had not kept Mrs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> from repeat offenses. As conditions of probation this time, <PERSON> Riley </PERSON> ordered that Mrs. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> continue receiving therapy for kleptomania, introduce herself to local merchants, shop with an adult escort, list any stores she may have taken items from during the past two years, make restitution to those stores, complete 200 hours of community service work, continue to improve her English-speaking abilities and take a lie detector test every six months.
