<HEAD>Jury Denies Award to Shark Attack Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A surfer bitten by a shark at a public beach has lost a lawsuit against the county in which he charged that as in the movie `` Jaws'' authorities failed to warn bathers because of a holiday weekend. A jury deliberated 77 minutes Wednesday before rejecting a $ 63,000 claim by <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Popper </PERSON> against <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> over a leg injury he received in the May 21, 1983, attack. <PERSON> Popper </PERSON>, 22 when he was bitten, had argued that sharks were sighted off <LOCATION> Haulover </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> in the days prior to his attack, but no warning was issued, even though lifeguards commonly post signs advising of dangerous currents and poisonous jellyfish. `` Why would <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> make the decision to expose people to sharks rather than expose sharks to people?'' <PERSON> Popper </PERSON>'s attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothlein </PERSON> said in his summary. `` There can be only one reason _ there was a holiday weekend coming up and sharks are bad for buisiness.'' Assistant county attorney <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> called those arguments absurd. `` As this trial went on, it became apparent these men were trying to orchestrate the sequel to `` Jaws,'' <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> said. In the <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Benchley </PERSON> novel `` Jaws'' and the movie made from it, the mayor of a fictional beach town fails to heed warnings about shark dangers for fear it will hurt businesses awaiting a holiday weekend crowd. <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> also noted that <PERSON> Popper </PERSON> had been surfing in the area for 10 years prior to the attack and was back surfing in the same spot six months later.
