<HEAD>Hill Negotiators Detect Move Toward Compromise with Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional negotiators on the federal budget said Thursday they detected a move toward compromise with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on which taxes should be raised. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s recommended $ 1.16 trillion budget for fiscal 1990, which opens Oct. 1, proposed to bring in about $ 14 billion through higher taxes, fees for government services, and sales of government assets. The White House contends its specific proposals do n't violate <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` no new taxes'' campaign pledge. Lawmakers said there was little chance of enactment for many of the president's tax proposals, such as expanding the Medicare tax to all state and local employees and cutting the capital-gains tax rate. `` I think they recognize the problem that the revenues that are presented right now, that there's some difficulty in achieving those,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> But it was important that the overall total of $ 14 billion still be raised, he said. <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> and other congressional budget-writers met Thursday with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, and the senior members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' tax-writing committees. Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the Democrats were not proposing to raise more money than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed. `` I think they understand revenues are needed and they've outlined a number of revenues,'' he said `` My message was whatever we do has to be credible, that we have to show the financial markets that we've seriously addressed the problem'' of the deficit. `` Yes, I think there is some movement,'' he said, when asked if progress was made in the meeting. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> declined to answer reporters' questions. <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said there was no change in the administration's position but he did not want to comment on what the lawmakers said. The Gramm-Rudman law mandates that the federal deficit, which is expected to exceed $ 163 billion this year, be reduced to $ 100 billion in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, in a breakfast speech at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, said the scope of the budget talks would be limited by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s willingness or unwillingness to discuss raising taxes. He said taxes needed to be raised and spending cut to produce a serious deficit-reduction plan. With the budget negotiators looking for places to cut spending, pressure continued to increase spending. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> by voice vote approved a recommendation that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adopt <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to increase military spending next year to keep pace with inflation, and boost it 1 percent above inflation the next two years. Rep. Rep. G.V. `` Sonny'' <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, D-Miss., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> budget task force that spending on veterans' health programs must increase faster than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is proposing `` What the budget committee decides in the next few weeks will probably be long remembered,'' he said, citing a crisis in the system and the contribution he said the programs make to the nation's defense. `` So if we must delay the procurement of one or two bombers in order to insure that our veterans receive needed health care, then we must do it. It's an easy choice for me,'' he said.
