<HEAD>Jewish Groups Calls for Boycott of Meetings with Pope</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jewish groups are calling on Jews around the world to boycott meetings with Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> because the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> has failed to remove a convent from the site of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>, the World Jewish <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> section of the World Jewish <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which represents 34 American groups, adopted a resolution that calls for <ORGANIZATION> WJC </ORGANIZATION> members in 70 countries to refrain from meetings with the pope during his frequent travels. The resolution, adopted at a meeting of organization leaders in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, will be introduced at the May 7 meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> WJC </ORGANIZATION>'s International Executive in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> The resolution said the boycott call was `` an expression of anguish and moral distress'' at the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to comply with a 1987 agreement that would remove the Carmelite convent to grounds outside the extermination camp in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` The convent controversy is symptomatic of a clear pattern by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> to revise the history of the Holocaust and the role of the church during that terrible period,'' the resolution said. Pope <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> XII </PERSON> has been widely criticized for failing to act or speak out against the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>' murder of 6 million Jews during World War II. The clash over the convent comes at a time of increasing tensions between the world Jewish community and the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. Nobel laureate <PERSON> Elie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiesel </PERSON>, a Holocaust survivor and author, recently accused Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> of trying to `` de-Judaize'' the Holocaust by ignoring Jewish suffering in speeches and comments about that era. Jewish groups are also angry that the pope has met twice in the last three years with Austrian President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, who has been accused of complicity in Nazi atrocities. The convent at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> was established in 1984 by a dozen Carmelite nuns in a building the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> had used to store poison gas canisters. That action set of a storm of international protest from Jews who wanted the camp site left undisturbed as a memorial to its victims. Jewish and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leaders met in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> in 1987 and agreed that the convent would be removed by Feb. 22, 1989. The church undertook, in writing, to move the nuns to nearby grounds outside the camp so they could continue their educational activities about the Holocaust. In recent months, <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> officials have said a site had been chosen for the new convent. One cleric said work on the building would soon be completed, but a <ORGANIZATION> WJC </ORGANIZATION> delegation that visited the area in January said it had found no construction at all.
