<HEAD>Housing Construction Sags After Mild-Weather Surge in January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Housing construction plummeted 11.4 percent in February, the government reported Thursday, with analysts blaming the sharp decline on harsher weather last month and the bite of higher mortgage interest rates. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said new homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.5 million units last month as the weather turned cold again after an unseasonably mild January. February's pace was down from a rate of 1.69 million units in January, the highest level in nearly two years. Analysts said a longer-term slowdown in the housing market is being caused by the steady upward climb of interest rates. `` We do n't expect housing to suddenly fall off the cliff this year, but we do expect it to progressively weaken with higher interest rates,'' said economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Interest on fixed-rate mortgages averaged 10.86 percent last week, up from 9.84 percent a year earlier, according to a survey by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Initial rates on adjustable-rate mortgages were up even more sharply, with the starting rate on a one-year ARM averaging 8.93 percent last week, up from 7.53 percent a year earlier. <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Colton </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Homebuilders </ORGANIZATION>, said rising interest rates were the `` dominant factor'' behind the association's forecast for a 7 percent slowdown in housing construction this year. An increase of 1 percent in the interest charged on a $ 100,000 mortgage adds $ 62 a month to a homeowner's payments, <PERSON> Colton </PERSON> said. `` That has a big impact on affordability,'' he said. Housing construction reached a post-recession peak in 1986, when 1.81 million units were built, then began sliding. Last year, the level was 1.49 million units. Single-family homes were built in February at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.05 million units, down 13.1 percent from the pace in the previous month and the biggest drop in five years. Apartment construction, meanwhile, was down 7.2 percent in February to an annual rate of 453,000 units. Construction of multifamily housing peaked in 1985 and then began a sharp slide, largely the result of changes in the tax code that made such projects less attractive to investors. <PERSON> Berson </PERSON> said recent data on apartment construction have been more encouraging, suggesting that `` the depressing effects of tax reform and overbuilding may be behind us now.'' Housing permits, a bellwether of future housing activity, fell 6.8 percent last month to a rate of 1.4 million units after dropping 3.8 percent during January. February's decline in permits was the biggest drop since a 9 percent fall in January 1988. `` The building permits data for both months suggest that rising rates have taken a greater toll on housing than is suggested by the starts numbers,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> for a year has been nudging interest rates upward in an effort to slow the economy and restrain inflation. Most analysts expect interest rates to peak at mid-year and then gradually decline again. <PERSON> Colton </PERSON>, of the homebuilders, said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has been reacting to `` inflation paranoia'' and risks driving the country into a recession by pushing interest rates too high. `` We think that at a minimum the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> needs to be very careful,'' <PERSON> Colton </PERSON> said. Housing activity dropped last month in all four regions of the country, with the biggest decline in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, where starts fell 22.6 percent to 229,000 units after surging 47 percent in January. Construction was down 13.7 percent in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> to 277,000 units, and fell 8.7 percent in the West to 400,000 units. In the South, starts were down 6.8 percent to 592,000.
