<HEAD>Communist Leaders Adopt Program To Reform Soviet Farming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to detail changes approved in agricultural system.
No pickup. ^By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders today adopted a sweeping reform program for the inefficient Soviet agricultural system that they hope will end chronic food shortages. The plan, adopted by the plenary meeting of the party's 300-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, would give the nation's farmers the right to lease state-owned land for life However, it would also maintain the network of state and collective farms that have chronically failed to feed the Soviet people. The party also elected its 100 members to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, a new legislative body that will meet for the first time this spring. Among them was President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The plenum acted after debating <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s plan to give farmers long-term leases on state-owned land to make them more attentive and efficient. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also says farmers should be given freedom to decide what to plant on that land, rather than having that decided by the bureaucracy. Politburo member <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> told a news conference the leases could be signed for any period of more than five years and be passed on to succeeding generations of farmers. He said no one would be forced into leasing land. He also said the giant state and collective farms would remain the backbone of the Soviet agricultural system. `` Radical changes in rural life and production relations should be carried out on a purely voluntary basis ... without any kind of force or repressive methods,'' <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said in his first appearance before foreign reporters. Setting targets for leasing would only encourage strong-arm tactics to fulfill the plans, <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> is the Politburo member in charge of farm policy and is widely regarded as a conservative force on the Politburo. Before the plenum he spoke out for including leasing in a wide variety of methods to improve agricultural production. He said the approach to agriculture will include leasing, self-financing and greater democracy in rural life. The plenum abolished the giant `` Gosagroprom'' superministry in charge of agricultural policy, and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> interrupted its chief, <PERSON> Vsevolod </PERSON> <PERSON> Murakovsky </PERSON> who spoke out in favor of continuing the system in which all local regions are required to send a percentage of their harvest to central authorities. Showing his impatience with domination of local producers by the central bureaucracy, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> interrupted again when another speaker brought up the issue of the government orders. In a speech on Wednesday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> painted a bleak picture of Soviet agriculture, with chemically despoiled land, deliberate destruction of sound system prevalent in the 1920s, and massive investments gone sour. The situation is so bad that it will be years before the country can feed itself, he said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s detailed report on years of failed reforms made it clear that he believes nothing less than radical change will free Soviets from rationing of meat and cheese now found in many cities. His proposal to abolish a government superagency created in 1985 to oversee the country's farm sector was a tacit acknowledgement of the failure of even his early attempts to revitalize agriculture.
