<FIRST>r a AM-PesticidePollution     03-16 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pesticide Pollution,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Pesticide Pollution At Denver Arsenal Is Hurting Wildlife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Army report obtained by the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> says pesticide pollution at the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION> is harming and killing wildlife, and posing a threat to humans who may eat the tainted game. The report was based on a three-year study of the pollution's effect on animals and plants at the 27-square mile superfund cleanup site north of <LOCATION> Stapleton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, the newspaper said in Thursday's editions The report probably will determine the extent of the cleanup at the site, a federal official said Wednesday. The report was compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION> Englewood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, consulting firm hired by the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. It found that: _ The flesh of game such as deer, rabbits and pheasants contained contaminants in higher concentrations than <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> levels for safe human consumption. _ <ORGANIZATION> Grasshoppers </ORGANIZATION> eaten by waterfowl and raptors contained mercury and high levels of aldrin and dieldrin, pesticide components known to cause thinning of egg shells and weight loss in birds. _ Dangerous levels of dieldrin in prairie dogs. _ A minimum of 20,000 waterfowl died during the 1950s after landing on polluted ponds at the arsenal. `` Dead coyotes, owls and hawks found all over the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION> had significant concentrations of pesticides in tissues,'' the report said. The Army manufactured chemical weapons at the facility from 1942 through the 1960s. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> leased a portion of the arsenal for pesticide production through the early 1980s. Waste from both operations are known to have polluted groundwater, surface water and soil at the facility. Use of the old arsenal has been a subject of controversy. Federal and state officials, including Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON>, have suggested turning the land into a park or wildlife preserve. Health officials have warned, however, that extensive cleanup work must be completed in order for the animals to survive. If contaminated water and soil are left untreated, pollutants will continue to be absorbed by plants, ingested by insects and carried up the food chain to large game animals, they say. `` If they continue to eat in contaminated areas, the problem is only going to worsen,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Edson </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>'s project manager at the arsenal said Wednesday the report will have an impact. `` It looks like the study might drive the decisions regarding how clean it must be made,'' said <PERSON> Connally </PERSON> <PERSON> Mears </PERSON>. `` We'll pay particular attention to the implications from the study to determine what needs to be done to ensure protection of both public health and the environment.'' Army spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> said Wednesday the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> did n't want to comment because the report was still in draft form.
