<FIRST>r w AM-AutoInsurance     03-16 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Insurance,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims with Lawyers Claim More Injuries, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Auto accident victims with lawyers claim more neck and back injuries than those without legal assistance, an insurance industry study reported Thursday in speculating that lawyers drive up insurance costs. The study also said that, on average, one out of six accident victims hiring lawyers was steered to a particular doctor or clinic by the lawyer, and said that people represented by lawyers hire substantially more chiropractors, physical therapists and psychotherapists. The findings came from a study of 46,694 injury claims paid by 34 insurance companies in the spring and summer of 1987. Those companies sell nearly 60 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto insurance. The claims were made under five coverages: bodily injury liability, uninsured and underinsured motorists, personal injury protection and medical payment. `` States with high attorney involvement tend to have high auto injury costs, and states with low attorney involvement tend to have low auto injury costs,'' said the study conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> All-Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a group of insurance industry trade associations and companies. At the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, whose members are plaintiff attorneys in personal injury cases, spokeswoman <PERSON> Madeline </PERSON> <PERSON> Applebaum </PERSON> said no one had seen the study and she could not comment. The insurance group found that almost 45 percent of claimants hired lawyers, up from more than 31 percent in 1977. The group speculated that the ending of restrictions on advertising by lawyers in 1978 might have helped cause the increase. The average bodily injury claim payment increased 139 percent in those 10 years, well ahead of the 85 percent increase in the Consumer Price Index. After noting a 124 percent increase in the cost of medical care, the study said, `` Another possible reason for the large incurease in auto injury costs is that attorney involvement has increased 42 percent since 1977.''
</TEXT>
