<SECOND>AM-Whale Rescue,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fog Hampers California Whale Rescue Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Biologists stalking a 35-foot <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> gray whale lost the migrating beast in fog before they could cut away a tangle of fishing nets that could kill it, officials said Thursday. The northbound whale was spotted Tuesday off <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Point </PERSON> with netting wrapped around its flukes. Wildlife experts fear it will eventually drown, said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` We do n't know how much netting is trailing underwater. Eventually, the whale will probably tire out and die,'' said <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>. Biologists participating in the rescue estimated the whale was trailing about 70 feet of netting. A team of biologists from the Long Beach-based <ORGANIZATION> Whale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> followed the whale from <LOCATION> Dana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Crystal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cove </LOCATION> area off <LOCATION> Laguna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, trying several times to get close and cut away the nets. They lost it in fog near <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, 45 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` The whale is moving at a pretty good clip and the rescuers could n't catch up with it,'' said <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON>. Agent <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Sautter </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said it was extremely difficult to catch a whale moving in the water. `` By the time you get a small boat over there they go down again,'' <PERSON> Sautter </PERSON> said. `` It also stresses the animal and it may do more harm than good.'' Another <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> gray whale was reported ensnared in fishing nets early Thursday off Point Conception, 120 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Sautter </PERSON>. `` We are trying to get someone up there and free it,'' he said. Whales began migrating from the warmer waters in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> earlier this month and will continue their northward treks through May. `` Our real problem time is really next month and into May because the cow-calf pairs are the last to leave,'' said <PERSON> Sautter </PERSON>. `` The young frequently get separated and get into trouble.''
</TEXT>
