<FIRST>r w AM-SavingsBonds     03-16 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Savings Bonds,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savings Bonds Sales Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Savings Bonds declined in February for the first time in five months, falling 14.5 percent to $ 691 million, the government said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said sales fell $ 117 million from January but were still up $ 33 million, or 5 percent, from February 1988. Effective last Nov. 1 through April 30, bonds held five years or longer will earn an annual rate of 7.35 percent for the six months, up from 6.9 percent during the previous six months. As of Feb. 28, the total value of savings bonds held by Americans was $ 113.3 billion, up 8 percent from a year earlier. Sales for the first five months of fiscal 1989, which began Oct. 1, totaled $ 3.3 billion, up 11 percent from the same period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
