<SECOND>AM-Computer Spies,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Concludes German Spies Didn't Hurt National Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has tentatively concluded that a spy ring of West German computer hackers did not gain access to the types of secrets that would jeopardize <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s national security, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s chief spokesman, said he was not at liberty to discuss the specific computer networks the German hackers penetrated, what they learned in the process and what they passed on to the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. But, in breaking two weeks of official silence, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> no longer viewed the case as a serious threat to military security. `` Based on the information that we have thus far, and this is not complete ... our best judgment is that the computer hackers did not penetrate secure programs,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. The initial review of evidence assembled by American and West German authorities suggests the spy ring never gained access to the computer systems that contain classified secrets, he continued. `` All this is subject to change should new information turn up in the course of the investigation. But, to the best of our knowledge, it does not appear at this point that there was any compromise of classified information,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. The West German government broke up the computer espionage operation March 3, arresting three individuals and later disclosing that eight others were still under investigation. On March 6, a spokesman for the chief federal prosecutor in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Prechtel </PERSON>, told reporters the continuing investigation suggested `` the information obtained by the hackers does not appear to be that sensitive.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government, however, had declined until Thursday to say whether it agreed with that assessment. The West German ring was cracked in large measure through the work of a lone <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computer expert, an astronomer named <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoll </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stoll </PERSON> has said he observed the ring trying to break into about 450 computer banks, and that the hackers did gain access to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s general data bank, named <ORGANIZATION> Optimus </ORGANIZATION>, as well as computers at several defense contractors and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> ARD </ORGANIZATION> television network has reported the hackers also tapped <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and `` Star Wars'' research computers. Citing unidentified sources, the network reported that three hackers handed over information from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> during a 1985 meeting with two <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. The TV network also reported that authorities believe the West German hackers were recruited by the Soviet intelligence agency in 1985 and `` were paid with cash and drugs.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, while breaking the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government's silence on the matter, declined to confirm precisely which computer databanks the hackers penetrated. `` No classified programs. That's really about all I can say on the subject,'' he replied. `` I do n't have any information that would imply there was any involvement by Americans,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> added.
</TEXT>
