<HEAD>Soviets Arriving for Nuclear Inspection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has notified the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that two 10-member teams of nuclear weapon inspectors will conduct `` short-notice inspections'' at <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> facilities starting Friday, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Thursday. The inspections, authorized by the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty ratified last year, will be the eighth and ninth such inspections of the 20 allowed each side this year. `` In accordance with the INF Treaty, the teams will announce which two sites they intend to inspect on Friday morning. And the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> will then transport them to the sites where they will begin the 24-to-32 hour inspections,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. The INF Treaty requires the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to cease production, and destroy all existing stocks, of nuclear missiles with a range of roughly 300 to 3,000 miles.
