<HEAD>Judge: Christian Group Has Right To Distribute Literature On Beach</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The town of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> agreed Thursday to allow a <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> group to pass out its tracts on the beaches during spring break after a federal judge defended the rights of the evangelists. Ministers had sued the resort town after an official sent them a letter advising that distribution of the literature would violate an anti-soliciting ordinance. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Filemon </PERSON> <PERSON> Vela </PERSON>, however, advised the town at a hearing that `` the public beaches are a public forum'' and that handing out religious literature was protected by the Constitution. Ministers <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' Street Reach Ministries sued here Tuesday after receiving a letter from <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Becher </PERSON>, public works director for the island. In the Feb. 3 letter to <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Belcher </PERSON> wrote, `` I interpret preaching the word of God as soliciting and -LRB- it -RRB- therefore falls under these ordinances.'' After <PERSON> Vela </PERSON>'s remarks, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> officials agreed to leave the ministers alone as long as they did not solicit funds on the beaches, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cunningham </PERSON>, town attorney. <PERSON> Vela </PERSON> said the agreement obviated the need for a restraining order against the town. Attorney <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Sekulow </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> group, said, `` It's unfortunate that it did have to come to court, because frankly all that was involved was the distribution of free religious literature and sharing <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> on the beaches of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON>, youth minister at <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>'s non-denominational Word of <ORGANIZATION> God </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, said the group wants to provide an alternative to companies promoting beer and condoms to the 200,000 to 300,000 students expected to visit the island 25 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION> during the month of March.
