<HEAD>Senate Democrats Privately Debate Legislative Agenda</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats debated in private on Thursday over a broad agenda for the 101st <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that pledges not to `` oppose the -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB- administration automatically, but to propose new policies and pursue them cooperatively.'' A 10-page draft `` agenda for action'' that served as the basis for the closed-door discussion shied away from specifics on many of the major issues confronting <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. It omitted any mention of the possible use of higher taxes to reduce the deficit, and skipped over details of any effort to resolve the savings and loan crisis. At the same time, it called for enactment of a lengthy list of legislation that seemed certain to spark combat with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, ranging from a hike in the minimum wage to a program of national volunteer service, strengthened environmental enforcement and widespread, affordable health care. It also called for an expanded commitment to education, research and development, agriculture and trade. `` It is not a political platform,'' said the draft that produced debate two days in a row at closed party caucuses just off the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. `` Neither can it include every item of interest to every senator, or accommodate every difference of emphasis and viewpoint.'' Democrats initially hoped to make a public release of the material on Friday, but officials indicated the date was likely to slip past the two-week Easter recess that begins at the end of the week. They said some changes had been made in the draft, a copy of which was made available to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, but declined to discuss them. Sen. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Daschle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, who was in charge of the effort to produce the agenda, said the discussion had been a `` healthy debate,'' that centered in part on the concerns by some senators that the draft was short on specifics. Other senators said Democrats might try to come up with a second, more concrete set of promposals later in the year. The proposed agenda grew out of a commitment by Sen. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, the newly elected majority leader, to consult widely with other Democrats and produce a set of legislative guidelines for Democrats to adhere to during the two-year <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that convened in January. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Daschle </PERSON> to coordinate the effort, and the result of <PERSON> Daschle </PERSON>'s conversations with <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senators was reflected in the draft agenda that he and the majority leader presented to the 55-member <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> caucus on Wednesday and Thursday. `` With this report we offer the president our hand,'' said the draft. `` We do not expect the administration to accept every item. We seek only cooperation and progress.'' It says that the job for Democrats in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is `` not to oppose the administration automatically, but to propose new policies and pursue them cooperatively.'' The draft agenda committed Democrats to ensuring a prosperous economy, protecting the national security, preserving the environment and defending `` essential family values,'' and outlined specific legislation to accomplish each of those goals. But on many of the most contentious issues, Democrats shied away from specifics in their draft. `` It is imperative that we significantly reduce budget and trade deficits,'' they said. But the only two specific steps mentioned for deficit reduction are a demand for `` realistic economic projections'' and insisting on `` accurate calculations of budget numbers.'' When it comes to the faltering savings and loan industry, the draft agenda called for taking legal action against those who committed fraud and abuse and urged unspecified `` tough new regulatory reform.''
