<FIRST>r w AM-CancerResearch     03-16 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cancer Research,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Cancer Studies Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY B. DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 University researchers in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> reported results of two separate experiments Thursday which could someday lead to new drugs to use against cancer. _ <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> researchers reported what they said was the first stimulation of the immune system in mucous-lined tissues against a cancer-causing chemical This could lead to inoculations that could keep some cancer-causing chemicals and toxins from being absorbed by the body. _ A team from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> reported tests of a complex compound that, when given with certain steroid drugs, is up to 1,000 times more powerful than current drugs in inhibiting the growth of small capillary blood vessels that tumors need for growth Without the steroids, the compound is a powerful stimulator of capillary growth, which is necessary for ovulation, menstruation and growth of the placenta in women and wound repair in both sexes. Whether suppressing capillary growth is a fruitful anti-cancer strategy has to await safe and effective suppressors, the <LOCATION> Harvard-Pennsylvania </LOCATION> group said. Both reports were published in the issue of Science magazine which is published Friday. Many body tissues exposed to the outside environment are lined with mucous, particularly the nose and mouth. If those tissues are invaded by a virus, a bacterially produced toxin or similar agent, which might produce a cold or other illness, they secrete antibodies. If the virus reappears, the antibodies bind to it and prevent its absorption, as is believed to happen with the viruses that cause colds. Vaccines such as the <PERSON> Sabin </PERSON> oral polio vaccine work, in part, by priming this secretory immune system, one of several in the body, to generate antibodies. But ordinary chemical molecules are generally too small to elicit such a response. At the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Silbart </PERSON>, a toxicologist who is a research fellow in pathology, and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keren </PERSON>, professor of pathology, bound a powerful cause of cancer in laboratory animals, 2-acetylaminofluorene or AAF, to the toxin produced by the cholera-causing bacterium Vibrio cholerae. They measured absorption into the bloodstream of a radioactive derivative of the AAF-toxin complex across the membrane of the intestines of rabbits immunized with the complex and compared that with the absorption of the same substance in a control group of rabbits immunized with an unrelated toxin. Absorption of <ORGANIZATION> AAF </ORGANIZATION> into the blood was more than twice in the control group as it was in the test group. The article said the results suggest `` that oral vaccines against carcinogens and toxicants could be developed for humans.'' As to the absorption after immunization, `` Ideally, we'd like to eliminate it completely,'' said <PERSON> Keren </PERSON> in an interview. `` In nature you're going to be exposed to chronic low doses and you might see'' reductions of a factor of 100 or so. `` This is the first hard evidence that you can make the secretory -LRB- immune -RRB- response ... and that it can interfere'' with absorption of the carcinogen, but `` many years of work'' are needed to produce a useful vaccine, he said. The Harvard-Pennsylvania team, led by <PERSON> Judah </PERSON> <PERSON> Folkman </PERSON>, professor of surgery at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, noted that heparin, a complex chemical used as an anti-coagulant drug, has been found to promote capillary growth by itself and to inhibit that growth when combined with certain steroids. Not all investigators have been able to find the anti-capillary effect, and the <LOCATION> Harvard-Pennsylvania </LOCATION> team wrote that `` potent inhibition of angiogenesis -LRB- capillary formation and growth -RRB- ... is also subject to the variable activity of different heparin preparations.'' Those preparations have been `` nonuniform and heterogeneous in composition, molecular size, structure, position of subtituents and sequence. This heterogeneity probably accounts'' for the variability in findings of the effects of heparin. The team used beta-cyclodextrin tetradecasulfate, a doughnut-shaped compound made up of seven repeating units of a substance called glucopyranose with two sulfate groups attached to each unit. The `` hole in the doughnut'' is necessary to carry the steroid drug to the surface of the target cells, the investigators theorized. Tested in chick embryos and rabbit corneas, the activity of beta-cyclodestrin tetradecasulfate showed vessel-suppressing activity `` 100 to 1,000 times that of commercially available heparin,'' fully reproducible from one preparation to another. In the corneas, the substance used with cortexolone `` decreased vessel growth to 18 percent of that of untreated control eyes,'' measured according to vessel length, and to 8 percent according to the density of blood vessels. By itself, beta-cyclodestrin tetradecasulfate stimulated vessel length to 164 percent of untreated controls.
</TEXT>
