<HEAD>Marshals Defend Against Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Marshals </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday a critical audit commissioned by Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> did n't accurately represent the agency's operations. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Marshals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said the finding that the agency's financial management system was only `` marginally adequate'' was `` not supported by the specific findings in the report.'' `` That language is taken from their coversheet, their generalization of their findings,'' <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said. He said the study actually found that `` files and paperwork were not located in a form or fashion the auditors thought was desirable.'' `` That did n't suggest there was anything unaccounted for,'' <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said. Neither <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> nor the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would release the audit, which was disclosed in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> offered a point by point rebuttal of the findings reported in the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, saying: `` to the extent that the auditors found nothing to suggest failure in meeting our operational requirements, nothing suggesting fraud or misuse of funds is a very positive result.'' `` An audit is an exercise to find fault. They found fault but what they found we think was of minimal signficance to our principal mission,'' he said. `` We consider the entire audit a declaration that the <ORGANIZATION> Marshals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is in extremely good shape except for the fact that some of the auditors who did the audit would like to see us with a larger bureaucracy.'' <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> cited a finding that the agency's procurement staff still had not begun efforts recoup overcharges by private security firms that were uncovered in a 1987 audit. The staff responsible for collecting the money overcharged by security firms in eight judicial disticts had postponed that effort while renegotiating contracts with private contractors hired to guard courthouses and prisons. `` It's not as matter of the money disappearing,'' <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said. `` The bills are in hand. We simply have to devote the contracts personnel to go back and pursue the collections which we will be doing.'' A finding that several of the agency's small airplanes used for hauling prisoners were not designed for that purpose `` was a particularly good example of the auditors reflecting bad information,'' <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said. Seven of the 13 small planes are being refurbished so they can be used to transport prisoners, <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> gave the <ORGANIZATION> Marshals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> the surplus aircraft last year, he said. The audit also found the Marshals' Service has not conducted adequate background checks of people hired to protect courthouses or guard prisoners. <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said private security firms are responsible for checking the backgrounds of guards it furnishes under contracts. Off-duty policemen hired to guard prisoners in hospitals are usually provided by local police departments, he said. `` It is n't a matter of people walking in off the street in police uniforms,'' he said. The gaurds are hired as result of `` formal contacts with official representatives'' of local police departments. The audit also found the agency once leased an airplane for $ 10,000 to transport director <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> and two other people from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> after a Marshals' Service plane broke down. <PERSON> Boyle </PERSON> said the plane was leased because <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and seven other senior officials could not have traveled by commercial airlines in time to attend the ceremony.
