<HEAD>Forest Service Say Sales From National Forests Netted $388 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government lost money on timber sales in more than two-thirds of the nation's 120 national forests during fiscal 1988, but still recorded an overall profit of $ 388.7 million, the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. In its second annual accounting of the costs and benefits of national forest timber sales, the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said its timber sales program made a profit of $ 442.2 million in 46 national forests, mostly in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the parts of Southeast. The logging program in the other 74 national forests lost a total of $ 53.7 million. Officials said more than 80 percent of the 12.6 billion board feet of timber harvested from national forests was taken from forests where revenues exceeded expenses. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, chief economist and vice president for resource planning and economics for the <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, said the report reinforces the society's view that the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s timber sales program is an `` environmentally destructive federal boondoggle.'' The Wilderness Society has been urging the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for several years to halt timber sales in national forests where expenses exceed revenue. The society contends that logging activities in such forests usually are the most damaging to the environment, since the trees tend to be located in the most unapproachable areas. In the rugged Southern Appalachian national forests, for example, the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said it lost $ 8.34 million on timber sales in fiscal 1988, an increase of $ 1.56 million from the previous year.
