<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Alaska Oil Exploration Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee on Thursday approved legislation that would allow oil exploration in the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION> but no drilling leases until after a government-financed study considering alternative energy sources. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> defeated an amendment offered by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON>, D-Colo., and <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Bumpers </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>., that would have delayed any possibility of oil exploration until a comprehensive energy conservation plan was submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> The energy plan language the committee accepted was presented by Sen. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>, R-Ore., and is identical to a compromise included in the same legislation last session While the previous bill also passed the energy committee, it failed to get to either the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor for a vote. The House has not taken up the measure yet this session. Opponents say the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> needs to have a plan for saving energy and finding alternatives to fossil fuel before it starts drilling for more oil, especially in a part of the country that is the breeding ground for one of the largest herds of migrating caribou in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and home to many other forms of wildlife. Supporters say oil exploration is necessary for national security. `` The closest we've come to nuclear war is in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> to protect our oil supply,'' said <PERSON> Hatfield </PERSON>. But he also spoke of a need for conservation, saying: `` No matter what the actual oil find in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, our national energy needs will require the development of alternative sources of energy. ... The spotlight trained on energy conservation efforts during the late'70s and early'80s has suffered a blackout.'' His amendment requires the departments of interior and energy, the Council on Environmental Quality and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> to prepare a national energy plan within 15 months after the bill is enacted. The plan must consider all potential energy sources and projected energy demands. Bids for oil leases could be taken while the study was under way, but no leases could be granted until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had had six months to study the report. The amendment also requires that the energy secretary establish a grant program to promote research, development and marketing of conservation techniques and alternative fuels. This program would get its money from the sale of oil found in the refuge. Sen. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D-La., called the <LOCATION> Bumpers-Wirth </LOCATION> proposal `` a killer amendment'' because it not only said oil exploration must be delayed until the energy plan was established, but that pursuing oil exploration would take another act of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> applauded the passage of the bill, saying the refuge may provide as much as 1 million barrels of oil to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> every day for as long as 30 years. The institute said more than 6 billion barrels have been produced at <LOCATION> Prudhoe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> since 1977 when drilling began there. Another 3 billion barrels are still believed to be available from <LOCATION> Prudhoe </LOCATION>. Oil companies want to start drilling at the refuge, which is just east of <LOCATION> Prudhoe </LOCATION>, so that oil will continue to flow from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> when the fields in <LOCATION> Prudhoe </LOCATION> are dry.
