<FIRST>r w AM-StayingSingle     03-16 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Staying Single,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Black Women Have Less Financial Incentive than White Women
to Marry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Black women are spending twice as many years living without a spouse than white women, at least in part because they believe they have less financial incentive to get married or stay married, a researcher says. An ongoing study of the economic and other disparities between races determined that black women are catching up financially with black men at a rate much faster than the pay of white women is approaching that of white men. The researcher, <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> sociology professor <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>, said one obvious reason for that is that wages paid black men lag well behind those paid white men. Still, he said, black women often develop the perception it is not in their best financial interest to get or stay married and because of that, they are waiting longer than white women to marry and are divorcing more frequently. `` Black women, when they look around and think about getting married, see that the pool of black men with high earnings is relatively small,'' <PERSON> Farley </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Wednesday. `` This gives them less of a financial incentive to get married or to remain married.'' Another reseacher, interviewed Thursday, did not dispute <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>'s finding but said the underlying factor behind it was most likely years of wage discrimination against black men that has resulted in black women having a longer tradition of having to work than white women Because of that, black women have a greater sense of financial independence, even if their wages are lower than those paid white women, said <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, director of the women's studies program at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> `` I think it's true that black men's low income affects the marriage rate of black women,'' <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> said. `` But it's overly cynical to say money is the only thing that gets one married.'' <PERSON> Farley </PERSON> said that in 1987, 30 percent of black women between the ages of 15-44 were living with a husband, compared with 52 percent in 1960 and 70 percent in 1950. Fifty-five percent of white women in that age bracket were living with a husband in 1987, down from 69 percent in 1960 and 70 percent in 1950. Several studies have noted complaints by black women that there is a shortage of black males in the marriage pool, but <PERSON> Farley </PERSON> said that when numbers alone are considered, those complaints are unfounded. `` There have been nearly equal numbers of black men and women within each age group since the 1970s, so there is not an absolute shortage of black men,'' he said. `` However, the persistently high unemployment rate and limited earnings of black men may lead some black women to delay marriage and, correspondingly, some black men may hesitate to take on the financial obligations of a family.'' Data from 1975-80 indicate that black women on average will spend 16 years of their 73-year life span with a spouse while white women can expect to spend 33 of their expected 77 years with a mate, <PERSON> Farley </PERSON> said. Higher homicide and incarceration rates among blacks likely contribute to those numbers, <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>'s data were compiled as part of a larger study he is conducting to determine why civil rights programs designed to bring blacks and other minorities on an equal economic footing with whites have failed to do so. Working with data from the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> and other sources, <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> determined that the average annual earnings of black women and white women are close _ $ 13,800 for black women in 1987 and $ 14,700 for white women. But earnings of black women are much closer to those of black men, who made $ 18,500 in 1987, while white women still lag well behind white men, who made $ 28,000 in 1987. `` Relative to the incomes of their potential mates, black women are doing better than white women,'' <PERSON> Farley </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
