<HEAD>Government Shake-up Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> on Thursday accepted the resignations of all 54 ministers in his Cabinet, preparing for a government shake-up in a political crisis over a bank scandal. The Socialist government also proposed a law allowing more representation for smaller parties and raising the parliamentary majority required to form a government, making governing coalitions more likely. The main conservative party said the law is aimed at keeping it out of power. The Cabinet reshuffle will be the second since the $ 200 million fraud, forgery and embezzlement scandal involving a fugitive Greek banker broke five months ago, leading to the resignations of eight Cabinet ministers. It will also be <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s 16th Cabinet reshuffle in eight years. Government sources indicated <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> intends to use the reshuffle to purge the Socialist government of ministers implicated in the scandal and attract waning support for his governing <ORGANIZATION> Panhellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> PASOK </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s party has come under heavy fire for its handling of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crete </ORGANIZATION> scandal, in which <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> and senior government officials have been accused of taking payoffs. A statement issued by government spokesman <PERSON> Sotiris </PERSON> <PERSON> Kostopoulos </PERSON> said the new Cabinet would be appointed and sworn in Friday. The draft electoral law is to be submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Friday, and lawmakers are to vote on it within the next few weeks. The main conservative opposition <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> accused the government of trying to hamper its efforts to win a clear majority in the upcoming June elections. `` The government has admitted that it has ceased to contest power and its exclusive concern is how to prevent us from acquiring an overall majority,'' <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Constantine </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitsotakis </PERSON> said in a statement. Interior Minister <PERSON> Akis </PERSON> <PERSON> Tsochatzopoulos </PERSON> said the proposed electoral law would allow smaller parties to have more seats in the 300-member single-chamber <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. According to <PERSON> Kostopoulos </PERSON>, the premier asked his ministers to resign in order to go ahead with the reshuffle. `` All the ministers have been asked and verbally submitted their resignations,'' the spokesman said. Banker-publisher <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Koskotas </PERSON>, 34, was indicted in the scandal and fled <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> on Nov. 6. He was arrested in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where he is jailed awaiting a decision on extradition requested by <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. The banker has alleged that <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> and other senior Socialist officials received millions of dollars in payoffs and authorized plans to loot millions from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crete </ORGANIZATION> while he was its chairman. The draft bill proposes a new proportional system for electing deputies and increases the margin needed to elect a government from 45 percent of the vote, the previous level, to about 48 percent, an electoral analyst said. The analyst said on condition of anonymity that the new law would open the way for coalition governments. Under the country's present reinforced proportional system, large political parties are heavily favored in seat distributions. In the 1985 elections, the system gave <ORGANIZATION> PASOK </ORGANIZATION> 45.8 percent of the vote and 161 seats. New Democracy received 40.8 percent and 126, the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> got 9.89 percent and 12 seats, and the Eurocommunists polled 1.84 percent and one seat. Political defections have left <ORGANIZATION> PASOK </ORGANIZATION> with 154, the conservatives with 111 and the Communists with nine. The Eurocommunists retain their one seat and the rest are independents.
