<HEAD>Metzenbaum: Corporations Shouldn't Make Older Workers Sign Away Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Older workers have been coerced into signing away their rights as corporations try to get rid of better-paid employees in favor of younger, lower-paid newcomers, three early retirees told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing Thursday. `` It is difficult for me to believe that an employee who works in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> today ... who has been a loyal and successful worker for one employer for a long time, can be fired from his or her job and forced to sign away their rights under the law,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION> `` If I had known more about the equal rights laws, and had known on Dec. 31, 1983 that my replacement was 28 years old, I would not have signed anything,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee on Labor. The subcommittee, headed by Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, is considering Metzenbaum-sponsored legislation to forbid employers from asking older workers to waive their rights under the law as a condition of taking advantage of early retirement incentives. `` Three-fourths of employers do n't use waivers. Why do the other 25 percent have to?'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said. A <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> survey of 60 `` Fortune 100'' companies showed 24 percent of the companies that had early retirement incentives required workers to sign waivers in order to get beefed-up benefits. The use of waivers has tripled over the past 10 years, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Delfico </PERSON> told the committee. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> told the panel no new law is needed because of regulatory action taken in 1987 aimed at accomplishing the same goal. But the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> survey showed 1987-88 was a peak period for the use of waivers. The companies surveyed by <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, reported they used the waivers `` to avoid having terminated employees file claims and lawsuits after receiving enhanced benefits from exit incentive programs,'' <PERSON> Delfico </PERSON> testified. <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON> said he was one year from being vested in his pension plan when the car dealership for which he was service manager fired him after 12 years on the job. In a New Year's Eve meeting, the dealership offered six months' severance pay in exchange for a signature on a release of all claims, <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON> said. `` I was given no reason for my termination. They had already hired someon in my place,'' <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON> told the panel. `` I was told I had to sign the release letter immediately in order to get the severance pay. `` I asked to take the documents home to review them, but they said no. I asked for time to talk to an attorney, but they said I did n't need to because the dealership's lawyers had already gone over everything,'' he said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, a draftsman, said he was told by his manager at <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> there was a `` 99 percent sure chance you will be laid off'' if an early retirement offer was refused. `` I had only seven working days to make a decision,'' <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, said he was offered a year's salary if he signed documents waiving his rights under the Age Discrimination Employment Act. `` What happened to me should n't happen to anybody,'' he said. A law partner in a national firm testified that <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>'s proposal could hurt companies that have n't discriminated `` The real effect of -LRB- the bill -RRB- in individual cases would be to create a system whereby disputes could not be settled without the intervention of <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> or a court, and would put an end to many internal company grievance programs that have been developed over the years to deal with employee complaints,'' said attorney <PERSON> Cathie </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shattuck </PERSON>, who's represented both employers and disgruntled employees.
