<HEAD>Party Adopts Agricultural Reform, Elects Congress Members</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 14 grafs with more Ligachev quotes, other detail;
picks up 12th pvs `Soviet television...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Communist Party approved sweeping agricultural reforms Thursday, giving farmers long leases on state land to produce more of the meat, fruit and fresh vegetables for which housewives now wait in line for hours. An average Soviet citizen now consumes about half as much meat and fruit as an American, but up to double the sugar and potatoes. <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, the ruling Politburo's man in charge of farm policy, promised the people diets `` up to generally recognized standards of nutrition'' by 1996. `` We are not promising something that we can not achieve,'' he told his first news conference with foreign reporters. `` We will be able to change the food situation for the better.'' The meeting of the 300-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also elected the party's 100 members to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION>, a new 2,550-seat legislative body that will meet for the first time in the spring. President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was among them. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had proposed that farmers be given long-term leases on land so they would become more efficient. He also urged that they be allowed to decide what to plant on the land rather than having the bureaucracy decide. Western analysts have said the new system will do little good unless lease-holders are allowed to choose which crops to plant, set their own prices and make other decisions. <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said leases could be signed for any period of more than five years and be passed on succeeding generations of a family. He said no one would be forced to lease land and that the giant state and collective farms would remain the backbone of the Soviet agricultural system. `` Radical changes in rural life and production relations should be carried out on a purely voluntary basis ... without any kind of force or repressive methods,'' said <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>, 68, who is widely regarded as a conservative force in the Politburo. Setting targets for leasing would only encourage strong-arm tactics to fulfill the plans, he said. In statements at the meeting, leasing was only one of many methods for improving production. He said the new approach to agriculture also would include self-financing, and greater democracy in rural life. State and collective farms still will dominate agriculture, he said. Some Soviet press reports have come close to advocating they be scrapped, but <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> said none of the 12 Politburo members favor it. `` Any proposal that leads to abolishing state and collective farms has no foundation whatsoever,'' he declared. Even when land is leased to individuals and groups, he said, state and collective farms will oversee production, `` proceeding from the needs and possibilities of society.'' Soviet television showed an hour-long report on the meeting, including speeches by local and Moscow-based officials echoing <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s calls for agriculture. The meeting abolished the giant superministry in charge of agricultural policy, and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> interrupted its chief, <PERSON> Vsevolod </PERSON> <PERSON> Murakovsky </PERSON>, who favored the traditional system in which all local regions are required to send a percentage of their harvest to central authorities. The television, breaking with its ususal practice, cut off its report before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> gave his final statement to the plenum. Ususally <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s statements in televised forums constitute the main part of the TV report. In a nearly two-hour speech Wednesday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> painted a devastating picture of Soviet agriculture, with chemically spoiled land, investments gone sour and destruction of systems prevalent in the 1920s. He said food shortages were inadmissible. `` The shortage of food creates social tension and generates not merely criticism but actual discontent.'' He said conditions in villages in some regions were so bad that emigration to the cities had reached a `` critical level.'' When <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> forced agricultural collectivization in the 1930s on a populace that was 80 percent agrarian, millions of peasants were deported to <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> and other remote regions or fled to cities. Catastrophic famine ensued. Ever since, farmers working for state-owned farms have generally delivered their yields to market at fixed prices to meet quotas set by the state bureaucracy.
