l thought out _ initiatives that might well make the headlines, but might not be very good for the health of the country.'' Asked about the <ORGANIZATION> Bush-Quayle </ORGANIZATION> campaign's acknowledged management of the daily news, packaging events and keeping the candidates away from reporters to keep from cluttering the canned message, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he was not talking about campaigns but added: `` You've got a certain message you want to get across.'' In his speech, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he was criticizing `` the way frantic efforts to gain press attention and produce sound bites can distort our political process by elevating form over substance, and image over reality.'' As to the blistering press reports about his own background that percolated throughout the campaign, the vice president said he probably benefited from it in the long run. He said the intense scrutiny was to be expected because he had been a little-known senator outside his home state of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> picked him for a running mate. `` You're an open target to criticism by your opposition. That is the way we conduct our campaigns,'' he said. `` It's healthy to see how one musters the scrutiny. I believe I have emerged a stronger and better person because of it. It's an experience that had a meaningful purpose for me as being the vice president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.''
