<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem gunners blasted <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s port Thursday, setting a cargo ship and a warehouse afire in fierce battles with Christian forces around the capital. No casualties were reported. Artillery duels in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and in the mountains above the capital coincided with a nationwide strike staged by Moslems to mourn victims of the previous week of fighting, which police said left 49 people killed and 161 wounded. A Syrian official was quoted as saying an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> committee has canceled a third meeting between rival Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinets </ORGANIZATION> to end the violence. A police spokesman said Moslem gunners blasted the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> port with 25 rockets, setting fire to a cargo ship that tried to return from open waters during a lull in the fighting. The spokesman identified the stricken vessel as `` The Angie Wipp'' and said he could not give any details about its flag, owners or what kind of cargo it carried. One of the port's warehouses also took a direct rocket hit during the attacks, said the spokesman, who can not be further identified under standing regulations. Christian gunners fired a barrage of 155mm howitzer fire at the Moslem residential districts of <PERSON> Sabra </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Kasskass </LOCATION> abutting <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION>, said a police spokesman Sniper fire and occasional grenade blasts crackled across the ruins of the old commercial district. The police spokesman said the new hostilities in <LOCATION> Souk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el-Gharb </LOCATION>, 15 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, erupted shortly before sundown between Christian army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s forces, which hold the town, and Druse fighters on nearby hills. The town commands a network of mountain roads leading from Druse territory to the Christian heartland north and northeast of the capital. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s forces appeared to be following through with his stated intention to drive <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s 40,000 troops out of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. Militiamen of Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> are backed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. The Christian-run Ad-Diyar newspaper on Thursday quoted an unidentifed Syrian official as saying that <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> `` has not yet taken a decision to retaliate against Gen. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> ... But if <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> should continue his provocations, retaliation will be decisive.'' The official was quoted as saying Arab League peace talks will not be held. The fighting was sparked by a March 6 air-and-sea blockade <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> clamped on illegal harbors run by Moslem militias south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The blockade angered <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>, whose party runs two illegal port facilities. <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> vowed to bombard the Christian-run <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> port as long as the blockade of Druse harbors was maintained. <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s commerical sea traffic was virtually halted and <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, the nation's only air gateway, has been shut since Saturday. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, 53, heads the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> cabinet that has been vying for legitimacy with acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>' Moslem cabinet. The rival governments have been in place since <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> failed to elect a successor to President <PERSON> Am