<HEAD>Federal Judge Rules Utah Must Allow Sweat Lodges For Indian Inmates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A two-year legal battle over the state's refusal to allow ceremonial sweat lodges for Indian inmates at <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> ended Thursday when a federal judge ruled the ban is unconstitutional Applause broke out in the packed courtroom and American Indians from several different tribes chanted and pounded drums outside after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> struck down the ban in a bench ruling on motions for summary judgment. `` I'm grateful. The words are kind of hard to come by at this time because the feeling is so good,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roybal </PERSON>, an <PERSON> Assiniboine </PERSON> <PERSON> Sioux </PERSON> who, as a <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> prison inmate in March 1987, initiated the lawsuit with five other inmates. `` What this thing is all about is us trying to help our people to help themselves,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> had contended the sweat lodge, which tribal officials contend is central to purification and ceremonial rites dating back 40,000 years, threatened security because the lodge must be dark and enclosed. But <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> cited two <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings and the success of sweat lodges in 19 other state prison systems and two federal penitentiaries in rejecting arguments that the small willow and canvas structures posed a security risk. The judge said the prohibition was unreasonable and resulted in `` the Native American religion not being accommodated to the extent other religions are.'' `` The sweat lodge will simply be another chapel located within the prison,'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, an attorney representing the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said guards could monitor ceremonies and prison officials could impose limitations such as searches and requirements that the lodge be dismantled after each service. `` The record is clear that 19 other states and the federal prison system accommodate these sweat lodges without risk to security,'' <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON> said. Telephone messages left at the office of <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Tesch </PERSON>, the associate <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> attorney general who defended the case for the state, were not immediately returned. The <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> was one of several groups that provided legal or moral support to the inmates' cause. The Native American Rights Fund and the giant <ORGANIZATION> Navajo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION> also joined the plaintiffs in the lawsuit, while the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, representing pastors from six denominations, urged Gov. <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Bangerter </PERSON> to intervene on the inmates' behalf. Prison officials had earlier offered to allow a modified sweat lodge equipped with a window and mechanical heating, instead of the required heated rocks, but plaintiffs' attorney <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> called the suggestion `` blasphemous.'' <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> concurred, telling Associate Utah Attorney General <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Tesch </PERSON>, at one point, `` It's like saying to a Christian you can have a ceremony but do n't mention Christ.'' Attorneys for the <ORGANIZATION> Navajo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION>, which manages sweat lodge programs for 500 inmates in federal and state systems, argued that the ceremonies are vital to rehabilitation. The sweat lodge provides a link between the incarcerated Indian inmate and his tribe, and the program administered by the Navajos offers drug and alcohol counseling in addition to spiritual guidance, said Navajo lawyer <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergen </PERSON>.
