<HEAD>Economic Reformer Becomes Premier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ante </PERSON> <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> took office as premier Thursday and promised market-oriented reforms to rescue <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> from an economic decline that began with the death of President <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> in 1980. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON>, a successful businessman, said in his inaugural speech a free-market economy is the `` ultimate achievement of mankind, for which no alternative has yet been found.'' He also said `` there is no solution to the economic crisis without the strengthening of political democracy in the country,'' and advocated creation of `` a new modern socialist system.'' A new Cabinet, much trimmer than before, also was sworn in. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON>'s government has 19 ministers, compared to 29 under <PERSON> Branko </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>, who resigned Dec. 30 because his government could not resolve the economic crisis. This Balkan nation of 23 million must undergo `` fundamental change'' in order achieve economic revival, <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> said. Inflation has reached an annual rate of 346 percent, and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> owes $ 21 billion to foreign creditors. Labor unrest and ethnic conflict have become chronic. Much of the recent ethnic trouble has involved the southern province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, where ethnic Albanians form a majority of 90 percent. About 2,000 Albanian miners have been on strike in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> for nearly a month. The government raised the prices of gasoline and diesel fuel Thursday for the third time this year, by an average of 18.7 percent, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> reported. Yugoslavs, whose average monthly pay is equivalent to $ 120, now must pay about $ 1.82 a gallon for gasoline. <PERSON> Markovic </PERSON> indicated he would seek closer links to the West, including greater economic cooperation with the European Economic Community. He advocates reshaping the banking system along Western lines, creating a stock market and ending state subsidies to companies that lose money. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> left the Soviet bloc in 1948 and is a founding member of the organization of nations that profess non-alignment. <PERSON> Mikulic </PERSON>'s government was the first to resign since the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> gained power after World War II. The new one is a mix of prominent politicians and technocrats, with only two ministers retaining the seats they occupied in <LOCATION> Mikulic </LOCATION>'s government. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Budimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Loncar </PERSON> and the defense minister, Gen. <PERSON> Veljko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadijevic </PERSON>, carry over but Defense Minister <PERSON> Dobrosav </PERSON> <PERSON> Culafic </PERSON> lost his job. <PERSON> Culafic </PERSON> was severely criticized for his handling of ethnic strife in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, the ancient heart of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. The remaining Serbian minority accuses the ethnic Albanians of discrimination. Gen. <PERSON> Petar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gracanin </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, is the new interior minister. <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> is the largest of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics, and <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> is an autonomous province within it.
