Dec. 5, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> was warned in a telephone call of a plot to bomb a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> airliner on a Frankfurt-U.S. flight during a two-week period in December. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued an `` intelligence alert'' that there might be a bomb attempt against a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> flight from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. Speaking on BBC-TV, <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said the Nov. 22 warning was sent to British airlines and airports, `` and of course the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> sent out their own warning to the American airlines.'' Asked about <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s statement that it did n't get the second warning until Jan. 17, <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said: `` There is no importance to it whatsoever. All it contained, virtually, was a color photograph of a cassette player and a few more unimportant pieces of information about how a bomb in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> had been constructed.'' He said the evidence that the bomb was placed aboard the plane at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> `` is very slender _ indeed all the evidence seems to point the other way.'' Asked if this meant he was blaming <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and West German authorities for failing to prevent the bombing, he said: `` I do n't make any comment about that That's for the investigators to decide and for the police.'' West German authorities say there is no firm evidence that the bomb was smuggled aboard in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Langendorf </PERSON>, chief of the <ORG