<HEAD>Score Federal Homeless Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates for the homeless and state and congressional housing experts on Wednesday criticized a federal panel charged with coordinating programs for the homeless, saying it had done virtually nothing to provide shelter for people without housing. The complaints about the <ORGANIZATION> Interagency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on the Homeless came at a joint hearing of two <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittees Wednesday, while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on housing introduced legislation its sponsors touted as the `` framework for a new national housing strategy.'' The litany of the council's failures began in the opening statement from Rep. <PERSON> Cardiss </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., who chairs the Government Activities and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee of the Committee on Government Operations `` It did n't hold meetings; it did n't set policy; it did n't coordinate federal programs; it did n't assess the needs of the homeless; it did n't recommend legislative changes or funding levels,'' said <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> It `` has failed almost completely to carry out the mandates set for it by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said. The council, established in 1987 by Title II of the McKinney Act, was given the responsibility to coordinate 20 new programs created by the law, monitor implementation of programs to the homeless, disseminate information about the programs to local governments and non-profit organizations serving the homeless, and help them develop new programs. But Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the Employment and Housing subcommittee and co-host of Wednesday's hearing said much of the information that homeless providers needed to apply for <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> funds was provided instead by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> NGA </ORGANIZATION> testified that after receiving numerous requests from the states for information, she had developed and updated three times a report on the status of programs under the <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON> act and related legislation. `` This publication contains the type of information the council should be disseminating,'' said <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>, chiding the council for not fulfilling `` its most basic mandate.'' Other witnesses said the council has failed to develop a complete staff, identify regional and field coordinators for programs and to clarify their duties, focused too much on the development of an electronic data base which homeless providers could not use, missed application deadlines, met only five times in 18 months, and produced only three monthly newsletters which contained useless information. The council, comprised of the heads or their designees of 10 Cabinet departments and five independent agencies, was headed by former housing secretary <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON> joked that the late <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON> had been seen more often on Capitol Hill than <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>. `` The duties with which the council is charged and its ability to carry them out must be brought into balance,'' said <PERSON> Cassandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, the council's former executive director. She said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> gave the council broad authority to develop programs and issue timetables, but not the power or resources to fulfill its mandate as described in <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> also recommended increasing the staff size and removing the council from under the administrative wing of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. She said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> had been resistant to sharing information on homelessness and virtually non-communicative. But <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> had provided administrative support to the council on a continuing basis, according to <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Stimpson </PERSON>, a deputy assistant housing secretary. He said the new administration has made homelessness one of its highest priorities and sees the council as `` an effective partner'' in addressing the problem.
