<SECOND>PM-Another Look: William Douglas, Adv 20,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday PMs, March 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Justice William O. Douglas Still Creates News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note anniversary of nomination is March 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifty years after his appointment to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and nine years after his death, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> remains a source of strong emotions in the state that shaped his life and his opinions. A critical documentary is scheduled to air next month, a major symposium on <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' career is planned in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, newly released government files reveal an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> scheme to discredit him, and the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> is considering the $ 100,000 purchase of his <LOCATION> Cascade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> hideaway for a public memorial. `` He is a compelling figure,'' said <PERSON> Walt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, whose documentary is to air on public television stations. `` The strength of his personality, the magnitude of his work. He was a person who saw a chance to do good and he did it.'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> was raised in poverty in <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION>, graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Whitman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION>, then taught high school here for two years before deciding in 1922 to become a lawyer. After serving as a law professor, lawyer, and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, he was nominated to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on March 20, 1939, by President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>. During 36 years on the high court, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> wrote a record 1,200 decision. He was a consistent supporter of abortion rights, First Amendment press protections, the environment, and the rights of criminal suspects, including the controversial Miranda decision. He used his position to oppose racism in schools and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> surveillance of Vietnam War protesters. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> recently overturned some affirmative action programs and will hear arguments on a case that could affect its landmark ruling legalizing abortion, so <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' views remain important, said H.G. <PERSON> Locke </PERSON>, organizer of the three-day <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> symposium scheduled to begin April 15. It will look at him as environmentalist, internationalist, civil libertarian and as a man. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>'s documentary, funded by the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> and produced by <ORGANIZATION> KYVE </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Yakima </LOCATION>, is scheduled to air in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> on April 17, the anniversary of <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' elevation to the court. It paints an unflattering portrait of <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' domineering mother and includes a scathing attack by his daughter, a discussion of his four marriages and his extramarital affairs, and interviews with former clerks who remember a driving perfectionist with little regard for their personal lives. What emerges is a picture of an egotistical, often unpleasant man, deeply scarred by early poverty, who rose primarily through his brilliance. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' daughter, <PERSON> Mildred </PERSON> <PERSON> Read </PERSON>, remembers a distant father with little time or use for his children. `` He did n't want to be talked to at breakfast because he was reading the paper. He did n't know what to do with us.'' His first clerk, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsberg </PERSON>, now a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, lawyer, recalled a stern boss: `` There was never a thought that I was overburdened.'' Ms. <PERSON> Read </PERSON> said her father had many affairs, moving on as he grew tired of each woman. <PERSON> Mercedes </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichholz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' second wife, whose lengthy affair with the justice broke up his first marriage after 29 years, said, `` His pursuit was so hot and heavy he wore me down.'' The <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> Oregonian reported in January that secret <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> files showed a pattern of misdeeds against <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> covering two decades and including former President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s attempt to impeach him in 1970. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> first began keeping tabs on him in the early 1950s, when former Gov. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Langlie </PERSON> wrote to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brownell </PERSON> that communists were regular guests at <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' summer home in La Push More than three decades later, state officials are once again concerned with one of <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' summer homes _ but this time they wish to honor the native son. A bill has been introduced in the House that seeks to purchase the alpine cabin that <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> built in 1965 near <LOCATION> Goose </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prairie </LOCATION>, about 25 miles east of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rainier </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Cascade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> report issued last Tuesday noted that turning the cabin site into a wilderness studies institute would be appropriate. `` Using the property would encourage an understanding of wilderness principles,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Rotell </PERSON> of the forest service. <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, the jurist's fourth wife, put the home up for sale last year. If it becomes a public memorial, she has agreed to return many of the furnishings and memorabilia to the chalet-style dwelling.
</TEXT>
