<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Oscar Telecast, Adv 20,0956</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, March 20 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reviving Oscar Magic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Critics say the Academy Awards telecast is showing its age. Producer <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> says that's the way it should be. In an attempt to keep the program's ratings from slipping, <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> will celebrate Oscar by reveling in its yesteryears. `` I'm restoring it, hopefully, to what it was in its glorious day,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said of the March 29 broadcast of the 61st Annual Academy Awards from the Shrine Auditorium in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The program will be shown at 9 p.m. EST by <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> and scenic designer <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Clausen </PERSON> will recreate a likeness of the Cocoanut Grove, the tropical nightclub where the Oscar dinner banquet was held in 1940. Famous movie couples will be seated at tables between the palm trees, and a bandstand will be on the stage. `` This is the ultimate variety show,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said. `` It's also the ultimate awards show that all the other awards show copy. So I have to make this a return to Oscar _ the way it was in the old days _ because now you have the Tonys, the <PERSON> Grammys </PERSON>, the American Music Awards, the People's Choice Awards. ... There's an awards show on every other week. `` The Oscars are supposed to be really glamorous and fun. It's the highest awards we give our royalty in this country I'm going to shock people with glamour and humor.'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> comes from a career filled with flamboyant spectacles. As the producer of the stage hit `` La Cage aux folles'' and the movies `` Grease,'' `` Ca n't Stop the Music'' and `` Where the Boys Are'84,'' his projects have rarely strayed from playfulness and overblown kitsch. He even held a black-tie dinner party in 1976 at the <LOCATION> Lincoln </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION> jail in a rundown section of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, to celebrate the opening of `` Murder by Death,'' which starred the late author <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> <PERSON> Capote </PERSON>. `` Whether people like me or do n't like me, or they like what I do or do n't like what I do, they know that I love <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> and I'm a big enthusiast for <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said. `` For the last four years, the orchestra has not been in the auditorium; they were at an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> studio five miles away and the music was piped in. But this is going to be a Broadway show. I insisted that the orchestra comes back, <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamlisch </PERSON> will be in the pit conducting, and ramps have been put over the orchestra pit so the people can run up the aisles. `` I am producing, really, two things: A live show for the people who are there _ like a <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> opening night _ and a television show which has a feeling of a Broadway opening night for the people at home.'' There will be no single program host this year. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON> will present the first statuette, <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> will present the last, and dozens of other stars will manage everything in between. Off-screen couples will be paired on-screen: <PERSON> Farrah </PERSON> <PERSON> Fawcett </PERSON> will appear with <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neal </PERSON>; <PERSON> Goldie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawn </PERSON> will be with <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Demi </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> will be escorted by her husband, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>. `` It's like ` Chariots of Fire.' It's like a relay race,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said. `` The presenters pass the torch to the next person.'' The telecast will honor awards presenters as well as winners. When <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Novak </PERSON> appear to hand out a trophy, the audience will be shown a clip from their work together in 1958's `` Vertigo.'' The awards show will be held on Wednesday this year, unlike the traditional Monday. The move is a result of both the preceding Easter holiday and a possible television technicians strike the following week. The show, <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said, will be seen in 164 countries, including the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for the first time. `` When it was announced that I was going to produce the show, people said, ` You've got to have more of the entrances and the arrivals. That's what people love to see.' ... The Oscars are about entrances. And so you will see great stars, through five generations of different age groups, making the entrances down these incredible staircases.'' One production number will focus on up-and-coming stars, and there will be a retrospective of film musicals. `` I wanted to bring my love of the musical movie to the Oscars,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said. `` Through lots of research, I realized that more movie stars made musicals in the'50s than any other decade. So I have put together this homage to the stars of the'50s musical, and you will see people like <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Grable </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> ... but also <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanza </PERSON>, <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ava </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayworth </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lana </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said complaints about past Oscar shows running past their allotted three hours miss the real point. `` You only realize how long it is if you're bored,'' he said. `` My answer is: You did n't ask how long ` <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Hur </PERSON>' was. Now that ` Lawrence of Arabia' is out again _ it's almost four hours long _ no one complains. If you're entertained, you do n't watch the clock.'' To keep the pace brisk, <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> winners with multiple trophy recipients _ as is common in technical awards _ will have one designated speaker. After 30 seconds of thank yous, the microphone will go dead and the camera will go to the next podium. Said <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>: `` They can talk as long as they want, but no one's going to hear it.''
