ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``New York Stories,'' ``The Adventures of Baron Munchausen''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Both movies were released March 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` New York Stories'' It began as an excellent idea: Take three top American filmmakers, set them out on the streets of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and loop their efforts into one full-length feature to celebrate those collective talents and the city they supposedly enshrined. Unfortunately, the idea does n't quite gel with `` New York Stories.'' The Touchstone Pictures release consists of three vignettes by <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Coppola </PERSON> and <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. But only Scorsese's `` Life Lessons'' is worth the cost of today's pricey movie tickets. It's also the first story in the production so one can easily slip out at its conclusion and skip the next two. `` Life Lessons'' also is the only vignette that truly mirrors the spirit and attitude of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> _ in this case, the downtown art world. It has a feel, texture and mood, thanks in part to the gritty and witty original screenplay by Bronx-born writer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, and the sensitive and probing lens of the celebrated cinematographer <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Almendros </PERSON>. It is a tight short story, a film exposition that develops as brilliantly and explosively as the giant canvases <PERSON> Almendros </PERSON> so wonderfully captures with his camera. <PERSON> Coppola </PERSON>'s `` Life Without <PERSON> Zoe </PERSON>,'' by contrast, is a shallow effort centered around the <LOCATION> Sherry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION>, the privileged few and the superficialities of Eurotrash. It has nothing really to do with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and in fact concludes in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s `` Oedipus Wrecks'' justifies itself as a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> story with a cameo by Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> and a throwaway line about how New Yorkers take certain bizarre happenings in their stride. <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolte </PERSON> gives a memorable performance in `` Life Lessons'' as <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON> `` The Lion'' Dolby, a brash, uncompromising, paternalistic artist whose brutal, expansive paintings match his passion and daring. He plays father to young women, taking them in as his art assistants and repaying them with `` life lessons.'' <LOCATION> Ahem </LOCATION>. His latest, <PERSON> Paulette </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Rosanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Arquette </PERSON> -RRB-, fancies herself an artist but has become smothered by <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON>. She's decided to leave him, but he lures her back with no strings attached. They resolve their relationship in a predictable way, but it's fun to watch. <PERSON> Arquette </PERSON> gives the same pouty, whiney, adenoidal performance she's given in such movies as `` The Big Blue.'' She's difficult to listen to, let alone watch. And she's dwarfed by <PERSON> Nolte </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Lionel </PERSON>. What a joy he is, from the opening shots of a paint-splattered cognac bottle, palette, cassette player and the artist himself staring at a blank canvas while Procul Harum's `` A Whiter Shade of Pale'' blasts through the studio, to his actual execution of the canvas. One feels his brush strokes, which surely no one lower than God is directing. `` Life Without Zoe'' offers little inspiration. Which is regrettable given the vision and talent <PERSON> Coppola </PERSON> has displayed in other works: `` Apocalpyse Now,'' `` The Godfather,'' `` Tucker.'' The story concerns 12-year-old <PERSON> Zoe </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> McComb </PERSON> -RRB- who lives alone at the Sherry cared for by the hotel's male staff. She is spoiled, precocious and chatty. Her father -LRB- <PERSON> Giancarlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Giannini </PERSON> -RRB- is a world famous flute player and stays on the road. Her mother -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Talia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shire </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is an emotionally frayed photographer with an adolescent sensibility. She, too, would rather be on the road than home. These people do n't seem to like each other or their daughter very much. But it's difficult to like any of them. <PERSON> Coppola </PERSON>'s characters are not real. One does not care about the distraught mother or the abandoned child, and the father comes across as a smarmy gigolo. There is a happy ending with a united family, but life would indeed be better without <PERSON> Zoe </PERSON>. The best thing about <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s `` Oedipus Wrecks'' is the title. After that, it's all down hill. The movie is only for those diehard <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> fans who get their jollies with endless jokes about the much-maligned Jewish mother, and who think that sitting with an analyst is a hip thing to do. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> plays a 50-year-old nebish who wants to marry the unobtainable WASP -LRB- <PERSON> Mia </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrow </PERSON> -RRB-. But mom's not too keen on this arrangement. Borrowing from his `` Purple Rose of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> employs an outlandish and bizarre trick that virtually leaves Mom in the sky. <PERSON> Mae </PERSON> <PERSON> Questal </PERSON> is wonderful as the mother, and <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kavner </PERSON> _ the <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgenstern </PERSON> of TV's `` Rhoda'' _ is more Jewish than <PERSON> Jewish </PERSON> as the nice Jewish girl who gets the nice Jewish boy with a little help from Tarot, witch doctors, voodoo and tea leaves. The <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Rollins </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Joffe </PERSON> production was produced by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenhut </PERSON> and is rated PG.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` The Adventures of Baron Munchausen'' <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Hieronymus </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchausen </PERSON> was a German soldier and adventurer who lived in the 18th century. He also was a master prevaricator whose tales would shrivel <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunyan </PERSON>'s to munchkin size. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON>, a founding member of the irreverent <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Python </PERSON> troupe, has taken this legendary liar and made `` The Adventures of Baron Munchausen'' the third in his fantasy triology that includes `` Time Bandits'' and `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>.'' Where `` Time Bandits'' primarily had a comedic appeal to youngsters and `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'' tapped more philosophical and political chords, `` <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchausen </PERSON>'' is a priceless romp with more visual effects and excursions into pure fantasy than any movie in memory. There's even an unbilled cameo by <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> as the King of the Moon. The story opens in `` late 18th century, the Age of Reason, Wednesday,'' with an attack on an ancient city by the ferocious forces of the Ottoman Empire. A play about <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchausen </PERSON> is underway at a local theater, but the real baron is in the audience and takes issue with the mockery on stage. The movie soon becomes the baron's story. And the spectacle is nonstop: a hot-air trip in a balloon made of ladies' knickers that takes the baron -LRB- <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> -RRB- and <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Salt </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Polley </PERSON> -RRB-, a little girl who believes in imagination, to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> and heaven; heads that separate from bodies; a Venus rising from a half-shell, complete with little angels with little wings; sea monsters; strange trees, creatures, seas. But there's so much more in <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON>'s odyssey. The film is a wondrous and brilliant work whose underpinnings tap the very essence of imagination and conformity. The rigid bureaucrat <PERSON> Horatio </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryce </PERSON> -RRB- questions the place of fancy, imagination and dreamers in the age of reason. There is n't one, he says. Fairy tales, however, never die. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> McKeown </PERSON>, who also has the dual role of <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Adolphus </PERSON>, wrote the masterful screenplay with <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON>. <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Idle </PERSON> appears as <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> and <PERSON> Berthold </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> is Vulcan. The <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> release is produced by <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuhly </PERSON> and is rated PG.
</TEXT>
