 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit narrowed sharply in January to $ 9.49 billion, the lowest imbalance in three months, as a big decline in consumer imports offset a higher oil bill, the government reported. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that the imbalance between imports and exports fell by 13.7 percent from a revised December deficit of $ 10.99 billion as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> posted a rare trade surplus with <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> fell to its lowest point in 2 -LCB- years.
