<HEAD>Federal Judge Throws Out Arbitrator's Ruling in Morrell-Union Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An arbitrator's ruling that union workers who staged sympathy strikes should get their jobs back from <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morrell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was thrown out by a federal judge. Company officials called the judge's ruling Wednesday a major victory and said it frees <PERSON> Morrell </PERSON> from any back pay obligation. The union promised to appeal. At the time the arbitrator made his ruling, a union leader said the back pay to the 2,400 workers who went on strike could amount to $ 40 million. In a 14-page decision, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Battey </PERSON> ruled that arbitrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rentfro </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> law professor, overstepped his authority when he decided in November that a six-month sympathy strike at <PERSON> Morrell </PERSON>'s flagship plant in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> in 1987 was legal. <PERSON> Battey </PERSON> ruled that <PERSON> Morrell </PERSON> does not have to follow <PERSON> Rentfro </PERSON>'s decision and rehire workers who were replaced during the sympathy strike `` We will immediately move to the 8th -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> and hopefully get the proper decision,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> 304A in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATIO