<HEAD>Trade Deficit Drops; Markets React Favorably</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be led with Commerce Department report on February housing
starts, scheduled for 8:30 a.m. EST; and Federal Reserve report on factory
use, tentatively scheduled for 9:15 a.m. EST.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Exports and imports both fell in January as the trade deficit declined to $ 9.49 billion, according to a government report that economists said may be good news for inflation. The decline in imports and exports could mean the rapid economic expansion is cooling slightly, removing some pressure on production costs and prices, economists said Wednesday after the release of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report. The nation's merchandise trade gap fell 13.7 percent in January from a revised $ 10.99 billion in December, the department said. A big decline in consumer imports offset a higher oil bill. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks gained 14.29 points on Wednesday to reach 2,320.54. The dollar also was buoyed by the numbers, while the bond market, where pessimism is entrenched, ended the day roughly neutral after an early rally. The markets' overall favorable reaction showed how investors have been more worried lately about inflation than about the trade deficit. Ordinarily a decline in exports would be considered bad news because it delays shrinkage in the trade gap. But the 4.3 percent drop in exports in January was seen as favorable because it meant there was less pressure on the nation's factories to churn out goods for shipment abroad. A 6.9 percent drop in imports was also seen as good news because it meant declining demand for goods and services. Strong consumer demand and a strain on factory capacity have combined to increase inflation. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> has responded by pushing up interest rates, which has hurt stock and bond prices. Slackening growth could allow the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to ease off on interest rates. Still, other reports Wednesday showed that the economy's aging expansion continues to have plenty of strength. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said business inventories rose 0.7 percent in January while sales rose 1 percent. A report based on surveys by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s 12 district banks said the economy's growth is putting upward pressure on production costs and prices. `` Consumer spending, except for autos, has apparently gained momentum while manufacturing, especially for export, continues to show strength almost everywhere,'' according to the report, known as the Tan Book.
</TEXT>
