<HEAD>U.S. Oil Production Continues Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> oil production fell for the third straight month in February and overall <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude production continued to decline sharply, an industry trade group said. Imports also rose last month compared with the same time last year but consumption remained flat, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said in its monthly report Wednesday. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> production, which had offset declines in other parts of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in recent years, fell by 100,000 barrels a day in February, while other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production dropped by 300,000 barrels a day, a total decline of about 5 percent, <ORGANIZATION> API </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The year-to-year declines in production indicate a continuation of decreases in lower 48 production as well as a flattening, if not a reversal, of an upward trend in Alaskan production seen during the last several years,'' the trade group said. Imports in February totaled 7.9 million barrels, compared with 6.9 million barrels at the same time last year, but receded from January's high of 8.2 million, the group reported. API, which represents major oil producers and refiners, said the January import surge reflected an effort by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil companies to take advantage of cheap and plentiful world oil before <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> began cutting back its output early this year. Imports now constitute over 40 percent of the oil consumed by Americans, a level that has raised concern about national security as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> becomes more dependent on foreigners for petroleum needs. `` The continued decline in domestic production and rise in consumption together imply underlying growth in imports of more than 10 percent per year,'' the trade group said. Contributing to the rise in overall imports last month was a strong increase in oil products such as heating oil and gasoline. For the first two months of 1989, product imports were up 20 percent over the same time last year. Also, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> refinery capacity has shrunk in recent years and refineries are currently operating at more than 80 percent capacity. Gasoline deliveries, meanwhile, fell 1.5 percent from last February, due partly to a normal seasonal slowdown, the institute report said. Heating oil deliveries growth also dropped to 3.2 percent despite colder-than-normal February weather, <ORGANIZATION> API </ORGANIZATION> said. Despite the growing imports and slowdown in gasoline demand, total inventories fell by 8 million barrels in February, down slightly from January and from the same time last year, the report said.
