<HEAD>Commodities Futures Regulators: Market Cops or Industry Pansies?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fraud probe into the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> futures exchanges coincides with a congressional review of the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and has raised new questions about its ability to police abuses. Theoretically, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could decide not to reauthorize the 15-year-old regulatory body. But <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> officials say accusations that they have failed to curb corruption in the freewheeling futures pits are n't true. `` We've had these same kinds of criticisms from the start,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rainbolt </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer for commodities traders and brokers and a <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> vice chairman. `` Everybody's got a vested interest in doing or saying whatever they need to promote their particular cause,'' he said in a recent interview. `` It's a combination of bureaucratic sour grapes, regulatory competition and power plays in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> was created in 1974 to enforce federal laws regulating the futures and options markets. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reauthorized it in 1978, 1982 and 1986. Lawmakers are considering legislation this year to extend its authority through 1994. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the commission, planned on a quick reauthorization process. However, its chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Eligio </PERSON> `` Kika'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, ordered an in-depth review after learning of an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation of alleged fraud and illegal trading on <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> futures markets, the nation's largest. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> probe reportedly involves allegations that brokers and traders cheated customers out of millions of dollars in deals on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. An immediate question that surfaced in the probe was why the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> did n't root out such corruption if it existed. Futures trading had been regulated since 1936 by the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, but <PERSON> Rainbolt </PERSON> said the agency _ `` with 161 employees in the basement of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> and no real authority at all'' _ was unable to keep pace with growth in the industry. From 1969 to 1973, volume in regulated commodities doubled and trading in unregulated commodities quadrupled to create what a congressional report said was a $ 400 billion industry. With growth came the potential for abuses, such as the sale of unregulated options by a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> company that parlayed a $ 1,000 investment into a multimillion-dollar company by using new investors' money to pay old customers. The firm's collapse in the early 1970s, resulting in more than $ 71 million in customer losses, was cited as the catalyst for congressional action to scrap the exchange authority and create the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>. In a report on its activities in 1988, <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON> said the commission assessed more than $ 2 million in civil penalties for violating commodities laws last year, decided more than 500 reparation cases and issued more than 185 opinions and orders. Nonetheless, critics have branded the commission as lax and excessively reliant on industry self-regulation. The exchanges have their own operating rules, established in alliance with the industry-operated <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. It, in turn, acts with approval of the federal commission. `` This whole system was born when the emphasis was to deregulate,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> English, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., chairman of the subcommittee investigating the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> `` The issue, as we look at the whole system, is to reassess the entire deregulation mentality: Is it adequate? Does it need to be changed?'' Futures industry officials contend self-regulation works well. Some say the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> is too meddlesome now. `` Speaking as one of the regulated, I get mad at the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> and disagree with them every day,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Damgard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> trade group and a commodity purchaser himself. `` But the relationship is not so adversarial that we're unwilling to admit we have somebody over there who's smart, who understands our industry and who will listen,'' <PERSON> Damgard </PERSON> said. `` That is an agency that, over the last 15 years, has matured into one of the finest government agencies we have.'' Even if lawmakers reauthorize the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>, some predict the debate will resurrect jursidictional arguments over who should regulate futures trading: the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> or the rival <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> has been a better regulator,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, D-Tenn. `` You need a strong regulatory body, regardless of what its initials are, to police a group of very impressive _ and sometimes greedy _ traders and brokers.
