<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is headed by investor <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>, has accumulated since last summer a 6.3 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> that is now valued at about $ 1.15 billion, <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> has disclosed. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> officials said they viewed the purchases as a `` strong vote of confidence'' from the widely-respected investor, who with his wife controls 45 percent of the <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb.-based <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION>'s stock. In a telephone interview Wednesday, <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> described the stock purchase as `` simply a passive investment'' and said he is happy with the way the company is being managed. <PERSON> Berkshire </PERSON> <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON> is a diversified holding company. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> has a reputation for taking sizeable stakes in a limited number of companies and hold them for a long time. The disclosure sent <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> stock up $ 1.25 a share to $ 51.50 in active trading of about 1.1 million shares on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goizueta </PERSON> disclosed the <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> holding in a memo to the soft drink maker's employees late Tuesday. He said <PERSON> Berkshire </PERSON> had accumulated 6.3 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>'s common stock over the `` last several months. Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> has about 364 million shares outstanding. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> said the stake amounted to about 22 million shares, accumulated by various insurance subsidiaries of <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION> over the past eight or nine months. In his memo to the employees, <PERSON> Goizueta </PERSON> said the investment `` is in keeping with <PERSON> Berkshire </PERSON> <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON>'s track record of making long-term investments in companies with a strong consumer franchise and a focused business.'' He called it `` a strong vote of confidence and a welcomed endorsement of our past success and future potential.'' He also noted that <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> was `` one of the biggest fans of <ORGANIZATION> Cherry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>'' and declared it the official soft drink of <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION> at that company's 1986 annual meeting. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> acknowledged that he favors the drink, and said he has been `` very impressed by the international strength of the Coca-Cola brand and the job that management has done.'' He said his company had not previously disclosed the stake because insurance companies are not required to do so until their holding reaches 10 percent or stands at 5 percent at the end of a year. Federal rules require other shareholders to disclose a holding in a company when it reaches 5 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> is the world's largest soft drink maker. It earned $ 1.04 billion, or $ 2.85 a share, on revenue of $ 8.34 billion in 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which has about 1.14 million common shares outstanding, has a stock value of about $ 5.47 billion based on its closing price of $ 4,800 a share Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>, known as much for his folksy wisdom and unpretentious lifestyle as his financial acumen, has combined a patient, value-oriented stock strategy with a knack for finding investment diamonds in the rough. Forbes magazine estimates his personal wealth at about $ 1.4 billion. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> acquired <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> cloth-milling concern with $ 10 million in assets, in the mid-1960s. Since then he has turned it into a diversified holding company with about $ 2 billion in assets. Most of <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION>'s operating revenue comes from insurance operations. The company also has interests in the publisher <ORGANIZATION> Buffalo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, in <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and in <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities-ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>.
