<HEAD>Dollar Climbs Against Yen; Nikkei Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished higher against the Japanese yen today, while share prices erased earlier gains and lost ground on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar closed at 130.73 yen, up 0.85 yen from Wednesday's 129.88-yen finish The currency, which opened at 130.68 yen, fluctuated in a range of 130.60 yen and 130.95 yen. Dealers said the currency's strength in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed its gain in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> overnight, inspired by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report Wednesday that the nation's trade deficit fell to $ 9.49 billion in January from a revised December shortfall of $ 10.99 billion. A <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> dealer said `` there was no reason to sell the dollar'' considering the trade figures. Dollar-buying interest remained strong throughout the day, the dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` Market players' dollar-buying interest will remain strong for a while,'' the dealer added. On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 376.13-point winner the previous day, erased its gains in the early session and lost 2.24 points, or 0.007 percent, to finish at 32,098.24. After moderate gains in the morning session, trading in the afternoon became directionless and fell, said a trader with a major securities firm in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, also speaking on condition of anonymity. Although trading was active, profit-taking by speculative investors in the afternoon session resulted in the Nikkei's loss, he added. Volume on the first section was estimated at 1.3 billion shares. `` But demand-supply balance in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> stock market has been getting better,'' the trader added.
