<HEAD>Dollar Edges Up, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar edged higher in light European trading early today despite what dealers said was a concerted bout of dollar-selling by European central banks. Gold prices fell. Dealers said several central banks, including <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, intervened together on the open market in efforts to curb the dollar's recent rise They said the size of the intervention was not immediately clear, but was large enough to temporarily interrupt the dollar's upward trend. A trader in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> predicted the central banks would be unable to dampen bullish interest in the dollar. `` They intervened to put the brakes on the dollar and to show the market that they are present,'' he said. The dollar headed sharply higher Wednesday after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government reported that the nation's trade deficit shrank to its lowest level in three months, from a revised December shortfall of $ 10.99 billion to $ 9.49 billion in January. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.85 Japanese yen to a closing 130.73 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it fell back to 130.27 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's rates included: 1.8684 West German marks, up from 1.8670; 1.6060 Swiss francs, up from 1.6038; 6.3225 French francs, up from 6.3200; 2.1129 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1065; 1,370.50 Italian lire, up from 1,369.37; 1.1967 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1935 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.7225 from $ 1.7235 late Wednesday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 390.40 a troy ounce, down from $ 392.25 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 391. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the noon bid price was $ 390.70, down from $ 393.25 bid late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 5.65 to close at a bid $ 396.89. Silver bullion fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a bid price of $ 6.07 a troy ounce from $ 6.12 bid late Wednesday.
