<FIRST>r f PM-FarmScene     03-16 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Increased Plantings, Higher Fuel Prices Add to Energy Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers are expected to boost plantings of corn and some other major crops this spring, and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analysts say fuel needed to do their field work will cost more _ again. Energy prices overall are expected to edge up in 1989 due to higher crude oil prices, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said in the March issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine. `` Farm fuel prices rose slightly in 1988,'' the report said. `` As a result of higher crude oil prices in the last quarter of 1988, average petroleum product prices paid by farmers should rise throughout 1989.'' The report said the increase in crude oil prices during last year's fourth quarter was prompted by an agreement of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> to hold down production. Under <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>'s agreement in November, there would be a price target of $ 18 per barrel and a reduction in output from the 17-year high of 22.5 million barrels per day to 18.5 million per day in the first six months of 1989. The agreement also brought <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> back into the cartel with a quota equivalent to that of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, the report said. According to Department of Energy forecasts, economic growth of about 2.5 percent will offset higher crude oil prices, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> petroleum consumption will therefore inch up about 1 percent this year. The report said that for the first time since 1980, domestic petroleum demand last year averaged more than 17 million barrels a day. Refiners paid an average of $ 14 per barrel in the last half of 1988, down 25 percent from 1987 prices. `` But prices surged near the end of 1988, and West Texas Intermediate -LRB- crude -RRB- reached $ 18 per barrel in January 1989,'' the report said. `` Crude oil prices are expected to range from $ 15 to $ 20 per barrel in 1989.'' Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> domestic production will probably slacken again this year to about 8 million barrels a day, down 200,000 from last year. And 1988 output of 8.2 million barrels a day was the lowest in 24 years. `` Expanding demand and decreasing domestic production are expected to boost <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> net imports in 1989 to 6.8 million barrels per day, or 39 percent of domestic consumption,'' the report said. `` This rate may be compared with a record high import of 8.6 million barrels per day in 1977, and a low of 4.3 million in 1985.'' The energy supply and price outlook for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agriculture mostly reflects world market conditions, currently characterized by abundant oil supplies and higher prices. `` In 1989, farmers can expect plentiful supplies of diesel fuel, gasoline and LP -LRB- liquefied petroleum -RRB- gas, but at slightly higher prices than last year,'' the report said. Yet, the combined use of gasoline and diesel fuel by farmers has declined in recent years because of improved farm production technology, shifts from gasoline to more efficient diesel units, and greatly reduced crop plantings. `` Although acres planted greatly influences the fluctuations in farm energy use, other factors also have contributed to the decline,'' the report said. `` Continued replacement of older gasoline machines with diesel-powered machines, particularly in the production of cotton, rice and some minor crops, has resulted in greater use of diesel fuel.'' Besides acreage cutbacks under some government crop programs, last year's drought-reduced yields also contributed to an estimated 5 percent reduction in farm fuel use in 1988, the report said. Lower grain moisture levels at harvest also reduced energy requirements. But expenditures for farm energy _ gasoline, diesel fuel, LP and electricity _ were about $ 7 billion last year, up 3 percent from 1977 because of higher prices and greater reliance on electricity. `` In 1989, energy expenditures, which comprise about 5.5 percent of total farm production expenses, are projected to jump 7 percent to $ 7.5 billion, largely due to an expected 4 percent to 11 percent increase in planted area of the eight major crops,'' the report said. This will offset long-term reductions in fuel use related to conservation, primarily from 28 million acres of land taken from production under the Conservation Reserve Program.
</TEXT>
