<FIRST>r f PM-IRSErrors Bjt   03-16 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IRS Errors, Bjt,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Answers Wrong 50 Percent in Some Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> employees in some parts of the country are giving correct answers to telephoned tax questions barely half the time, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> says. Nationwide, say auditors for the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is correct only 60 percent of the time _ not the 69 percent claimed by the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> less than a week ago. Some of the answers that <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> considers correct could lead taxpayers to foul up their returns, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBaube </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> director of taxpayer services, quarreled with the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> estimate _ but only slightly. `` As far as the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is concerned, whether we are answering 30 percent of the questions wrong or 40 percent of the questions wrong, either number is absolutely unacceptable,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Government Operations consumer subcommittee Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>' own tests of its telephone-assistance system indicate a performance no better than last year's, even though employees have had an extra year to acquaint themselves with the big 1986 tax overhaul. While the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> figures it is correct 69 percent of the time nationally, in some of the 29 calling sites the accuracy rate is in the 50s and in others it is in the 70s, <PERSON> LeBaube </PERSON> said. He did not identify those areas. In an effort to improve performance, <PERSON> LeBaube </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> is switching to a more permanent work force, hiring fewer people to work only during the filing season. The agency also is assigning more supervisors and using new procedures to discover problem areas of tax law that are causing most problems for the telephone `` assistors.'' <PERSON> LeBaube </PERSON> advised taxpayers who call the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> toll-free numbers to write down their question, the date and name of the person who provided the answer. If an answer leads to an incorrect tax return and the taxpayer produces such a record, <PERSON> LeBaube </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> will waive any penalty. `` The assistors are not properly trained to answer questions right 100 percent of the time?'' asked Rep. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>. `` That, to me, is really an intolerable situation. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> blames a complicated tax law for part of the problem, as well as the frequency of changes in the law. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> has said some <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employees are reluctant to probe for additional information from taxpayers before answering their tax questions. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has about 5,000 employees answering telephoned tax questions during this filing season; about 1,500 of them are temporaries. All are required to have at least a high school education and receive at least five weeks' tax training. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> complaints that the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> was overstating its accuracy rate prompted Chairman <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Ga., to call his subcommittee into session for a rare public airing of a dispute between two government agencies <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> agreed to work together on one test of the telephone-assistance system and hammered out 62 questions that <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> officials are expected to ask clandestinely about 15,000 times this filing season. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> agreed to score answers in only three ways: Correct; correct and complete, or incorrect. After the tests got under way, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> wanted a fourth grade: an answer that while not technically correct likely would not result in a faulty return. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> refused to go along, contending some of those answers from <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employees were potentially misleading. <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> insisted and on its own beganscoring those answers _ which were 8.8 percent of the total _ as correct. Thus, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> came up with an accuracy rate of 60.4 percent. <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> added the 8.8 percent in the fourth category and reached a total accuracy rate of 69.8 percent. Changing the method of judging the system in the middle of the test `` raises questions about the validity of its -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>'s -RRB- reported results and whether it is making progress toward improving the accuracy of its responses,'' said <PERSON> Jennie </PERSON> <PERSON> Stathis </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was not our intent to mislead anyone,'' <PERSON> LeBaube </PERSON> told the subcommittee. `` In retrospect and in fairness to <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, we probably should have announced both numbers.''
