<HEAD>Tax-Committee Members Join Budget Meetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Negotiations over the fiscal 1990 budget are getting down to the touchy topics of tax increases and entitlement cuts, but bargainers say decisions are still off on the horizon. `` Well, we're going to talk revenues and see where the conversation takes us,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON>, D-Calif., said Wednesday Although President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has promised no new taxes, his $ 1.16 trillion budget includes $ 14.2 billion in new revenues that need to be discussed, <PERSON> Panetta </PERSON> said. That figure includes new `` fees'' for government services and changes in the tax law that the White House argues are not tax increases. The heads of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> tax-writing committees were joining the budget talks for today's meetings. The conversation was also to touch on entitlement programs under those committees' jurisdiction Both Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, and Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., have said their panels would not approve the $ 5 billion in <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> cuts requested by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> has also nixed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan to cut the tax rate on capital gains. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> on Wednesday said $ 7.5 billion of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> tax package was based on items <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> previously rejected or was unlikely to approve _ the capital gains tax, expanding the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> tax, and repealing a scheduled cut in the airport excise tax. `` I find it troubling that the administration, instead of showing leaderhip on this issue, is effectively leaving it up to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to fill the gap,'' he said. `` I know very well the political constraints that the president is operating under, given the ` read my lips _ no new taxes' pledge he made during the campaign last year,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. `` But I must say in all candor ... I'm going to do my best to help him but it's hard to see how the numbers are going to add up. Sen. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, D-Tenn., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the appearance of the tax-writing committees in the budget talks did not mean that the panel was leaning toward a tax boost The negotiators wanted to `` ascertain from them what's realistic by way of spending restraints or what might be realistic by way of revenue enhancements,'' he said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, the director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, described the meetings as laying out the options rather than hard bargaining. `` We still have n't really begun what I would call serious negotiating,'' he said. Asked when the hard part would begin, he said, `` I thought it was going to start a long time ago, and so far it's still going pretty well,'' he said.
