<FIRST>r f PM-Soviet-Food-Excerpts     03-16 1010</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Food-Excerpts,1049</SECOND>
<HEAD>Excerpts of Gorbachev Speech on Agriculture</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Soviet-Food</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s speech Wednesday on developing `` an agrarian policy that will be able to restore the peasant as the master on the land and dependably resolve the food problem.'' They were taken from the English-language translation by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. _ On the overall problem: Further delay in this matter is simply inadmissible Drastic changes in the countryside are an essential prerequisite for the country's economic and social progress. ... We all remember the concern expressed by delegates to the 19th national party conference when discussing the food supply situation in the country. We described this problem as ` our society's biggest wound.' The state has to buy large quantities of grain, meat, fruit, vegetables, sugar, vegetable oil and some other staples abroad. We are still behind developed countries, big and small, in labor efficiency, yield capacity and livestock productivity and in the diversity and quality of foodstuffs. The gap is widening rather than narrowing. The shortage of food creates social tension and generates not merely criticism, but actual discontent. Huge capital and other investments have been made in agriculture in recent years, but the inputs have failed to yield equally substantial results.'' Comrades, we should work out an agrarian policy that would enable us to blunt the sharp edge of the food problem in the immediate future and to grow enough farm produce, in terms of both amount and choice, to stabilize food supplies in the 13th Five-Year Plan -LRB- 1991-96 -RRB-. In the 13th five-year period, it is planned to increase the output of foodstuffs by 26 percent to 30 percent, while the output of farm produce will grow by 16 percent. _ On <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s brutal collectivization of agriculture: In the process of combatting the kulaks, violence was inflicted upon the huge mass of middle-strata peasants and even poor ones Millions of peasants, together with their families, were torn away from their land plots and native areas and suffered misfortunes, often dying in camps and exile. _ On leasing: Let us not fix assignments, let us not set deadlines The point at issue is the transfer of land and other means of production to lease-holders, their real control over those means. ... If the plenum backs the relevant proposals of the Politburo, the Presidium of the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION> Supreme Soviet and the government, and we adopt corresponding documents, this will create legal and economic prerequisites for an extensive transition to leasing. _ On price reform: The purposes of economic restructuring can not be achieved, new methods of economic management can not be introduced and a socialist market can not be formed without a price reform ... Purchase prices of some kinds of quality products are so low as not to stimulate the development and rational distribution of specialized highly marketable production. The documents circulated among you envisage the introduction of new purchase prices of farm produce as of Jan. 1, 1990. ... The range of products priced in a centralized way should be reduced. _ On banks: There is a need for radical restructuring of the activity of banks, particularly of the agro-industrial bank It is necessary to ensure that they are really interested in the development of production and act as business partners. _ On the independence of agricultural enterprises: Agricultural enterprises are really doubly dependent On the one hand, they are subordinated to higher bodies along the departmental line. They are also managed in no less, perhaps even in a greater degree, by local party and government bodies, starting from the district level. Perestroika presupposes a radical change in the system of managing the agrarian sector at all levels. ... We proceeded from the assumption that no one should interfere in the day-to-day economic activities of collective and state farms, and still less with peasant and individual small holdings. _ On equipment problems in agriculture: Workers of the agrarian sector rightly complain that the machine-makers, abusing their monopoly status, often foist upon them outdated models of expensive machines with low dependability and efficiency standards This is ruinous not only for agriculture, but for the country as a whole. We produce more tractors than any other country in the world, and yet complaints about their short supply are common. ... Machine-makers should be put in such economic conditions that would rule out the manufacture of shoddy equipment. _ On waste in agriculture: Our losses in grain harvesting and pre-storage treatment amount to 15 million and even 20 million tons About as much is lost in storage and processing. In all, comrades, the losses equal our purchases abroad. Due to the sparsity of meat packing plants, their low technological standards, and inefficient use of raw material, meat losses, even according to the lowest estimates, add up to around 1 million tons. This despite the acute shortage of foodstuffs. Such is the dimension of the problem. Many problems stem from the methods of economic management, people's attitude to work and their poor motivation to achieve better end results. _ On ecology: What must be done as a matter of urgency is putting reclaimed lands in proper order and taking measures to put land and water to more rational use Efforts to come to grips with ecological problems that have piled up should not be put off either. We should drastically raise standards and increase accountablity when it comes to the production, transportation and storage of chemicals and especially their application to the soil. _ On life in the villages: The peasant mode of life has lost its attractiveness and prestige People, above all the young, are leaving villages. The disregard for the needs of villages and the hypertrophied urban development brought about great social distortions and complicated the normal economic functioning of whole regions. The rates of house building in villages in the 13th five-year period must at least be doubled. Villagers justly raise the issue why rural areas have been put on ` short rations' and why peasants have been left to struggle with their problems alone, although the country has vast resources.
</TEXT>
