<HEAD>House Sends Bill To End Eastern Walkout To Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation that would force President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to intervene in the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> strike faces stronger opposition in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passage has already given organized labor a morale boost. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the union-sought measure 252-167 on Wednesday, largely with the support of the chamber's majority Democrats. Only 20 Republicans supported the legislation, and just 15 Democrats voted against it. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> opposes the bill, and Republicans in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are expected to maneuver to try to block it. That chamber's tricky procedures often allow a minority of legislators to wreak havoc on legislation they oppose, and the bill is given only a long-shot chance at ever becoming law. Nonetheless, lobbyists for organized labor, who have rallied around <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s striking unions, say they will push hard for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passage. `` We trust they'll take it up,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGlotten </PERSON>, director of legislation for the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>, said after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> begins a two-week recess after Friday's session, and supporters of the measure say they would like to see an effort to take up the bill before the break. Time is a factor in the dispute, with striking workers needing money to pay their bills and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> already having obtained protection from creditors under the bankruptcy code's Chapter 11. Eastern is demanding $ 125 million in wage and benefit concessions from members of its machinists union, which wants $ 50 million in improvements. The walkout has forced Eastern to fly only about 100 flights daily, compared to 1,040 before the strike. The measure would require a cooling-off period of up to 26 days and force <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to appoint an emergency board, which would study the dispute and recommend a solution. Neither Eastern nor the 8,500-member <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>, which began its walkout March 4, would be required to accept the proposed formula. But even if the measure goes no further than the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, it has already has cheered labor and its Democratic allies. House passage is a morale-booster to the striking machinists and to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots and flight attendants, who have also walked off their jobs. It's an indication to the labor movement that after eight years of rough times under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, it is still capable of mustering support in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. And it has forced <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Republican lawmakers to appear to be defending <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> has been accused by workers of trying to break <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s unions and dismantle the company, and his business practices are often criticized by Democrats and Republicans alike on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, including <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> Rep. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON>, D-Calif., called <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> `` the neutron bomb of the airline industry, saving assets as booty and taking the people and letting them go. But Rep. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, R-Calif., told a reporter, `` I have n't heard any Republican stand up and defend <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> The bill's opponents say the Eastern walkout has caused inconvenience but not a transportation emergency that requires government intervention. They also note that Eastern and the machinists began bargaining for a new contract in October 1987, and say there is no reason to believe an emergency board would be successful. Supporters argued that the emergency board would provide cover for the two sides to be able to accept a solution to their bitter dispute without appearing to have given in.
