<HEAD>Panel to Question Officials in Generic Drug Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional subcommittee wants to question more than 60 government officials and employees in its investigation into alleged improprieties in the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s processing of generic drug applications A federal grand jury in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> reportedly is conducting a criminal investigation into the matter, based on information the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on oversight and investigations uncovered last summer. The subcommittee's investigation is proceeding independently of the criminal investigation, said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., subcommittee chairman, and Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican on the panel <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said Wednesday that the investigation centers on `` the question of whether <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> processed generic drug applications fairly and in accordance with the law.'' <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> said the panel's focus `` is on the approval process and whether or not it has been conducted in a fair and impartial manner.'' A report in the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> earlier this week quoted sources as saying the grand jury was investigating allegations that <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> employees took bribes and accepted favors to approve companies' applications to market generic drugs. The newspaper quoted one source familiar with the investigation as saying indictments could be returned by the end of the month. Generic drugs are low-cost versions of brand-name drugs. Once the patent for a brand-name drug expires, companies can copy the compound and apply to the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> for approval of a new generic drug. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> sent a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, whose department includes <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, telling him subcommittee investigators want to question employees at <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> and in the <ORGANIZATION> HHS </ORGANIZATION> general counsel's office. The lawmakers provided <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> with a list of 64 employees the investigators wanted to interview, but the subcommittee did not identify them. A subcommittee source said all but four of those on the list work at <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> and they reach as high in the agency as Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> noted in the press release that `` just because a government employee is questioned in an investigation of this magnitude does not imply any wrongdoing on their part.'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> told <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> that investigators wanted to complete the interviews by the end of the month. They also submitted a list of documents for the department to produce by March 24 and noted that most items on the list `` have been the subject of outstanding requests since last summer.'' <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON> said the agency had no comment, but he said, `` We of course will cooperate with the investigation. The agency is anxious to have everything resolved.''
