<FIRST>r f PM-Chile-Fruit     03-16 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Fruit,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chileans Angered Over Tainted Fruit Incident In U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With millions of pounds of Chilean fruit being held for testing in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports because of a cyanide scare, producers and workers whose livelihoods depend on fruit exports seethed with anger. `` Buy! Buy! Do n't believe the gringos' lies!'' a <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> street vendor of grapes chanted Wednesday. Some passersby laughed and many made purchases. Producers and union officials say thousands of industry workers have been laid off as a result of the scare. On Monday, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> urged consumers not to eat Chilean fruit after two grapes imported from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> were found to be tainted with cyanide. Most Chilean fruit was pulled from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets' shelves. Similar decisions were taken by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and several western European countries said they were tightening controls on Chilean fruit. Chilean exporters, growers and packers voluntarily suspended all operations Tuesday for 72 hours to allow thousands of crates of stored fruit to be checked. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday that `` not a trace'' of any alien substance had been found in the crates of fruit ready for export that had so far been checked. Officials of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s military government say preliminary estimates indicate the crisis could cost <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> at least $ 800 million. Nearly 65 percent of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s fruit exports _ grapes, melons, apples and peaches _ go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the country is at the peak of its fruit harvesting season. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Japanese embassies in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> received anonymous telephone calls earlier this month saying fruit exports would be poisoned. An investigation turned up nothing, authorities said. The Chilean agriculture minister, <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Sotta </PERSON>, says the cyanide found in the two grapes in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> on March 2 amounted to 0.52 parts per million. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said a child would have to eat 2,000 grapes to ingest a fatal dose. Wednesday afternoon, several of the nation's leading fruit exporters toured the capital's center street with pick-up trucks loaded with fruit, and gave away grapes and apples to the public. Hundreds of people enthusiastically ate them. Organizers said the idea was to show the world Chilean fruit is safe. Most Chilean fruit enters the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> through the port of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, others through <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. Boats containing hundreds of thousands of crates of Chilean fruit awaited off <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> as fruit inspections continued. In <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials completed sampling Wednesday of the 362,000 crates of grapes and other fruit from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. No further contamination was found. In <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Seguel </PERSON>, called the decision to remove the fruit from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stores `` totally out of proportion.'' <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Duran </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said nearly 40,000 workers had been laid off by Wednesday, but union leaders put the figure at 17,000 workers. `` The consequences of the thoughtless <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision are worse than those of several earthquakes,'' <PERSON> Duran </PERSON> told a Wednesday news conference. `` It is totally irresponsible to react like that because of two tainted grapes, just two grapes, not two clusters.'' `` I directly accuse the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of paving the way to terrorism against the international food trade in the future,'' <PERSON> Duran </PERSON> said. He said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision will encourage terrorists in the future. The Chilean govenment officialy blamed the tainting of the grapes to `` terrorism backed by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.'' The communists denied the charge. Angry reactions came from other quarters, too. <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Bardon </PERSON>, president of the state-owned <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, called the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision `` an agression, almost an act of war.'' He blamed `` certain sectors of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>,'' which he said were influenced by Chilean opposition politicians. Scores of citizens interviewed by radio and TV stations also strongly criticized the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision, calling it exaggerated.
