<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State representatives have approved a bill that could make <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> the third state to legalize casino gambling. The proposal approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> 57-42 Wednesday would limit the operation to a five-year pilot project in the northeastern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Lorain </LOCATION>. The bill was sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where a Democratic leader predicted passage, but Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> refused to say whether he would approve the proposal. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Meshel </PERSON>, a Democrat, said he thinks the bill could provide a badly needed economic boost for northeast <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, `` and I have n't heard a lot of opposition to it. I think it's going to pass. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> are the only states that have legalized casino gambling. Debate in the House involved claims that the bill would damage the state's image and hurt its economy. Republican Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Petro </PERSON> argued that industries considering locating in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> might look elsewhere out of family and community considerations. Gambling does not provide `` real jobs or real growth,'' he contended. Backers of the legislation said that an envisioned $ 300 million casino will have a major impact on the state's economy _ not only in <LOCATION> Lorain </LOCATION> but all across northern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, including <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, 40 miles to the east. The bill provides that if voters in <LOCATION> Lorain </LOCATION> approve of the venture, the casino would be overseen by a state commission of five members to be named by the governor.
