<TEXT>
 Discovery's astronauts today enjoyed the first home delivery in space of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> newspaper. A facsimile machine flying in orbit for the first time was used to send Discovery a copy of the front page of The Roundup, an employee weekly at the <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. And it was delivered in space before it was delivered on the ground. The issue had been rushed into print by editor <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphries </PERSON> so that it could be sent to the space shuttle today. The paper will not be distributed on Earth until Friday. Discovery astronaut Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagian </PERSON> stopped his work in space long enough to read the newspaper and comment to <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. `` Thanks for the home paper here, the Roundup,'' he said. `` We wanted to tell you that's the first newspaper that's been sent to an American spacecraft,'' replied <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Thuot </PERSON>, capsule communicator at <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's a good thing that it's you who is there because if it was <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> -LRB- Low -RRB- I would expect that he would have sent me up the Wall Street Journal,'' joked <PERSON> Bagian </PERSON>. <PERSON> Low </PERSON>, who is known to take an interest in finance, is capsule communicator on an earlier shift. The first newspaper in space carried a lead story about the Discovery launch on Monday and a story at the bottom of the page about a welcome home ceremony at Johnson for the five-man crew, which returns on Saturday. There also was a story about American-Soviet cooperation in the exploration of space and a feature about the value of <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> photos taken by shuttle astronauts. The facsimile machine aboard the shuttle 