<HEAD>Govenment Strikes Plea Bargain With `Dangerous' Hacker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 25-year-old computer hacker once declared `` a very, very great danger to the community'' pleaded guilty to computer fraud in a plea bargain with federal prosecutors. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> would be sentenced to 12 months in prison and three years on supervised release under terms of the agreement. The pudgy, youthful looking <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> was described by friends as a computer genius who called himself `` Condor'' and was capable of infiltrating any computer system. <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> pleaded guilty Wednesday to charges he infiltrated <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s computer system and stole one of its programs, and admitted stealing 16 <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> telephone codes and using them to make phone calls. It was not clear whether the long distance codes were used to access computer systems. Prosecutors agreed to dismiss two additional charges, one of which alleged that <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> infiltrated the computer system of <ORGANIZATION> Leeds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Mariana </PERSON> <PERSON> Pfaelzer </PERSON> declined prosecutors' recommendations until <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> is interviewed by probation department authorities She noted that he has a prior conviction for similar activities in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cruz </LOCATION>, and set sentencing for April 24. At a bail hearing on Jan. 3, <PERSON> Pfaelzer </PERSON> denied bail for the defendant, saying <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> posed `` a very, very great danger to the community'' _ reflecting public comments made by assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Weidman </PERSON>. Even <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON>'s access to the telephone was restricted. <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, has maintained that prosecution comments about the case were wildly exaggerated On Wednesday, <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said outside court that <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> had expressed a desire to undergo psychological counseling, which also was part of the plea agreement. `` He's a very talented man with a lot of ability and for whatever reason ... there's been a misuse of that ability,'' said <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>. `` A computer company that could harness his abilities would really get a talented employee.'' <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> never intended to damage computer systems or to sell information for profit. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Asperger </PERSON> said the government based its sentencing recommendation on <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION>'s estimate that <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON>'s actions had cost the firm between $ 100,000 and $ 200,000 in `` down time'' on its computer He said the computer system had to be shut down while the firm looked for damage. The government's initial estimates of damage to <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION>'s system were set at $ 4 million. It turned out there was no damage to the overall system, <PERSON> Asperger </PERSON> said, although <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> was able to steal and copy one program. <PERSON> Mitnick </PERSON> already has served more than three months in prison, and <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> added, `` He'll be out by Christmas.''
