<HEAD>Locals Profit From Contra Presence, Hope Fighting Is Over</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TEG1 of Feb. 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS TROJES, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Contra army stranded near here may be a headache for diplomats and a political problem in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but it has also brought a minor economic boom to the isolated valleys of eastern <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. `` I'm doing very well. Nowadays all is calm,'' said <PERSON> Eulogio </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Montoya </PERSON>, owner of the <LOCATION> Vendita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Miraflores </LOCATION> store, pointing to racks of cowboy boots at 80 lempiras each _ about $ 27 at the black market rate. Buildings throughout town are freshly painted and small stores are packed with everything from soccer balls to corn flakes. Families that never had electricity own generators, drink refrigerated Cokes and watch `` <PERSON> Cagney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lacey </PERSON>'' via satellite dishes. The boom began a little more than a year ago, when the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> cut military aid to the Nicaraguan rebels trying to topple the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government led by President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>. The Contras filtered out of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> as they exhausted supplies; about 11,000 fighters and thousands of family members now are living in camps a few miles from the border, supported by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. Many local Hondurans, who in thploded, killing one of her nieces and wounding four other children. Farther from the camps, the most common complaint about the Contra presence was drunken driving. `` I guess since they ca n't fight they have to entertain themselves,'' said <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodas </PERSON>, 21, of <LOCATION> Danli </LOCATION> <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Valladardes </PERSON>, who started a tire repair business in <LOCATION> Danli </LOCATION> with a rented air compressor, said he was trying to ride out an industry shakeout _ too many people competing for truck drivers' business His wife said Honduran criminals escape justice by joining the rebels; a <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> mechanic heatedly replied that the Contras are being blamed for anything that goes wrong within 50 miles. The 100 families of Capiri turned into refugees themselves in 1985, when there was frequent fighting in the border region. `` We had to get out of here,'' said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, a 63-year-old storeowner. `` Now, there's more confidence in being able to work.'' `` It's all up to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> added. `` Tell him not to turn up the flame.''
