<HEAD>Perfume Czar Hopes To Build House Of Fragrances Starting With 273
Address</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY301 of March 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON>'s blueprint for building the first American `` house of fragrances'' specifies a pyramid-shaped cornerstone. <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON>, the man behind one of the perfume industry's most successful scents, is introducing a new concoction that he thinks may create an even bigger splash than <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>. His new fragrance is called `` 273'' for the address on Rodeo Drive of the sumptuous <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> boutique that was the birthplace of the <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> perfume. It comes in a crystal flacon designed by <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> in a pyramid shape. If his dreams of 273's popularity come true, <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> says he intends to expand his fragrance collection under the provisional banner <PERSON> Clientele </PERSON> <PERSON> Privee </PERSON>, his interpretation of a Parisian perfumery. But <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> does n't want an exact repeat of the Giorgio success story. That fragrance family, which he sold to cosmetics and toiletries company Avon for $ 165 million in 1987, became phenomenally popular after its debut in 1981. Despite <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON>'s emphasis on exclusivity, <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> eventually became widely available in department stores and elsewhere, losing some allure in the process. <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> says it was difficult to resist demands from retail outlets clamoring to stock <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON>. `` But I will this time because I'm convinced small is beautiful,'' says the man who pioneered the use of `` scent strips'' in magazines, as a come-on for <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> At first, 273 will be sold solely through the boutique that has been rechristened `` <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hills </PERSON>.'' It's pricey, having an elevated `` prestige'' status among its perfume peers. One ounce of the perfume costs $ 185 and 2.5 ounces of the cologne goes for $ 45. If demand for 273 takes off, <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> will face some ticklish marketing. Prestige products pose sales-pitch paradoxes. People who fancy such goods _ from perfumes to watches to the latest exotic dog breed _ typically do n't want things just anybody can buy. So, from a merchandizing standpoint, the problem becomes one of satisfying demand enough to stimulate interest but not so much that the product loses the special cachet that scarcity supplies. Moreover, the availability of prestige perfumes is overflowing. Movie stars, from <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> to <PERSON> Cher </PERSON>, clothing designers and entertainers have added their own contributions to the gushing stream of new products. A footnote to the recent history of numerous perfume introductions is the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> debut in March of fragrances by <ORGANIZATION> Bic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, of throwaway razor, ballpoint pen and cigarette lighter fame. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Shore </PERSON>, who follows the scent business for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, says the lifespan of perfumes is frequently as short as 12 to 24 months. If a fragrance lingers for four years or so, it is considered a franchise from which successful spinoff products can be derived. `` Incredibly saturated'' is how Shore describes the market, adding that it is polarized with ultra high-priced items at one extreme and mass market stuff at the other. Unit sales have fallen for the past five years, he says. Modest growth in sales' value occurred because new fragrances fetch increasingly higher prices. He estimates retail sales rose to $ 3.25 billion in 1988, up from $ 3.15 billion a year earlier. <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> has a simple answer to whether 273 will rise to the top. `` There's always a market for the best,'' he said during an interview while on one of his frequent trips to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. 273 is described as a flowery, fruity, spicy blend of more than 250 ingredients, with the key ones being gardenia, tuberose and jasmine. Its components are expensive and so is its packaging. The crystal, pyramid-shaped bottle is embossed with a 24 karat gold line surrounding the stopper. Bright yellow, reminiscent of the <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> hue and <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON>'s favorite color, and fire-engine red are used for 273, as well as for the <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> store. During a conversation, <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON>, who left his native <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1941 and speaks Swiss, French and English, gives the impression he would rather not know the word `` discount'' in any language. His boutique, which claims to have the highest sales per square foot of any store in the country, never marks down prices on merchandise. For more than 20 years of running the store, <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> has had the good fortune to discover little-known designers who cultivated big followings, such as <PERSON> Halston </PERSON>. The boutique was originally called <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> who decided to Italianize his name because Italian imports accounted for much of the clothing carried in the shop. <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> bought out <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> and another partner in the mid-1960s. <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> seems to embody <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>. He owns a vintage Rolls <PERSON> Royce </PERSON> and is definitely a have, not a have-not. Recently, he appeared fit and pleasantly tanned, clad in a expensively styled suit. Recovering from back surgery required after years of jogging, he was more comfortable standing through an hour-long interview in his suite at a chic hotel on the east side of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s Central Park. When his former wife, <PERSON> Gale </PERSON>, came up with the idea that blossomed into <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> perfume, <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> was disinterested. `` At first, I thought it was not a good idea.'' He says he does n't normally wear fragrances himself but now the business is in his blood. At 63, <PERSON> Hayman </PERSON> says he has no intention of retiring anytime soon and hopes to establish his Clientele Privee _ French for private client _ as a perfume powerhouse. End adv for Sunday, March 19.
