 Stock prices climbed today, propelled by new evidence of a slackening in economic growth. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.21 to 2,322.75 in the first half hour of trading. Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed issues, with 438 up, 260 down and 495 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> came to 27.87 million shares as of 10 a.m. on Wall Street. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> reported this morning that industrial production was unchanged in February from the month before. A separate government report showed a decline of 0.2 percentage points, to 84.3 percent, in capacity utilization of the nation's production facilities Analysts said those figures were read by traders as evidence of an easing in the strains the economy has been exerting on inflation and interest rates. However, brokers also noted persistent uneasiness about Friday's impending report on the producer price index for February A 1 percent increase in the index during January unsettled both the stock and bond markets. A further complication for the immediate market outlook was the `` triple witching hour'' taking place on Friday, when the last trading occurs in a series of stock-index options and futures. There was talk on the Street that this quarterly phenomenon could produce more volatility than recent similar occasions, since the pace of computer program trading by professionals using these contracts appears to have revived lately. Gainers among the blue chips included <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION>, up \ at 46 -LRB-; <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, up -LRB- at 45 |; <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION>, up \ at 32 -RRB-, and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANI