<SECOND>PM-Third World Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru,0801</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with testimony; picks up 4th graf pvs, Brady
unveiled.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, which is asking banks to forgive voluntarily part of the $ 410 billion debt owed by Third World countries, opposes establishing an international agency that could require writing off some of the loans, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was told today. Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON>, the principal architect of the voluntary debt-forgiveness plan, said such an agency would cause more interruptions in the repayment of loans and interest and further reduce the value of the loans in secondary markets. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year directed President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to explore setting up an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Debt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> that could require renegotiation of the loans on more favorable terms to developing countries. Many lenders have been able to get only 40 percent of the loans' face value in selling them to other lenders. `` We have concluded after months of study that debt reduction and debt service reduction can be successfully accomplished in the marketplace,'' <PERSON> Mulford </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee on international finance and monetary policy `` We believe that -LRB- a -RRB- market-oriented approach ... addresses congressional concerns with less risk to tax-payers'' than a new international agency would, he said. The panel's chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON>, D-Md., praised the administration for recognizing the necessity of forgiving some of the debt `` To paraphrase <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>, this is not so much the beginning of the end, or even the end of the beginning, but it is perhaps the beginning of the beginning,'' <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON> said. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday that many of the details are likely to be worked out only after individual negotiations begin with some of the major Third World debtors, major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic allies, banks and international institutions. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> unveiled the plan in a speech last Friday in which he conceded that the so-called 1985 Baker Plan, named for his predecessor at <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> and now Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, had largely failed in solving the Third World debt crisis. Instead of asking banks to forgive a portion of their loans to impoverished, debt-saddled nations in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> plan called on them to write new loans for countries willing to make government enterprises private and institute austerity programs. Many countries did, but few new loans were written by private banks. And much of the new money that did come forth from international lending institutions such as the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> was used by many debtor nations to pay the interest on their loans to private banks. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> suggested <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks could be encouraged to forgive a portion of their loans with guarantees that the World Bank or the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> would provide, if necessary, money to the debtor countries to make interest payments on their remaining balances. `` At least you're moving in the right direction _ decreasing their debt instead of increasing it,'' Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, told <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>. In outlining the new plan, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said only through voluntary debt and debt-service reduction can some developing countries ever hope to restore their credit worthiness. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not publicly endorse the new plan until Tuesday, raising questions about whether the initiative was <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s alone or had the backing of the full administration. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> acknowledged Wednesday there was some `` confusion'' in the administration, but said his speech outlining the new strategy had been approved in advance by the president. Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> lender banks have vigorously resisted efforts by some lawmakers, among them Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, to force them to write off a portion of their Third World debts. `` Across-the-board mandatory solutions are simply not the answer,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, head of debt restructuring at <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. He said imposed debt forgiveness `` would seriously retard'' the ability of Third World debtors to return for new loans. But with riots two weeks ago in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> over austerity programs and radical political movements on both the left and right threatening many fragile Latin democracies, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is now looking at Third World debt as a national security issue as well as an economic one. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks now hold $ 97.7 billion of Third World debt, compared with nearly $ 140 billion six and one-half years ago when the crisis was precipitated by <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> stopping interest payments on its debt because of plummeting oil prices. The six largest borrowers _ <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> _ now owe those nine banks some $ 47 billion, less than the $ 65 billion of their combined capital bases.
