<BYLINE>Year-Old Bustup of Lord Geller Ad House Leaves Bitter Taste</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to make it walked sted stalked.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's been a year since rebellious executives walked out of advertising agency <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Einstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to start their own, a split that has left two emotionally scarred rivals and courtroom accusations of business sabotage. Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>'s biggest client, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, took its business elsewhere. A legal dispute on the breakup remains unresolved. Two agencies now use the Lord name in their logos. Moreover, Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> and the new agency, Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> & amp; Partners, combined handle only about 60 percent of the business and employ only about two-thirds as many people as <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> did before the breakup. The saga has drawn attention outside the advertising world because it has raised questions about the impact of executive defections in other service industries such as law and accounting. Some ad agency folks took delight in the courage the breakaway executives showed in leaving, citing a desire for autonomy. But at the same time, they sympathized with those left behind. A marketing consultant who advises advertisers about selecting an ad agency said the lingering legal controversy about the breakup may be frightening some potential clients from considering either agency. `` In making a search for a new agency, a company is looking for a long term, stable relationship, and I think both agencies at the moment are viewed as kind of unstable agencies,'' said <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Canter </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Canter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Achenbaum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>, however, insists it has stabilized with billings of $ 50 million and a payroll of 100 people, down from $ 212 million in billings and 320 employees before the breakup. Billings reflect the amount of money advertisers pay for broadcast and published ads. Agencies often get a percentage of billings for their work. Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> said its growth from zero to $ 75 million in billings and 82 employees in its first year makes it one of the fastest growing startups. Of those employed at Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> before the breakup, between 65 and 70 still work there while about 40 are working for Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>. About 210 have gone elsewhere, either because they were laid off or quit. Ad industry analysts say the deep pockets of Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>'s parent, the Britain-based <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, may guarantee its survival <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION>'s chief executive <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> is believed to be committed to maintaining <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> as a second ad network separate from <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION>'s other agency, <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> Co.. Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> also has a powerful partner, the ad agency <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubicam </ORGANIZATION>, which holds a 49 percent stake in the new <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> helped found <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Einstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in 1967. Five years later, <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> and his partners sold the agency to <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. The agency probably is best-known for its <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> work, especially the campaign that used the <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> `` Little Tramp'' character to show how <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s personal computers can bring order to the most chaotic businesses. Along with <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> was purchased as part of <ORGANIZATION> WPP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>'s unsolicited $ 566 million acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> JWT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in July 1987. Lord and other top executives of Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> chafed under <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON>'s rule, and after <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> rejected a buyout proposal, they decided to leave. On March 18, 1988, Lord and another Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> founder, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, joined four other Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> executives in the walkout, leaving only a memo to announce their resignations to the people they left behind. The 63-year-old Lord, whose plans to retire at age 64 were put on hold indefinitely with the new agency startup, concedes it was `` a terrible way to do it'' but said his lawyers advised against telling the staff in person. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wardell </PERSON>, the only member of the seven-person management committee at Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> who did not defect, recalls hearing a roar build outside his office as copies of the memo were dropped outside each door. He promptly assembled a group to keep the agency running and contacted clients about what had occurred. Within three weeks, Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> hired about 40 people, most of them <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> colleagues who wanted to join their old bosses, and signed ex-Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> clients <ORGANIZATION> WNBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION> magazine. <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> sued the defecting managers, accusing them of a conspiracy to sabotage their old agency. The executives denied it. A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state court judge barred Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> from signing Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> clients. But as of this past week the judge had not entered a final ruling and had not dealt with the phase of the case in which damages, if any, will be determined. Within a month of the breakaway, <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Wardell </PERSON> as president of Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> and hired two outsiders to help him run the agency, <PERSON> Agi </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> of N.W. <PERSON> Ayer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Ogilvy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Mather. Ms. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said she was enticed by the challenge of proving wrong `` everybody who thought it was going to fall apart.'' In the next few months, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> II fashions, The Wall Street Journal and a division of <ORGANIZATION> Fuji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Photo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> left <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>. But <ORGANIZATION> Schieffelin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Somerset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> kept its <PERSON> Hennessey </PERSON> cognac there, as did the <ORGANIZATION> Contel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> corporate account. Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON>, meanwhile, got special projects from <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> with the court's consent and added a $ 30 million account from <ORGANIZATION> Saab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scania </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Both agencies were shut out, however, when <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> took its $ 100 million account to two other agencies in September. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> accounted for about half of Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>'s billings. Eight days after that decision, Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> laid off 90 people, trying to cushion the blow by giving fired employees three months severance pay. Another layoff in December and attrition reduced the work force further. Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> shifted sights to new business. It landed a <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> drug account, <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON> home furnishing and <ORGANIZATION> Contel </ORGANIZATION> telephone operations. Travel, publishing, computers, fashion and financial services are areas Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> is pursuing. Lord <PERSON> Einstein </PERSON> reached the breakeven point in January, <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said, and is on the hunt for clients in food, travel, fashion and high technology. <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said his group had no way of knowing when they left that his old agency would lose clients and have to trim the payroll so much. `` What we left there was a healthy agency,'' <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said. He blames the post-breakup problems on <PERSON> Sorrell </PERSON>. But even at that, <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said he tries to keep tabs on what has happened to his former employees and said nearly all have found other ad jobs. So how does he feel about having his name on two agency doors? `` I do n't feel any better about it than <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> does,'' <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said. Lord <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> considered changing its name but decided against it. `` Our victory will be all the sweeter with the same name,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>.
