 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it has frozen talks for a new trade accord with <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> because of what the economic bloc regards as the country's human rights abuses. EEC External Relations Commissioner <PERSON> Frans </PERSON> <PERSON> Andriessen </PERSON> said discussions could not go on unless the government in <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> betters its human rights record. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> has had a trade accord with <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, covering only industrial goods, since 1980. In talks for a new pact, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> sought to broaden the accord by adding cooperative ventures and trade in farm goods.
