<HEAD>Automaker Posts Large Profit Drop, Worker Approve Package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the British luxury car maker, said Thursday its 1988 earnings fell 54 percent because <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> results were hurt by the weak dollar. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> car workers voted to accept the company's latest pay offer, ending a strike threat at the Coventry plant, the company said <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> said 4,497 workers approved the two-year pay package, and 3,527 rejected it. The company offered rises of about 4.7 percent in the first year and 4.4 percent in the second, plus bonuses. The workers had threatened weekly one-day strikes and refusal to work overtime. In its earnings report, <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> said earnings for the year totaled 28.4 million pounds or $ 48.8 million, equivalent to 27 cents a share, vs. 61.3 million pounds or $ 105 million, equivalent to 58 cents a share, in 1987. Sales rose 7.3 percent to 1.075 billion pounds or $ 1.85 billion, compared with 1.002 billion pounds or $ 1.72 billion a year earlier, bolstered by strong sales in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, it said. <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> said the weak dollar reduced last year's earnings after taxes by about $ 77 million. Plans to offset the impact of a weak dollar in 1988 `` were only partially successful,'' the company said. These plans included increased output and sales, competitive pricing, and higher productivity. Last year, while overall sales rose 8 percent to 51,939 units, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales slipped 9 percent to 20,727 units, and Canadian car sales fell 19 percent to 2,154 units, the company said. The company has reduced its dependence on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. Last year, about 45 percent of sales came from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, compared with 65 percent in 1986. In <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, sales rose a strong 31 percent, and sales on the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> continent advanced about 20 percent. `` There will be more satisfactory profits in the near future and we'll be able to tackle challenging exchange rates,'' Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said. `` Faced with the difficult hurdle of exchange rates we are doing a competent job,'' <PERSON> Egan </PERSON> said. `` But we need to become more efficient and make sure we become as cost-effective as out key competitors.'' <ORGANIZATION> Jaguar </ORGANIZATION> did not provide quarterly or half-year results and is not required to under British law.
