 Iranian said Thursday that new oil reserves found in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> will help boost Iranian off-shore oil production to 700,000 barrels a day within four years, state-run <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio reported. A broadcast by state-run <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, quoted Oil Minister <PERSON> Gholamreza </PERSON> <PERSON> Aqazadeh </PERSON> as telling a news conference that seismic testing in Iranian waters off the coasts of <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ras </PERSON> <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Khaimah </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Sharjah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> had located huge reserves of oil and natural gas. At their peak in the 1970s, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s offshore fields had a total capacity of more than 700,000 barrels of oil per day. But many facilities were wrecked during the 8-year Iran-Iraq war with offshore production falling to its current level of 230,000 barrels of oil per day. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has been attempting to rebuild its oil industry since a <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nations-mediated </LOCATION> cease-fire Aug. 20.
