<BYLINE>By DERMOT COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> says federal law should allow economic considerations to be taken into account in deciding whether to protect species like the northern spotted owl. `` I'm told, on the one hand, that I want to protect an endangered species,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post-Intelligencer </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. `` On the other hand, I hear that's going to devastate the entire <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> lumber industry. `` How do we solve that problem? I believe we should be able to take economic considerations into account.'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>'s comments, made in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, came the same day a federal judge refused to delay the sale of timber on as much as 50,000 acres of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> land in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> that is home to the spotted owl. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>'s ruling left forest service plans for protecting the owl in effect pending trial on an effort by environmentalists to preserve even more habitat. Timber companies say the current set-asides are excessive. The forest service is in the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, outside <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>'s control. But <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said he expects to receive recommendations May 1 from the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> on whether to list the owl as endangered. Such a designation, sought by environmentalists to protect forests in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> from logging, could mean the loss of thousand of jobs in the region, timber industry officials have said. `` Maybe we should change the law'' to consider such economic factors, <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said. He added that `` the spotted owl business is probably the prime example.'' Sen. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., responding to a query on Monday, said a legislative proposal along the lines <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> suggested on Wednesday `` would create a national furor'' and `` turn the rest of the country against you. `` I do n't think such an effort -LRB- to change the Endangered Species Act -RRB- would get anywhere in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. Similar views were expressed by Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ore </LOCATION>., whose district leads the nation in the harvest of national forest timber He said log exports rather than environmental laws have caused domestic timber shortages. `` I think there will be a natural, emotional reaction to demand that the spotted owl be exempt from the Endangered Species Act,'' said <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>. `` It's a simple solution _ blame the owl _ but some people are bashing the environment as a smoke screen.'' <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> also rejected a request by the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Contract </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loggers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to stop the forest service from reducing the allowable timber cut. That issue, too, should be resolved at trial or in negotiations, he said. The judge asked all parties to state by March 29 what should be done to resolve the issue. The suit, filed Feb. 8, claimed the agency's owl management plan failed to set aside enough land to protect the bird. `` I'm really delighted with the decision because it buys us time, which I feel is what we need,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jolene </PERSON> <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON>. <PERSON> Unsoeld </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, that small mill owners, labor and environmentalists have indicated a willingness to discuss how to maintain a `` sustainable timber industry, as well as achieve some of the environmental objectives.'' <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> True </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, said environmentalists were reviewing their options. `` The biological evidence is that the owl is at the threshold of extinction and that it can not afford to lose additional habitat,'' he said. The forest service plan, approved in December, called for designation of 374,000 acres of mature and old-growth timber in 13 national forests as habitat for what the agency estimates are 2,000 breeding pairs of spotted owls in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>.
