<HEAD>FCC Abolishes AT&amp;T Long-Distance Rate Regulations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with action; picks up 4th graf pvs, Congressional
concern.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> today abolished regulations by which <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has set long-distance rates for more than two decades. The unanimous commission vote, which came after two years of hearings and filings from consumer groups, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the telephone industry, would replace <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's so-called rate-of-return regulations on July 1 with a formula designed to drive rates down and save consumers an estimated $ 900 million over four years. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> described the commission action as `` a major milestone ... in our approach to, our understanding of the regulatory process.'' He said it was time to move on from the rate-of-return process established for the old Bell System in the 1960s. `` We simply can no longer have a regulatory approach that was crafted in the 1960s, to use that system in the 1990s and beyond. It is simply outdated,'' he said. Commissioner <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said she favored the plan but with some concern, particularly over a provision that would limit how far AT & amp; T could lower its long-distance rates. But she said, `` I do support this grand experiment.'' Commissioner <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Quello </PERSON> also said he had concerns about the floors on <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T rates, and said he hoped they could be lifted quickly in future FCC rulings. But he described rate caps as `` a precedent-setting issue that is really going to benefit the public.'' He said the rate cap plan was `` long overdue.'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said local telephone companies will not come under the rate cap plan at this point, but that they would be included by July 1, 1990. He said the commission was going to accept further public comment on that issue and asked the local companies to submit plans to use rate caps by May 17. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said he thought he had calmed the waters in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> over rate caps, where there has been great concern that residential consumers would not be well-protected, particularly rural telephone users. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> maintains the plan would save consumers $ 900 million by letting <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T establish its interstate prices under a prescribed formula. But the so-called price caps proposal may be derailed in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, where opposition ranges from outright hostility to the view that the plan could be salvaged if it included better safeguards for consumers _ particularly rural telephone users. Congressional concern over rate caps, which <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> first proposed in a speech more than two years ago, caused him to postpone a vote on the plan in January. He tried to assuage congressional concerns about consumers this week in a lengthy response to a set of questions from Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, who chairs the communications subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. On the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> side, <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., and Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., who chairs the telecommunications and finance subcommittee, have been openly critical of <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee member, Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, D-Tenn., introduced legislation earlier this month that would prevent implementation of price caps until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can study the proposal more thoroughly <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said he wanted explicit assurances in the plan that universal telephone service and subsidies for high-cost telephone service in remote areas would be maintained and that long-distance rates would not rise disproportionately in those remote areas. Since the 1960s, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> has been subject to so-called rate-of-return regulation that allows it a certain profit beyond costs. Currently, <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T can earn about 12 percent above its expenses. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s plan would allow <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> to raise its rates 3 percent less than the rate of inflation _ in effect a 3 percent cut _ with an additional 2 percent reduction for residential and small business users. But if <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T could lower its expenses under such a system, its profits would increase. Rates would be set on three categories, or `` baskets'' of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T service: residential and small business; 800 services; and all other business services. Within the residential-small business basket, prices in the individual categories could not increase by more then 5 percent plus the change in inflation rate. Rep. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON>, D-Va., said at a hearing last month on the plan that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> should require <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T to share with customers half of any windfall profits arising from the plan Another subcommittee member, Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, said the revised plan had removed `` floors'' on prices in each of the categories. The plan, as outlined by <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, only would maintain ceilings on how high such prices could go. <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said that without floors <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T possibly could lower prices far enough to drive out competition, but <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said floors could discourage <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T from increasing efficiency to lower prices. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>'s plan would cover all dominant interstate carriers. For <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION> specificially, it would cap prices for a period of four years. The 3 percent reduction would be imposed after adjustments for cost changes outside of <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's control, such as the charges that local phone companies require <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T to pay to connnect with the local phone networks.
