agement would remain. `` The merger will capitalize on the unique strengths of <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspapers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> to build a combined organization with even stronger foundations and better future prospects,'' <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said in a release. Together the companies employ more than 40,000 people, including 5,700 in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. No jobs will be eliminated in the merger, officials said. The merger `` will assure that we can more efficiently pursue further organic growth and acquisitions in both daily newspapers and specialized information and publishing businesses,'' <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> said. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> _ which also has interests in travel and airline businesses _ reported its profit rose 23.8 percent in the year ended Dec. 31. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> reported earnings of $ 229 million for the year on sales of $ 3.74 billion up from a profit of $ 185 million on sales of $ 3.11 billion a year earlier Operating profit was up by 25 percent in the information and publishing segment and 30.4 percent in the leisure travel business. International <PERSON> Thomson </PERSON> completed the sale of its oil and gas interests to <ORGANIZATION> Lasmo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> completed March 6. The company previously announced it had an estimated gain of $ 475 million from the sale.
