<SECOND>PM-Futures Meeting, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0048,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Urges Futures Industry to Face Probe Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Ganis speech and comments by CFTC Chairman
Wendy Gramm; condenses references to rumors of pending indictments; no
pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The futures industry will ultimately be strengthened if its leaders take a direct approach to issues raised by a federal investigation of commodity trading fraud, the head of the industry's largest trade association said today. `` We ca n't make the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> investigation go away; but in the end it will become one of those events in our history which hardens the steel from which we will build the futures industry of the 1990s,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganis </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In his keynote speech at the opening of the group's annual meeting here, <PERSON> Ganis </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> `` is committed to promoting the highest ethical standards within the industry and will support all appropriate actions to protect the interest of the ... customers who rely on these markets. `` Trust is the very cornerstone of our ability to do business,'' <PERSON> Ganis </PERSON> told more than 1,000 brokerage executives, exchange officials and regulators attending the meeting at the posh <ORGANIZATION> Boca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> and Club. The meeting follows by two months the disclosure of an undercover federal probe of suspected fraud at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the world's two largest futures exchanges. No charges have yet been issued in connection with the probe. <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Valukas </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, would not comment on rumors circulating among defense lawyers that six people would soon be charged. The probe is believed to be targeting as many as 100 traders suspected of systematically cheating customers out of millions of dollars while executing their orders on the trading floors of the two <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> exchanges. Futures are contracts to buy and sell commodities and financial instruments at a specified price on a future date. The investigation has focused attention on certain trading practices that can lead to cheating, critics say. Chief among these is dual trading, the long-established practice among floor brokers of trading for their own accounts and their customers' accounts at the same time. <PERSON> Ganis </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a federal regulatory agency, has asked his association to submit its own analysis of dual trading. The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> is seeking similar responses from futures exchanges in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ganis </PERSON>, who heads <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a Chicago-based futures brokerage, also said the federal investigation `` calls into question the adequacy'' of self-regulation of the futures industry. Under the existing self-regulatory system, the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> allows individual exchanges to make and administer their own trading rules. <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, who also spoke at the the meeting this morning, said self-regulation had worked well in the past and called for renewed diligence among futures exchanges and brokerage firms in detecting and punishing wrongdoing. `` I know that you have the incentive to root out fraud and abuse in these markets,'' she said. `` So do we and we will continue to be aggressive in this regard.''
