<HEAD>For release Monday, March 20</HEAD>
<HEAD>Yankees Go For Catfish Au Gratin</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2 of March 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Southern catfish farmers, long unable to penetrate the huge but finicky <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> seafood market, are finally winning over <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> by abandoning the hush puppy approach in favor of lemon-pepper marinade and recipes like catfish and artichoke au gratin. Using a traveling chef to tout nouvelle catfish, the nation's largest processor, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pride </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catfish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indianola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, says it has tripled sales in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> during the last six months `` Down South, it's catfish, hush puppies, cole slaw and french fries,'' Delta Pride President <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinote </PERSON> said at a recent fish-industry trade show in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` But we know that just does n't go up here. What does go, said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Martel </PERSON>, executive chef at <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>'s Restaurant on <LOCATION> Beacon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, is catfish in lemon-caper beurre blanc `` We've had it on the menu for four months,'' Ms. <PERSON> Martel </PERSON> said. `` At first it was n't really accepted, but now it's selling very well.'' Southern farmers, searching for an alternative to depressed row crops like cotton and soybeans, began raising catfish in shallow, fresh water ponds in the early 1970s. Production has grown at a compound rate of more than 30 percent a year, from fewer than 5 million pounds in 1970 to more than 295 million in 1988, <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> figures show. In <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, where 85 percent of the nation's catfish are raised, more than 7,000 people now work in the industry. Retail sales in restaurants and supermarkets, estimated at about $ 10 million in 1970, topped $ 600 million last year. Almost all of those sales, however, were in the South and <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Although New Englanders are the nation's largest per capita consumers of seafood, they have long spurned catfish _ a fact that <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pride </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and other major processors realize they must reverse if they are to continue their rapid growth. `` People up here still think catfish are the ugly old things that <PERSON> Huck </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> pulled off the bottom of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Hinote </PERSON>. `` If we had the image of, say, rainbow trout, we'd be selling billions of pounds, not millions.'' Delta Pride's touring chef, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>, is trying to capture that clean, upscale image with recipes like grilled fillet of catfish with dijon mustard, catfish and artichoke au gratin, and cajun catfish with oysters and andouille sausage. <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION>'s Country Skillet Catfish division, meanwhile, is breaking into the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> market with pre-marinated packs of fish in flavors like cajun, lemon-pepper and mesquite. Two years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pride </ORGANIZATION>, a member-owned cooperative of 188 catfish farmers in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, sold virtually no fish in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Now, it sends two tractor trailers a week to the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area, delivering about $ 60,000 worth of fish at wholesale prices. <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION>'s catfish division, based in <LOCATION> Isola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, declined to provide comparable figures. But its Northeast sales manager, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Farr </PERSON>, said sales in the six-state region have doubled in the past year and are `` going up fast.'' Both companies said they have been helped by publicity about diseased flounder and tainted shellfish pulled from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> and other polluted <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> waters. `` The thing about catfish is, it's raised in well water and fed on pellets of soybean and corn meal that are certified free of toxins,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Catfish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a trade association in <LOCATION> Belzoni </LOCATION>, Miss. `` With all the concern about ocean pollution, the timing for catfish should be perfect.'' For retailers, catfish also has two other advantages _ a steady, year-round supply and constant prices, averaging between $ 4 and $ 5 a pound at retail outlets in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, seafood sales manager for <ORGANIZATION> Stop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a chain of 115 supermarkets in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. When <ORGANIZATION> Stop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Shop first began carrying catfish three years ago, <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> said, `` there was a lot of resistance.'' After heavy advertising, cooking demonstrations and sales promotions, sales picked up _ but they still do n't rival traditional favorites like cod and haddock. `` People like catfish,'' <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> said. `` But this is still good old <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>.'' End adv for Monday, March 20
