<HEAD>Chilean Official Confident Solution Coming on Problems of Fruit Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2, We are, to CORRECT minister's name to include surname.
Inserts grafs 6-8, A joint statement, with statement. Cuts last 5 grafs
pvs to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Chilean foreign minister said today after meeting with Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> that he is confident a solution can be found to the problems arising after a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government warning that citizens should not eat Chilean fruit. `` We are confident that with a joint effort we can have a solution,'' the foreign minister, <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Errazuriz </PERSON> told reporters. He described his meeting with <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> as `` very constructive'' and said, `` We need an urgent solution today.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, responding to Chilean anger over the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government warning, said the action was not taken on political grounds. `` It has been taken strictly as a health and safety measure and we think the foreign minister understands that,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. He added that Chilean officials and those from the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> were discussing possible solutions, but did not describe what options were under consideration. A joint statement issued after the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> meeting said the two sides agreed to work together on an urgent basis to resolve the problem. The Chilean side expressed deep concern over the country's heavy financial losses, noting that 200,000 workers and their families `` face unemployment and even destitution,'' the statement said. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> responded that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry and consumers were being harmed as a consequence of `` the despicable act'' of those responsible for poisoning the fruit. An <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the agency weighed economic as well as health concerns when it decided to warn the public about the possible poisoning of Chilean fruit, an agency spokesman said. Such a decision `` has great economic potential'' to harm the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> country that exported $ 581 million in fruit worldwide last year and hopes to export $ 850 million worth next year, said spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON>. On the other hand, `` you had a probable confirmation'' that cyanide found in two red seedless grapes from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> `` was a tampering, not a hoax.'' `` Then, how far do you go with a decision based on that evidence? That's very tough,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>'s decision was to warn consumers not to eat any Chilean fruit _ which includes virtually all fresh grapes sold in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets at this time of year _ and to urge stores to remove all Chilean fruit from their shelves. Supermarkets reacted quickly, and today produce shelves remain empty of Chilean fruit. Many stores have posted signs assuring customers that the fruit on display did n't come from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. At ports in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, tons of Chilean grapes, pears, raspberries, watermelons and other non-citrus fruit were being held under refrigeration while tests on the produce continued. No further contamination has been found, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have been meeting through the week with representatives of the Chilean government and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fruit importers to develop a plan that would `` do the least economic damage -LRB- to <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> -RRB- and assure the safety of the fruit supply,'' <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s warning to consumers appeared to come some 24 hours after <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors discovered two suspicious-looking red grapes that tests later confirmed to contain traces of cyanide, according to a chronology outlined by <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON>. The chain of events began March 2 when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> received a call from a Spanish-speaking male who threatened to inject cyanide into <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s export fruit. A government source, speaking on the condition of anonymity, has said the caller indicated in his threat that his motive was `` to focus attention on the lower classes of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>.'' The message was passed to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which began detaining ships with Chilean fruit at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> learned of the threat late in the afternoon on Friday, March 3, <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON> said. The following day, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> called in a group of <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials to talk about the situation, said <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON>, who attended the meeting that lasted into the evening. Young decided the detention by the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> should continue through the weekend, while he talked to officials at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION>, the Chilean ambassador and fruit importers `` to try to figure out the magnitude of this and grapple with the decision of what to do,'' <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON> said. But by the end of the weekend, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had concluded the threat was a hoax, he said. `` We felt at that point there was no reason for a full detention but that we would do surveillance,'' <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON> said. `` At that point we were prepared to let the fruit through,'' and issued a release about the hoax. A story about the determination that the call had been a hoax appeared in a <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> newspaper, and on March 8, the caller _ `` we assume it was the same guy,'' the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said _ phoned the embassy again and said the threat was not a hoax. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> heightened its inspections at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports, the spokesman said. Most of the fruit enters through the port at <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, and there the <LOCATION> Almeria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Star </LOCATION> had just arrived with the next major import from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, he said. It was on that ship that inspectors, making a visual inspection last Sunday, found two discolored grapes that had crystalline rings around puncture marks. The grapes were sent to an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> laboratory in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, which made an initial finding that the grapes contained cyanide. They then were sent to another <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> lab in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, which confirmed traces of the poison in the grapes, <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON> said.
