<HEAD>Navy Suspends Contract Bidding by Three Unisys Units</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with company comment, grafs 6-7, bgng ``Peter Hynes,''
sub for pvs graf 6, ``The company's''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday suspended three units of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> from bidding on or receiving federal contracts in the latest action stemming from an investigation of alleged defense contract fraud. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said it was suspending the bidding rights of the Shipboard and <ORGANIZATION> Ground </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, `` to protect the government's interests.'' <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> is a computer giant created by the 1986 merger of <ORGANIZATION> Sperry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. All three units suspended Thursday were once part of <LOCATION> Sperry </LOCATION> According to latest statistics, <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> is the nation's 15th largest defense contractor, having received $ 1.4 billion in work in fiscal 1988. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s suspension, however, applies to any contract with a federal agency and not just military contracts. Pentagon and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials were unable to say immediately how much business the three divisions did with the federal government. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Blue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, said Thursday the three suspended units performed about $ 1.6 billion worth of federal government work last year. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> as a whole is a $ 9.9 billion corporation, he said. He added that the suspensions wo n't affect the company's commercial computer sales to the government or industry because those are handled by other units <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON> added <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> was `` confident that by working with the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to confirm compliance to rules and by making any additional changes if appropriate, the suspension can be removed rapidly.'' The suspension came less than a week after a former <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> vice president and former <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> consultant pleaded guilty in federal court in <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, to trying to bribe former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials. Another <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> executive and a second <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> consultant entered guilty pleas on Jan. 27 to making illegal campaign contributions to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The pleas were part of the federal government's 2 -LCB- - year investigation into the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 150-billion-a-year procurement practices The probe is code-named `` Operation Ill Wind.'' The probe includes allegations that private consultants, hired by defense contractors, bribed <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials to obtain inside information that gave companies an edge in securing contracts. Citing the guilty pleas and a confidential investigative report prepared by <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the suspensions were justified by the `` egregious nature'' of the misconduct. `` The misconduct involves expense account abuses, improper use of consultants for lobbying purposes, improper corporate campaign contributions and bribery of government officials,'' it said. The service, as usual in the case in such disciplinary moves, gave no indication how long the suspensions might last. It did say, however, the management of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> had been vigorous in investigating the allegations and in putting in place a new management program `` to guard against such abuses in the future.'' `` Notwithstanding the actions on the part of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, in light of the number of instances of misconduct at former Sperry divisions; the egregious nature of the misconduct, and the fact that new instances of wrongdoing pertaining to the ongoing ` Ill Wind' investigation continue to surface, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has determined that the former <LOCATION> Sperry </LOCATION> divisions need to be suspended to protect the government's interests,'' the service said `` Evidence that the policies and procedures of <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> are understood and followed by these divisions is necessary, and <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> must perform some additional internal audits across the affected divisions to verify that the types of improper conduct in evidence ... are not pervasive elsewhere within the company,'' it said.
