<HEAD>National Semiconductor Loses $81 Million In Third Quarter From Cont.
Ops.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which has shed one division, agreed to sell another and laid off 2,000 workers to stem losses, announced Thursday it lost $ 81 million from continuing operations in its most recent quarter. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer, said the company's chip business was hurt by a decline in bookings in late 1988 caused by a buildup of customers' inventory, a slowdown in computer sales and seasonal factors. He said he expects improvement in the current quarter following a restructuring of the chip division, cutbacks in the worldwide workforce and reduced spending. The chipmaker's losses for the first nine months of its fiscal year through February 26 reached $ 116.8 million from continuing operations, compared with a $ 34.6 million gain during the same period a year earlier. In the third quarter last year, the company had a gain of $ 13.4 million from continuing operations. Net losses of $ 44.6 million in the quarter and $ 100.3 million in the nine-month period were cushioned by a $ 45.1 million gain from the sale of National's <ORGANIZATION> Datachecker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. That division, though, lost $ 8.8 million in the quarter and $ 28.6 million in the first three quarters Net sales were $ 589 million for the quarter, up from $ 572 million a year earlier. For the first nine months this year, sales were $ 1.8 billion, up from $ 1.6 billion a year earlier. `` The size of the loss does n't shock me, but it was larger than I anticipated,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammons </PERSON>, a computer industry analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tempe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION> `` I do n't know that it's going to hurt them any more on Wall Street. Nobody expected them to do very well this quarter.'' National Semiconductor's chances of recovering much in the fourth quarter are slim, <PERSON> Hammons </PERSON> said, and would depend on how well they market products and use the cash from their recent sales of divisions. `` They have some new products coming out that could help them, but I do n't think they'll be ready to help in this quarter,'' he said. On Feb. 27, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> announced it had agreed to sell its <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> for $ 398 million to <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION>, a unit of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. National Semiconductor expects to close the sale during the current quarter National Advanced Systems is <ORGANIZATION> Hitachi </ORGANIZATION>'s largest distributor of mainframe computers that run the same programs as <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s big mainframes. It has 2,200 employees worldwide, including 1,200 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. After that sale, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> would be pared down to about 35,000 worldwide. The company announced 2,000 layoffs earlier this year.
