<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     03-16 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0204</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market extended its recent rally today, propelled by new evidence of a slackening in economic growth. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> reported that industrial production was unchanged in February from the month before. A separate government report showed a decline of 0.2 percentage points, to 84.3 percent, in capacity utilization of the nation's production facilities Analysts said those figures were read by some traders as evidence of an easing in the strains the economy has been exerting on inflation and interest rates. However, brokers also noted a persistent mood of caution about Friday's impending report on the producer price index for February. A 1 percent increase in the index during January unsettled both the stock and bond markets. A further complication for the immediate market outlook was the `` triple witching hour'' due on Friday, when the last trading occurs in a series of stock-index options and futures. There was talk on the Street that this quarterly phenomenon could produce more volatility than recent similar occasions, since the pace of computer program trading by professionals using these contracts appears to have revived lately.
</TEXT>
