<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mixed in domestic dealings Thursday after rising in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> despite central bank intervention. Gold prices declined. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 388.75 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from Wednesday's late bid of $ 391.10. Traders agreed much of the activity centered around the Japanese yen. Before easing, the dollar had reached a high in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading of about 131.30 yen, a level not seen since last October. But traders said the move reflected more weakness in the yen than strength in the dollar. `` It was sort of a new level, but what happened was that there was selling of the yen, more so than a buying of dollars,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, a vice president at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> branch of <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The dollar put in a more positive performance earlier in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where the currency closed higher across the boards despite intervention to temper its rise. Dealers said the European central banks stepped in and had some success in forcing the dollar lower for awhile, but without added intervention by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, the currency gained on the day. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to close at 130.73 Japanese yen, from 129.88 yen. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar traded higher at 130.85. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to 130.86 yen, from 130.60 yen on Wednesday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.7210 late Thursday, cheaper for buyers than Wednesday's late $ 1.7235. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, one pound cost $ 1.7189, cheaper than $ 1.7200 late Wednesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8689 West German marks, down from 1.8723; 1.6083 Swiss francs, up from 1.6080; 6.3275 French francs, down from 6.3355; 1,371.75 Italian lire, down from 1,373.50, and 1.1953 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1964. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Wednesday's late rates, included: 1.8710 West German marks, up from 1.8670; 1.6075 Swiss francs, up from 1.6038; 6.3235 French francs, up from 6.3200; 2.1085 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1065; 1,371.00 Italian lire, up from 1,369.37, and 1.1965 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1935. Gold prices fell. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery closed at $ 389.80 a troy ounce, down from $ 392.10 on Wednesday. The decline overseas was more pronounced. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, gold traded at a late bid of $ 388.25 a troy ounce, down from $ 392.25. The late bid price in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> was $ 388.60 an ounce, down from $ 393.25. Earlier in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 391.70, down from $ 395.37. Silver prices also weakened. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery settled at $ 6.059 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.091 Wednesday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the metal traded at a late bid of $ 6.04 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.12.
