<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Fares, Bjt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern's Rivals Raising Fares on Competitive Routes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some rivals of strike-torn <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> have raised fares on competitive routes since the 13-day-old walkout began, moves they say stem from higher demand but that one consumer group complains is price gouging. Some competitors said Thursday that their recent fare hikes were unrelated to the Eastern strike, which has grounded most of the airline's flights. The walkout by Machinists has been supported by most of the pilots and flight attendants at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which sought bankruptcy protection from its creditors about a week ago. All the airlines are heading into the peak spring travel period combining Spring Break and the Easter and Passover holidays. Eastern archrival <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> says it has n't raised fares but has tightened fare restrictions as a result of the Eastern debacle. On flights from cities in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> to </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, where it competes with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> has boosted its cancellation penalty on discount fares to 100 percent from 25 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> took the action because the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> strike had led many passengers to book on multiple carriers including <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> _ creating `` no shows'' for those airlines, said <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Pate </PERSON>. In addition, she said, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> has reduced the number of cut-rate fares available on certain flights `` to protect business travelers.'' The spillover from the Eastern walkout meant that discount-fare passengers were displacing full-fare business fliers on <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> flights, Ms. <PERSON> Pate </PERSON> said. Other Eastern competitors _ notably <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ confirmed they recently raised fares on some routes they share with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>. Those moves were called `` opportunistic'' and `` gouging'' by <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, consumer affairs director of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Passengers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said he was skeptical about the insistence by <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> that their fare boosts were unrelated to the strike and were not an attempt to capitalize on Eastern's woes. `` You would hope they would be more sensitive during these unusual circumstances,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. The possible disappearance of Eastern from the skies likely would reduce the number of discounted fares available to passengers, he said. Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which also compete with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> on some routes, said those carriers had not raised fares since the Eastern walkout started March 4. <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> plans to increase its discount fares between <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, starting March 23 in order to bring them closer to <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> fares, which are sharply higher, said <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Blattner </PERSON> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. He called the timing of the move a `` coincidence.'' The round-trip discount fares between <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> will be raised from $ 239 - $ 259 to $ 259 - $ <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION>'s discount <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-Miami </ORGANIZATION> fares, which have n't been increased, range from $ 258 to $ 298. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> said that carrier `` has not raised any fares as a result of the Eastern strike.'' Rather, he said, <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>'s recent increases were an extension of a move begun last November. The latest hikes include a rise in the regular one-way fare between <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, to $ 329 from $ 319, also effective March 23. The <LOCATION> Boston-Tampa </LOCATION> route competes directly with Eastern. <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON> declined to give examples of other new fare increases applied to non-competing routes. `` These people are businessmen and they've seen an opportunity to raise fares,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>, an airline analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Provident </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. Some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and others have argued that a demise of Eastern could seriously reduce competition in the nation's airline industry, whose ranks have been thinned by deregulation. They have warned the reduced competition could lead to higher fares, defeating the intended main purpose of deregulation _ to make it affordable for more Americans to fly.
