<HEAD>Panasonic Consumers to Get Refunds in Price-Fixing Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Panasonic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> will issue refunds to about 687,000 consumers across the country as part of a $ 16 million price-fixing settlement agreed to this week, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said Wednesday. The refunds range from $ 17 to $ 45 for products such as videocassette recorders, cordless telephones, answering machines and stereo equipment marketed under the Panasonic or Technics brand name, <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. The company last year pressured retailers to charge a certain price for some of its most popular products, threatening to cut off their supply if they did n't comply, he said. The settlement worked out by <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>' office and <ORGANIZATION> Panasonic </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, was announced in January but was formally accepted Tuesday by officials in 48 other states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, he said <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, which deals with a separate <ORGANIZATION> Panasonic </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, is not covered by the agreement. Consumers who purchased products between March 1 and August 31, 1988, will be eligible for the refunds, <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Panasonic </ORGANIZATION> agreed not to engage in the alleged activities for five years but did not admit to any wrongdoing.
