<HEAD>Fruit Fallout: Poisoning Menaces $900 Million Import Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile-Fruit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The poisoning of grapes from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> poses a high-profile threat to a business that has grown to $ 900 million a year by using <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hemisphere </ORGANIZATION> farmers to put fruit on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> tables all winter. American importers and Chilean farmers worry that if the cyanide sabotage case is n't solved soon, they could lose the market for the 25 percent of their crop still on trees or aboard U.S.-bound ships. The tampering, which prompted the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to recommend pulling grapes, nectarines, pears and other Chilean winter fruit from market shelves, also might give the business a permanent public relations black eye, one big importer said. `` I think it's a major, major, overreaction ... an entire industry is being destroyed,'' <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> importer <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastes </PERSON> said Tuesday. Eastes, manager for the <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Oppenheimer-California </PERSON> import firm munched a couple of red flame seedless grapes from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> for reporters Tuesday to underscore his anger over the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s no-sell recommendation. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> advised grocers to pull Chilean fruit from the shelves Tuesday after tests in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> found cyanide _ at far below harmful levels _ had apparently been put in two clusters of grapes. Virtually all the so-called summer fruit on American grocery shelves this time of year is from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, whose farmers have learned to exploit the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hemisphere </ORGANIZATION> growing season that is a mirror image of that in the north. From a trickle of grape imports in the 1950's, the business has grown to projected shipments this year with a retail value of $ 900 million, said <PERSON> Caryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> spokeswoman for the industry. In 1979, when imports were starting to gain momentum, the retail value of Chilean grapes and stone fruit was $ 72 million, said Ms. <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>. By 1988, that had climbed to $ 600 million. More than 100 ships full of Chilean fruit are expected to land this year, to be distributed nationwide from the ports of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. The business is organized by the growers, under the banner of the <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Winter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fruit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, and the importers, called the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Produce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. That loose alliance carefully orchestrates the traffic to avoid ruffling the feathers of American farmers.: Grapes, which make up three-quarters of the shipments, are carefully withheld until the last <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> emperor grapes clear the supermarkets, usually sometime in December. Grape shipments are cut off _ earlier than would be decreed by nature _ in late April when the first <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> grapes make their way to market. There is little overlap in growing season for nectarines and other fruit, so there is less potential for conflict with <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> growers, Ms. <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON> said. Importers and growers are anxious for the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to declare the fruit safe, because products already on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shores is will deteriorate beyond salvation in a week or two, Ms. <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON> said. Additionally, an estimated 25 percent of the crop remains on the trees and vines of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s farms, or on ships headed north. Importer Eastes called the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s advice to quit selling Chilean fruit unnecessary and maintained that testing here and new security measures imposed at packing houses in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> adequately protect American consumers. He suggested the agency was trying to burnish an image tarnished in the public mind by the current furor over Alar, a possibly carcinogenic chemical sprayed on a fraction of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> apple crop. Fruits imported from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> include grapes, nectarines, peaches, plums, apricots, pears, <PERSON> Granny </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> apples, cherries, raspberries, blueberries, cantaloupe and honeydew melons.
