<HEAD>Health Plan Files Chapter 11; 1 Million Members Promised Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 9th graf with closing stock price. Picks up 9th
graf pvs, Maxicare, saddled....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Long-struggling <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> filed a federal bankruptcy petition Thursday but promised to keep serving the 1 million Americans covered by its plans in a dozen states. The company, which operates health maintenance organizations under the names <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> HealthCare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> HealthAmerica </ORGANIZATION>, announced it sought protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Code. <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION> promised to keep serving patients, and to continue paying doctors and hospitals. The filing, made in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION>, gives the company a reprieve from creditors and allows it to continue operating under court supervision while seeking to reorganize. Included in the filing are the Los Angeles-based parent company and operations in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Excluded is the company's <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> HMO. <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION>, once the nation's biggest private HMO, has been losing money for two years, and in recent months has cut membership from 2.3 million to 1 million by selling several health plans in 14 states. In announcing the bankruptcy, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratican </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, revealed the company was negotiating sale of its <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> plan, previously said to be part of the solid `` core'' the company intended to retain. <PERSON> Ratican </PERSON> said in a news release the company filed for bankruptcy because it could n't pay its bills. `` These actions enable us to protect our operations while gaining the time to finalize and implement a plan for reorganization,'' <PERSON> Ratican </PERSON> said. `` We acted in the face of increasing demands by creditors and our inability at this time to obtain additional financing.'' <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION>'s stock, which sold for as much as $ 28 a share in the company's boom years a decade ago, closed at 18.75 cents a share Thursday, down 50 cents from Wednesday's close. <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION>, saddled with debt, hit along with the rest of the HMO business with soaring medical costs, and struggling to overcome the effects of an ambitious expansion drive, has logged losses in eight straight quarters. In the first nine months of 1988, the company lost $ 250.5 million. Final 1988 results have n't been reported. Debt as of December included $ 150 million in bank loans and $ 295 million in bonds. <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION>'s health plans are structured in the form of health maintenance organizations, under which customers, generally enrolled through their employers, are entitled to visit designated doctors, generally for a small fee. Doctors are paid on a set monthly budget rather than being reimbursed for specific services. The intent is to cut the overall cost of medical care by encouraging people to get regular checkups and preventive treatment, rather than waiting to seek treatment until a medical crisis strikes. <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION> does n't own hospitals or clinics, as do some HMOs, so its assets consist primarily of a management team and `` good will,'' or its image with customers. Founded in 1973 by the husband-and-wife team of Chairman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON> and President <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION> grew quickly, capitalizing on the industry's belief that HMOs were the wave of the future. Easily raising money through stock sale and loans, the company grew into a national health plan. By the mid-1980s, HMOs were under pressure from rising medical costs. But Maxicare bit off a big chunk of new business in 1986 by buying two ailing competitors, <ORGANIZATION> HealthCare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> HealthAmerica </ORGANIZATION>. The strain of trying to digest the acquisitions was compounded by management's inability to keep costs and the number of doctor visits down, said analyst <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, who follows the company for the L.H. Friend & amp; Co.. Inc. investment firm in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Founder <PERSON> Wasserman </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> were ousted in August 1988 and replaced with <PERSON> Ratican </PERSON>, an outside director with a background in the entertainment business, most recently as president of ailing <ORGANIZATION> De </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laurentiis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which now is in Chapter 11. But he has so far been unable to reverse the slide. <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ratican </PERSON>, by reassuring investors the firm could work its way out of the hole, has done plan members a disservice. `` You've got a situation where a layman has an opportunity to switch plans ... and he reads in the paper ` This company's in good shape,' he continues his enrollment,'' <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> said. The bankruptcy filing comes at a critical time for the company's hopes at resurrection because workers generally are given the opportunity to switch medical plans each June, <PERSON> Reid </PERSON> noted Competing medical plans already have started marketing themselves among employees, and the filing is likely to both distract <ORGANIZATION> Maxicare </ORGANIZATION>'s management from that marketing effort
