<HEAD>Chilean Officials Call for Swift End To Fruit Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new 2nd graf with meetings today; INSERTS 5 grafs after
6th pvs, `The FDA' to add detail on talks with industry on level of inspections
being proposed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-level Chilean delegation called Thursday for `` swift action'' to avoid further economic and social turmoil in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> resulting from the suspension on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales of Chilean fruit over an apparent cyanide poisoning attempt. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were meeting with representatives of the Chilean government and its fruit growers, trying to find a way to release for sale the tons of Chilean fruit detained at American docks without compromising public safety. The Chilean call was disclosed in a joint communique issued after Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> met with the Chilean foreign affairs and agriculture ministers. As Chilean fruit continued to pile up at airports and docks and the livelihoods of hundreds of thousands of Chileans were threatened, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said a small team of <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors will be sent to <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> on Saturday to check security on Chilean fruit. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> meeting came four days after the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> warned Americans to avoid Chilean fruit because traces of cynadide were found in Chilean fruit shipped to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. There was no sign of an imminent end to the crisis despite the high-level attention it was receiving. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said technical meetings were continuing to determine what levels of inspections might be feasible for fruit at American docks. A government source who spoke on the condition of anonymity said there had been discussion of inspections of 8 percent to 10 percent of the fruit on the docks now and in the future, and release the produce if no contamination is found. However, `` it does n't appear to be feasible to do that high a level now.'' For the future, Chilean officials are proposing to inspect visually about 4 percent to 5 percent of their fruit before it is shipped for export, the source said. `` We're getting reasonably close on that -LRB- <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s -RRB- end of things on something that might be acceptable, but the problem of what to do with what's on the ships and in warehouses is still up in the air,'' the source said. The fruit that's been removed from store shelves `` is such a different problem they may just end up with no solution to that except to dump it,'' the source said. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Chilean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> estimates about $ 20 million worth of fruit is detained, under refrigeration, at docks and airports in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, about $ 4 million worth is to arrive in the next few days by ship, and $ 15 million worth is ready to be shipped from <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. Inspectors at ports in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> have examined 6,859 cases of grapes and nearly nearly 4,000 cases of other fruits: honeydew melons, nectarines, apples, raspberries, pears, cantalopes, plums, peaches, seedless watermelon, <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> Canary Melons and blackberries. The joint communique issued at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> stressed the determination of both sides to reach a solution. Chilean Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Errazuriz </PERSON> told reporters after the meeting that he is confident a solution will be found and described the encounter as `` very constructive.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, responding to Chilean anger over a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government warning that citizens not eat Chilean fruit, said the action was taken strictly as a health and safety measure. `` We think the foreign minister understands that,'' he said. In <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Aders </PERSON>, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said the entire food industry will be hurt by the discovery of cyanide in Chilean produce and cancer-causing chemicals in apples. `` The loss will probably be felt throughout the system,'' he said. Chilean produce continues to arrive in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and Aders noted one shipment reached <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Wednesday night. `` The indication is they're not going to let it be sold,'' he said. Aders predicted surveillance of imported fruit will increase, saying, `` I expect that there'll be a lot more activity at the dock, including vigilance at the point of shipment.'' But security will continue to be a problem. `` The whole food system is based on the integrity of the people in it,'' he said. `` Suddenly it's an attractive place for criminals to go to express a grievance.''
