<HEAD>Three Ex-Employees Indicted in Fraud Scheme</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT spelling of ``waver.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three former <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> executives were charged Thursday with conspiring to defraud the federal government, five months after the defense contractor agreed to plead guilty to fraud and pay a $ 115 million fine. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Valukas </PERSON> said the indictments `` demonstrate that the federal government will not waver from employing the resources necessary to protect the integrity of the defense procurement process.'' The indictments are part of an ongoing three-year investigation of the Rockford-based defense contractor. <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> pleaded guilty in October to fraud charges in a four-count criminal information. The $ 115 million fine was the largest fraud settlement in <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> history. The aerospace manufacturer allegedly overbilled the government for aircraft parts; underbid actual costs on other contracts and attempted to recover through overhead accounts set up for other purposes; and submitted claims for such things as babysitting expenses and country club memberships. <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernam </PERSON> said the company was not involved in Thursday's indictments. He declined further comment. The three men were identified as <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, 53, of <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, a former division controller; <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapel </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 46, of <LOCATION> Reston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, a former division pricing manager; and <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamann </PERSON>, 63, of <LOCATION> Rockford </LOCATION>, a former pricing group supervisor. They were charged with one count each of conspiring to defraud and scheming to conceal. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> was charged with two counts of making false statements, and Chapel and <PERSON> Hamann </PERSON> with four counts of the same offense. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> faces a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and $ 1 million in fines; <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hamann </PERSON> face 30-year terms and $ 1.5 million in fines if convicted. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Clabault </PERSON> did not say what role the three allegedly played in the fraud scheme involving <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION>. He declined to say whether the men acted on company orders or have agreed to cooperate. After the settlement was approved last fall, <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> was suspended from bidding on or receiving government contracts until a grand jury concluded its probe. On Jan. 26, <ORGANIZATION> Sundstrand </ORGANIZATION> agreed to repay an additional $ 62.3 million to the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and make cost-saving concessions on future contracts one defense official estimated could be worth another $ 34 million.
